[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ Hello, everyone, and welcome to my course on the Alekhine opening! Popularised by former World Champion Alexander Alekhine, the opening is signified by this move 1...Nf6 as a response to 1. e4. The general idea is a provocation: Black aims to give White more space in the centre to counter it at a later stage.This is the second series I have made on this opening, and I have expanded my knowledge over the past two years to add, exclude and improve upon the repertoire I made for the GingerGM website two years ago.The repertoire I'm about to show you in this course is the one I have personally used and played over the board. And with good results as well! I haven't lost a single game in the last two years.I have to acknowledge that I did choose my moments to play this opening and that I have had to defend lost positions due to mistakes. I usually employ it as a surprise weapon against, on paper, weaker opponents - opponents that I would like to play for a win against. Against stronger opponents, most of the time, I used 'sounder' openings - openings with a better reputation.From the start of this course, we should realise that, objectively, this opening is much worse than many other 1.e4 openings for Black. The engines certainly don't like it. That said, a significant advantage of the Alekhine opening is its surprise factor. Since many other openings are considered better, White players usually have not put too much time into their Alekhine repertoire.The surprise factor also lies in that White has to deal with a very a-typical opening structure that quite often requires precision in the early stages. The advantage is only reached with effort, and that has a lot of value. This makes the Alekhine a very interesting opening, and many top players have used it in their games over the years.You're welcome to leave a comment if I have missed a particular line if you have found a mistake somewhere, or even if you just want to talk about the repertoire. Enjoy the course, and I hope you will like it! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Chessable Note: Three-Tiered Approach to Learning "]
[Result "*"]

{ This course offers students a three-tiered approach to learning. You can naturally progress from one tier to the next depending on your ambition, level, and intended purpose for this opening in your repertoire. Many students may decide the first or first two tiers suffice for their preparation, and will use the rest of the course as a reference source to keep coming back to and consult as their experience with the opening grows.  Tier 1: Includes 40 trainable lines presented in the Quickstarter Guide chapter. This is a quick overview which will give you a good general idea of the repertoire, and allow your to start  trying out the repertoire in some games, but of course will still leave many holes, especially for things that you are likely to face less frequently.  Tier 2: Includes “Important Variations” which have been handpicked by the author as being particularly instructive and/or likely to have high relevance in many of your games. They include all the lines in the Quickstarter Guide, but also a broader coverage of the most important material throughout the chapters, where these lines show with variation titles in bold.   Tier 3: the entire 700+ trainable variations of the course.  If you wish to start out your studying by just focusing on Tiers 1 and 2, the right-hand Settings menu in the course enables you to set your Learn setting from “Everything” to “Important Only”. Which will allow you to study and review only the hand-picked important/bold lines in the course chapters.  Tips:   You can switch the Learn setting from "Important Only" to “Everything” at any point later.  If you choose to focus on Important Variations first, you may find your studying experience smoother if you also select to Study “All Moves” rather than just “Key Moves”.  In order to avoid the important Variations which are included in the Quickstarter Guide from showing up in your reviews twice, once for their Quickstarter variant, and once for their corresponding chapter variant, you can either review lines chapter-by-chapter, or pause the Quickstarter Guide once you have studied the important variations in the main chapters. }
