[Black "Exchange 7.Be3 Bg7 8.Rc1 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Rc1
O-O 9. b3 Bf5
{ Now, we are going to take a look at the more natural way of playing for White, focusing on quick development. }
10. Be2 d5 11. c5 Nc8 12. Nf3 { The second most played move in this position. }
12... Nc6 13. O-O
{ 13.h3  can be answered with  13...Be4  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Ng5  Nxd4  16.Nxe4  a6=  intending ...Nc8-a7. }
13... Bg4
{ This position is very similar to those we'll see inChapter 1.6. The only difference is that White has gained an extra tempo with Rc1. The funny thing is that it doesn't matter so much. Play usually turns out the same as the rook on c1 will very often be put on b1 to support a b4-push. The position is still slightly different, though, so here we'll look at some lines that differ from the ones inChapter 1.6. }
14. Ne5 { Perhaps the best way to play for an advantage. } 14... Bxe2 15. Qxe2
e6
{ It's best not to take on e5:  15...Nxe5?!  only improves White's pawn structure and taking the pawn on e5 gives White a fantastic initiative.  16.dxe5  e6  17.f4⩲  when White has more space and an easy plan to push pawns on the queenside. Notice how  17...d4  isn't possible here as White will just reply with  18.Rfd1  winning the pawn.However, worse is  @@StartFEN@@r1nq1rk1/pp2ppbp/6p1/2PpP3/8/1PN1B3/P3QPPP/2R2RK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Bxe5?  17.Bh6!  Bg7  18.Bxg7  Kxg7  19.Qe5+  f6  20.Qxd5+-  when White has a dominant position without the loss of any material. The engine already considers this position to be winning. }
16. f4 N8e7
{ White has a slight advantage due to their extra space, yet Black has no weaknesses and can try to break either on the queenside with ...b6 or perhaps even in the centre with ...f6 and ...e5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Exchange 7.Be3 Bg7 8.Rc1 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Rc1
O-O 9. b3 Bf5
{ Now, we are going to take a look at the more natural way of playing for White, focusing on quick development. }
10. Be2 d5 11. c5 Nc8 12. Bf3 { The most played move. } 12... e5
{ I had the pleasure of playing this move in a recent blitz game. It leads to a complex position that is very hard to deal with from the White side if you haven't seen it before. I managed to win the game quite convincingly.  12...e6?!  13.g4  Be4  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Bxe4±  was the game Corrales Jimenez,F @@StartBracket@@2559@@EndBracket@@-Zhao,J @@StartBracket@@2610@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2019. }
13. Bxd5
{ White's best move. White attacks b7 with the bishop, creating a threat. }
13... exd4 14. Bxb7
{ White ignores the pawn on d4 and goes for the a8-rook instead. } 14... dxe3
15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Bxa8 Na6
{ Black has more than enough compensation for the @@StartBracket@@full@@EndBracket@@ exchange. If we play actively, then we should be able to win the material back.  16...exf2+?  only helps White, as more than anything, White wants to develop, and this helps with that:  17.Kxf2  and now:A@@EndBracket@@  17...Bd4+  18.Kf1  Bxc5  19.Nge2  Nd7  20.Be4  Be6  21.Nf4+-  and we cannot create threats anymore.B@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@Bnnr2k1/p4pbp/6p1/2P2b2/8/1PN5/P4KPP/2R3NR b - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Nd7  18.Nge2  Nxc5  19.Rcd1!  Nd3+  20.Kg1+-  followed by Be4 and White is a full exchange up. }
17. Nge2
{ According to my database, the only move played in a real game. White develops quickly as they should. }
17... Nxc5
{ 17...Ne7?!  was a serious inaccuracy in the game Sarakauskas,G @@StartBracket@@2433@@EndBracket@@-Navarro Cia,M @@StartBracket@@2256@@EndBracket@@ Daventry 2020.  18.Bf3!  Nxc5  19.O-O  exf2+  Our knight on e7 is unable to move, which, compared to the text, gives us no initiative. White is now more or less a full exchange up.  20.Kh1  Rd2  with at least some kind of initiative, is better than the game, which continued  20...Nd3?  21.Rcd1  g5  compared to the mainline 17...Nxc5, this doesn't make much sense without the other knight on d6.  22.g4  Bg6  23.Be4!+-  and White is already winning. }
18. O-O exf2+ 19. Kh1 { Not allowing us to win back the exchange. } 19... Nd3
20. Rcd1 Nd6
{ The difference with17... Ne7. The knight is well placed here as it prevents White from exchanging our strong light-squared bishop with Be4. }
21. Bf3 g5
{ Creating a square for our bishop on g6. The position is equal. White struggles to untangle himself - if he succeeds, he has to give some material back. You can check some sample lineshere. }
*

