[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Exchange 7.Nf3 Bg7 8.h3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3
{ The line  7.Be3  Bg7  8.Rc1  is the subject of chapters1.1 and1.2.   7.h3  Bg7  8.Nf3  transposes to 7. Nf3. }
7... Bg7 8. h3
{ This move intends to prevent us from pinning the f3-knight with ...Bg4. Despite its good score, in the past two years, this line has been much less popular than the prophylactic @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pp1p/1n1p2p1/8/2PP4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be3  Bg7  8.Rc1  , which we previously discussed.However, I personally consider  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pp1p/1n1p2p1/8/2PP4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nf3  Bg7  8.h3  the most dangerous option. }
8... O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Bf5
{ Developing our bishop to a good square and preparing to play ...d5 on our next move. Now, the most played move is by far  11.Be3  . The percentage is about 70% if you include that the 2nd most played choice is  11.Bg5  h6  and then  12.Be3  . I don't consider developing the bishop to e3 White's best option, though.   Let's take a look at a less frequent yet still very dangerous alternative.  11.Be3  is covered inchapter 4. }
11. d5
{ The best way to play according to my engine, yet only played 16 times according to my database. It is a typical computer line which involves a long-term pawn sacrifice. White gives the c4-pawn up but gets the bishop-pair and long-term compensation in return. }
11... Na5 12. Nd4
{ Any other move loses the pawn for free. With this move, White is threatening to protect the c-pawn with b3. If White succeeds, our knights will be horribly placed on a5 and b6. Therefore, we have to take the c4-pawn.   12.Nd2?  is met by  12...Rc8  . }
12... Naxc4 13. a4
{ A useful inclusion. Without this move, the position is much less dangerous for Black. White gains ideas like Ra3, swinging the rook over to the kingside, and creating an outpost on b5 should Black play  13...a5  .   13.Nxf5  gxf5  14.a4  is slightly inaccurate because here Black has the extra option of  14...Rc8!?  although transposing to the mainline with  14...Na5  or  14...a5  might be better. }
13... Na5
{ A novelty when I first studied this line, but now played twice. I don't have a big preference between  13...Na5  or  13...a5  . I chose  13...Na5  because our piece will get very nice squares after a few moves.   I offer  13...a5  asan alternative, preventing White from playing a5. }
14. Nxf5 gxf5
{ The computer gives a significant advantage for White but looking at this position with human eyes, it's unclear how to proceed here with White. Looking at a few computer lines, White is putting his pieces on better squares and tries to increase the pressure on Black's position slowly. A move to remember for Black is to play a timely ...e5. }
15. Bg5
{ Played in both of the before-mentioned games. White is actively playing against our ...e5-break. Notice how Black's queen doesn't have a good square. }
15... h6
{ 15...Rc8?  was played in the game: Bogner,S  @@StartBracket@@2581@@EndBracket@@-Forster,R @@StartBracket@@2442@@EndBracket@@ Switzerland 2021.  16.Bd3!  Qd7  17.Qh5  e6  18.g4+-  and White blasts through the black kingside with a winning position. }
16. Bh4 Nbc4
{ An improvement I discovered two years ago and hasn't been played yet. The idea is that the a5-knight can have some annoying jumps to b3 in certain lines. Other moves are inferior:   16...Qd7?  17.Bb5!  .   16...Qc7?  17.Rc1  .   16...Nac4?!  17.Qc2  Rc8  18.a5  Nd7  19.Qxf5+-  and White had a winning advantage in the game: Peuraniemi,P @@StartBracket@@2458@@EndBracket@@-Schmidt,L @@StartBracket@@2412@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2020. White doesn't care about the b2-pawn and is targeting our king with a very dangerous attack. }
17. Qc2 { 17.Bd3?  is bad due to  17...Nxb2  . } 17... f4
{ With a little trap in mind, if you will. White could win a piece now by playing  18.b4  , right?   17...Qd7??  blunders a piece. The tactical justification of White's previous move is that b4 is now possible as the knight on c3 is protected.  18.b4+-  . }
18. b4 { This is actually a mistake now. } 18... Ne5 19. bxa5 Ng6
{ The beautiful point. Black wins back the piece as White can't defend against both ...Nxh4 and ...Rc8. Black already has the advantage due to White's weak pawns and the extra pawn. }
