15. Bg5
{ Played in both of the before-mentioned games. White is actively playing against our ...e5-break. Notice how Black's queen doesn't have a good square. }
15... h6
{ 15...Rc8?  was played in the game: Bogner,S  @@StartBracket@@2581@@EndBracket@@-Forster,R @@StartBracket@@2442@@EndBracket@@ Switzerland 2021.  16.Bd3!  Qd7  17.Qh5  e6  18.g4+-  and White blasts through the black kingside with a winning position. }
16. Bh4 Nbc4
{ An improvement I discovered two years ago and hasn't been played yet. The idea is that the a5-knight can have some annoying jumps to b3 in certain lines. Other moves are inferior:   16...Qd7?  17.Bb5!  .   16...Qc7?  17.Rc1  .   16...Nac4?!  17.Qc2  Rc8  18.a5  Nd7  19.Qxf5+-  and White had a winning advantage in the game: Peuraniemi,P @@StartBracket@@2458@@EndBracket@@-Schmidt,L @@StartBracket@@2412@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2020. White doesn't care about the b2-pawn and is targeting our king with a very dangerous attack. }
17. Qc2 { 17.Bd3?  is bad due to  17...Nxb2  . } 17... f4
{ With a little trap in mind, if you will. White could win a piece now by playing  18.b4  , right?   17...Qd7??  blunders a piece. The tactical justification of White's previous move is that b4 is now possible as the knight on c3 is protected.  18.b4+-  . }
18. Rae1 Ne5 19. Qf5 Nb3
{ Another point of @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppb1/1n1p3p/n2P1p2/P6B/2N4P/1P2BPP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Nbc4  . The knight on b3 suddenly is very active.   19...Ng6  20.Bd3  Nb3  transposes. }
20. Bd3
{ The only move to play for an advantage.  20.Bd1  Nd4  21.Qxf4  Ng6  22.Qg4  Nxh4  23.Qxh4  e5!  24.Qxd8  Rfxd8=  is about equal because of the opposite-coloured bishops. Black has no weaknesses and easy play with, for example, ...Rb8-b5 ideas. }
20... Ng6
{ The only move to stop the mating threat on h7.  20...Nxd3?  runs into the nasty in-between move  21.Bxe7!  +-  that wins an exchange for White. }
21. Bxe7 { Making use of the pinned knight on g6. } 21... Nd4
{ The only move. White attacks our queen and we are now attacking White's. If not for this move, we would lose an exchange. }
22. Qxg6
{ 22.Bxd8!?  is decent too. White chooses not to win the pawn but goes for initiative instead. For example, if  22...Nxf5  23.Ba5  Nfe7  24.Bb4  Be5  25.Rd1±  White has the more active pieces and the better pawn structure. Yet, Black is solid, and it's still not easy for White to break through. }
22... fxg6 23. Bxd8 Raxd8
{ Now after  24.Bxg6±  White is a pawn up, but it's not an easy win from here on. Black has active pieces and easy targets, and the opposite-coloured bishops give Black excellent drawing chances. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Exchange without c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. h3
O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Bf5 11. Be3
{ Overwhelmingly the most played move here. It makes a lot of sense to develop the bishop to e3, as it is well positioned. Yet, in this case I would regard it as an inaccuracy because it helps with our ...d5 break. }
11... d5 12. c5
{ Almost always played, but this is not the best move here.  12.b3!  is probably White's best move and transposes to11.b3. }
12... Nc4
{ And now it is clear why the bishop isn't too well placed on e3: it is targeted by our knight on c4. }
13. Bxc4 { White decides to take the strong knight off the board. } 13... dxc4
14. Qa4
{ 14.Re1  Bd3  15.Qa4  transposes, while  15.Ne2?  was played in Sebag,M @@StartBracket@@2510@@EndBracket@@ -Zhukova,N @@StartBracket@@2499@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2010. Black is better after  15...Nb4!∓  . }
14... Bd3
{ Protecting the c4-pawn. Instead, if  14...Nxd4?  15.Nxd4  Bxd4  16.Rfd1  e5  17.Qxc4  Be6  18.Qb4+-  White will win a pawn at the very least due to the pin on the d4-bishop. }
15. Rfd1 { Here Black has an important move to make. } 15... Qe8
{ A wonderful multi-purpose move played already in 2004 by Shabalov. It protects the knight on c6, supports an ...e5-push, makes room for the rook on d8, and sets up potential tricks with the white queen on a4.   15...Nxd4??  doesn't work for Black, unfortunately. It's a trick that many players have fallen for.  16.Nxd4  Bxd4  17.Rxd3!+-  This occurred, for example, in the game: Nepomniachtchi,I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ -Riazantsev,A @@StartBracket@@2638@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020. The idea is that if we take back the rook, White will win the d4-bishop with a dominating position. The two pieces are much better than the rook.   15...Qd7?!  and the knight would be temporarily pinned to the queen on d7.   15...Qc7?  16.Ne1!  and we will lose at least a pawn. }
16. Ne1
{ The most played move. White immediately targets the strong bishop on d3. }
16... Nxd4 { This is only possible thanks to the queen on e8. } 17. Nxd3 Qxa4
18. Nxa4 cxd3 19. Rxd3
{ Here there are multiple ways to make the position equal: } 19... Rfd8
{ 19...Nc2  is the most straightforward way of playing.  20.Rad1  Nxe3  21.Rxe3  e6  22.b4  I find this position a bit scary due to White's queenside potential, yet it should also be OK for Black after  22...b6  . }
20. Rad1 Nc6
{ Exchanging all the rooks and, with that, defusing most of White's initiative. We need to focus our attention on the queenside a bit, as White can advance those pawns quite easily, yet it shouldn't be enough for genuine winning chances. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Exchange - 11.b3 d5! 12.c5 Nc8 13.b4! #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be3
O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O
{ We delve into one of the most basic variations. White has played the most natural moves possible. }
10... Bg4
{ The main reason why the previous chapters are popular from the white side. }
11. b3
{ Defending against our threat of ...Bxf3.  11.h3?  Bxf3  12.gxf3  d5∓  and White's kingside structure is crippled. }
11... d5
{ Again, this is the right move to play. This should be as familiar as your neighbour's face by now. }
12. c5 { 12.cxd5  Nb4  is very pleasant for Black. } 12... Nc8
{ This is a position where white players often go wrong. Black's plan is to play ...e6-...N8e7-...Nf5 @@StartBracket@@perhaps even ...Qf6@@EndBracket@@ and collect the d4-pawn. White's correct plan is to play on the queenside. }
13. b4
{ White's best move. If  13.Rc1?!  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  e6  we can go for our usual plan of ...Ne7-...Nf5.   13.a3?!  is a waste of time - White wants to play b4-b5 as quickly as possible.  13...e6  14.b4  a6  was played in Zhu,J  (2424)  -Nakamura,H  (2749)  chess.com INT 2019. White cannot advance further because of the pressure on the b4-pawn. }
13... a6
{ A very calm and straightforward answer aimed at preventing White's b5.   13...Nxb4?!  only helps White:  14.Rb1  Nc6  15.Rxb7  White has an active and potentially annoying rook on b7. Also, our knight on c6 is undefended and can become a target with Qa4 or Bb5 at certain points. }
14. Rb1
{ 14.a3?!  does not support the a4-b5 plan. We continue with our standard play.  14...Bxf3  15.Bxf3  e6=  . }
14... e6 15. a4
{ Played almost exclusively. If  15.Qd2  Bxf3  16.Bxf3  N8e7⇆  we continue with our usual plan of ...Nf5. }
15... N8e7 16. b5 { Also played almost exclusively. } 16... axb5
{ 16...Na5!?  . } 17. axb5 Na5
{ This position is very much OK for Black. We have ...Nf5 and ...Nc4 as good moves while White struggles to deal with the newly-created threats. Even if White manages, then we still have an OK position. For example: }
18. Ne5
{ As usual,  18.h3?!  helps us.  18...Bxf3  19.Bxf3  Nc4∓  and Black is much more active. We can take on e3 and then increase the pressure with ...Nf5 and ...Bh6, as well as ...Ra3. }
18... Bxe2 19. Nxe2 Bxe5
{ Our king is quite safe - exchanging our dark-squared bishop for the strong knight on e5 shouldn't worry us. }
20. dxe5 Nf5 21. Bd2 Nc4
{ I would feel very comfortable here as Black. Our knights are very well placed and we have a couple of targets to play against. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Exchange without c4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. exd6 cxd6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Bc4
{ A very solid and, in my opinion, underappreciated line. White doesn't play c4 and instead goes for a c3-setup to support the d4-pawn. Play becomes more static instead of the dynamic complications seen in the previous chapters. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ By far, the main move, putting the rook on the semi-open file.  9.h3!?  Nc6  10.Nc3  Na5  11.Re1  transposes toChapter 1.10. }
9... Nc6 10. c3 { Or  10.a4?!  Bg4  11.c3  e5  . } 10... e5
{ The right way to play, in my opinion. White is behind in development, so now is the time to break in the centre. Also note that White isn't able to play Nc3 anymore which would be a great square for the white knight now.   10...Bf5!?  , for example, was played in the game: Grischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2747@@EndBracket@@-Bortnyk,O @@StartBracket@@2579@@EndBracket@@ ICC INT 2016.  11.d5!  Na5  12.Na3Ν  with a similar position to the variationafter 10.d5 - the only difference is that Black has played ...Bf5 and White has played c3. I think c3 is more useful and therefore I'm not recommending 10...Bf5.   10...Na5!?  is also an interesting possibility. }
11. Bg5
{ Developing with tempo as Black can't play ...f6 due to the bishop on b3. }
11... Qc7
{ 11...Bf6?  12.Bxf6  Qxf6  13.Nbd2  intending Ne4 leaves Black with some problems to solve. }
12. Na3 a6 { This prevents White's Nb5 and secures the black queen on c7. } 13.
dxe5 dxe5 14. Be3
{ This position is tricky to play. I messed around with some of the engine suggestions, and White could always create annoying little problems.  14.h3?!  might not be that useful after  14...Bf5  . }
14... Na5
{ The best move as usual, trying to push White's light-squared bishop off the a2-g8 diagonal. It involves sacrificing a pawn, but with that all of Black's problems are solved and Black's play becomes much easier. }
15. Bxb6
{ 15.Bc2?!  leaves White with a passive position once again after  15...Nbc4⩱  . }
15... Qxb6 16. Nxe5 Nxb3 17. Qxb3 Qc7
{ Keeping queens on the board is nice - we can develop our c8-bishop with tempo to e6, preventing White's a3-knight from ever jumping to c4.   However, even exchanging queens gives Black good compensation.  17...Qxb3!?  This ending should be fine as well after  18.axb3  Be6=∞  . }
18. Nf3 Be6 19. Qb4 { 19.Qc2  Rad8=∞  . } 19... a5
{ With good compensation for the pawn. A correspondence game continued: } 20.
Qh4 Bd5 21. Nb5 Qd7 22. a4 Bxf3
{ Disrupting the white king's position is more useful than keeping the bishop pair in this case. }
23. gxf3 Qd2 24. Rab1 Rad8
{ And after  25.Qe4⇆  a draw was agreed in the game Pellegrinon,F @@StartBracket@@2242@@EndBracket@@ -Grego,L @@StartBracket@@2306@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2011. Notice how Black always has active options to create problems for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Exchange without c4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. exd6 cxd6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Bc4
{ A very solid and, in my opinion, underappreciated line. White doesn't play c4 and instead goes for a c3-setup to support the d4-pawn. Play becomes more static instead of the dynamic complications seen in the previous chapters. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ By far, the main move, putting the rook on the semi-open file.  9.h3!?  Nc6  10.Nc3  Na5  11.Re1  transposes toChapter 1.10. }
9... Nc6 10. d5
{ I recommended this move to a student of mine. I tried to refute this idea over the board, yet I didn't manage to succeed. It took me some home analysis to figure out a good way for Black to play against this line. }
10... Na5
{ 10...Ne5?!  11.Nxe5  Bxe5  12.c3±  gives White a comfortable edge because of the space advantage and the weak black pawn on e7. }
11. c3
{ This position has been reached twice in Grandmaster practice. White's strategy is to create a favourable pawn structure where Black has no chance of counterplay. This is nicely illustrated in the two games played after  11...Nxb3  and  11...Re8  . }
11... a6
{ This little waiting move is my recommendation. Instead,  11...Nxb3?!  12.axb3  h6?!  is kind of useless, as White's main idea is Be3-Bd4.  13.Be3  Re8  Kovchan,A @@StartBracket@@2558@@EndBracket@@-Nevednichy,B @@StartBracket@@2185@@EndBracket@@ Iasi 2014. Now, after  14.Bd4±  , Black struggles to get counterplay as the break ...e5/...e6 leaves a weak pawn on d6 after White captures dxe6. Therefore, White has a solid space advantage.   11...Re8  12.h3  Bf5  13.Na3  Rc8  14.Be3  a6  15.Qd2  Nac4  16.Nxc4  Nxc4  17.Bxc4  Rxc4  18.Bd4±  We are following the game: Yu,Y @@StartBracket@@2675@@EndBracket@@-Ma,Q @@StartBracket@@2559@@EndBracket@@ China 2013. Once again, White has a superior pawn structure and Black struggles to find counterplay. }
12. Bg5 { Always a move to consider. } 12... Re8 13. Na3
{ Or  13.Nbd2  Nxb3  14.Qxb3  Nd7!  with potential on the light squares. }
13... Nd7
{ Rerouting the knight to a better square and making room for ...b5. This is one of the main points in this whole variation, and a move to remember. For example: }
14. Nc4 Nxc4 15. Bxc4 b5 16. Bb3 Nb6
{ And Black can start playing on the queenside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Exchange 6th move alternatives"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. d4 d6 5. exd6 cxd6
{ I also cover White's main alternatives  6.d5!?  and the very serious  6.a4!?  . After  6.b3?!  g6  7.Bb2  Bg7  we can play similarly to the Exchange Variation, and White will find the bishop on b2 to be misplaced. }
6. a4
{ A line that hasn't been played much, but I expect it to be played a lot more often after this course has been published. After studying the aggressive 4.a4, which is discussed ina separated chapter,  I realised that here  6.a4  might be a very serious option for White. For the next couple of moves, Black needs to play very precisely in order not to be overrun. }
6... a5
{ If  6...g6?!  7.a5  N6d7  8.Nf3±  , compared to the normal Exchange Variation, we have no counterplay whatsoever to compensate for White's space advantage. }
7. Nc3 g6 8. c5
{ This move signifies the danger of 6.a4. Without it, it is hard to see what the inclusion of  a4  and  ...a5  has given White, other than a weak b4-square for our knight to occupy. For instance,  8.Be3  Bg7  9.Rc1  O-O  10.b3  Nc6!?  and it's not clear what a4 a5 has gotten White. }
8... dxc5 9. Bb5+ { Played 69 out of 70 times. } 9... N6d7
{ 9...Bd7?  10.dxc5  Nc8  11.Qd4  f6  12.Nf3+-  leaves Black with a cramped position.   9...N8d7??  10.dxc5  and we lose our b6-knight. }
10. Bf4 Bg7
{ 10...cxd4?  offers White a tremendous initiative:  11.Qxd4  hitting the h8-rook and White is already close to winning. }
11. Nd5
{ Threatening a double attack on c7. White needs to be fast. If Black consolidates, the initiative will fizzle out. For instance,  11.Nf3?!  O-O  and White still has to prove the compensation. }
11... e5
{ Giving back the pawn temporarily is the best policy.  11...Na6!?  is a decent alternative, but  11...O-O ?  is not good:  12.Bc7!  Qe8  13.Nb6  and we lose material - the rook has to move, and the d7-knight is pinned, so the b8-knight is doomed. }
12. Bxe5 O-O
{ Not  12...Bxe5?  13.dxe5  O-O  14.f4!  and we can't comfortably untangle due to the hole on f6.  14...Nb6  15.Nf6+  Kg7  16.Nf3±  and White has a big advantage. }
13. Bxg7 { 13.Bc7?!Ν  Qg5  leads to some problems for White. } 13... Kxg7 14.
dxc5 Nc6
{ 14...Re8+?!  places the rook in a pin while White wanted to play  15.Ne2  anyway.   14...Nxc5??  15.Qd4+  loses a piece. }
15. Rc1 Nde5 { To make room for the bishop on c8. } 16. Ne2 Be6 17. Ne3 Qxd1+
18. Rxd1 Nd7 19. Rc1 Rac8 { And White will not be able to keep the c5-pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Four Pawns #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ 5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  takes us to theClassic with 6.c4. } 5... g6
{ A line that Magnus Carlsen more or less re-introduced in rapid online games. The idea is to develop our dark-squared bishop to g7, followed by short castle. This line is relatively new; therefore, all the analysis here is fresh, with lots of novelties and new ideas. Because of its freshness and complicated positions, I chose this line as my recommendation. White needs to make some difficult decisions, and even if White manages to get a clear advantage, we can still pose problems. }
6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3
{ Connecting the queen on  d1  with the rook on  a1  . For  7.Nf3?!  seeChapter 2.3. }
7... Be6
{ My recommendation, played by Magnus Carlsen in a Chess24 online rapid game. The idea is to provoke d5 and start undermining White's centre.   7...O-O?!  8.c5!  Very strong and good because White has connected the queen on d1 with the a1-rook, meaning that if we take on c5 and then exchange the queen on d1, White has control over the d-file and pushing the b6-knight even further back comes without a drawback. We want to avoid this.   7...dxe5?!  8.dxe5!  Once again possible due to the queen being protected by the rook.  8...Qxd1+  9.Rxd1±  White has more space and active pieces - a typical position we want to avoid. }
8. d5
{ The move we will cover here. White pushes the e6-bishop back with tempo. For  8.Nf3  seeChapter 2.2. }
8... Bc8
{ Black gave two tempi to provoke White to play d5 and will now start undermining the centre. }
9. Nf3
{ Developing and defending the pawn on e5. One of White's strategies is to keep the black bishop on g7 as restricted as possible. }
9... c6
{ We want to undermine the d5-pawn as soon as possible.   9...O-O  10.Be2  Bg4  would be a bluff, just as9...Bg4. We aren't exactly threatening to win the e5-pawn. We do, but White gets great compensation in return for it:  11.O-O!  Bxf3  12.Rxf3  dxe5  13.f5→  with fantastic compensation for the pawn. }
10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O
{ This is more or less the critical position of the 8.d5 line. I let the computer run for a few hours to see what it would come up with. The computer evaluation is around +1 here for White, which is similar to the best lines for White in all the alternatives that I have shown. }
11... dxe5
{ A novelty. In my view, the move that gives White the most trouble. In the classical spirit of this opening, we are trying to undermine White's centre and see if our pressure can be dealt with. }
12. fxe5 cxd5 13. cxd5
{ 13.Nxd5?  isolates the e5-pawn.  13...Nc6⇆  and White has problems. } 13...
Bg4
{ Compared to9...Bg4, we have traded off the c-pawns, which greatly weakens White's pawn centre. White has two main options here.   Note that defending the e5-pawn with  14.Bd4?  drops the d5-pawn  14...Nxd5  . }
14. e6
{ A very strong thrust, grabbing the initiative. I do think this move is hard to find over the board, and it very often leads to a long-term pawn sacrifice. Black needs to be quite careful for the next moves. }
14... Bxf3
{ Taking the dangerous knight off the board.  14...fxe6?  is a mistake. White will get tremendous pressure here.  15.Ng5!  Aiming for the e6-square and exchanging the bishop. For example:  15...Rxf1+  16.Qxf1  Bxe2  17.Qxe2  exd5  18.Ne6  Qd7  19.Nxg7  Kxg7  20.Bd4+  Kg8  21.Qe5  and Black can resign due to the mating attack. }
15. exf7+ { A useful inclusion for White. } 15... Rxf7 16. Rxf3
{ 16.Bxf3!?  is decent as well.  16...N8d7  and rerouting the knight to solid squares would make it hard for White to break our position. }
16... Rxf3 17. Bxf3 N8d7
{ White has a clear advantage, mainly due to the bishop pair and the slightly safer king. Black is solid, though, and if we can regroup our knights to good squares, then it will be hard for White to find a breakthrough. For example: }
18. Qb3 Ne5 19. Be2 Kh8 20. a4 Rc8
{ A black knight on c4 will be very annoying. White would rather keep their bishop pair. }
*

