[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Four Pawns #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ 5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  takes us to theClassic with 6.c4. } 5... g6
{ A line that Magnus Carlsen more or less re-introduced in rapid online games. The idea is to develop our dark-squared bishop to g7, followed by short castle. This line is relatively new; therefore, all the analysis here is fresh, with lots of novelties and new ideas. Because of its freshness and complicated positions, I chose this line as my recommendation. White needs to make some difficult decisions, and even if White manages to get a clear advantage, we can still pose problems. }
6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3
{ Connecting the queen on  d1  with the rook on  a1  . For  7.Nf3?!  seeChapter 2.3. }
7... Be6
{ My recommendation, played by Magnus Carlsen in a Chess24 online rapid game. The idea is to provoke d5 and start undermining White's centre.   7...O-O?!  8.c5!  Very strong and good because White has connected the queen on d1 with the a1-rook, meaning that if we take on c5 and then exchange the queen on d1, White has control over the d-file and pushing the b6-knight even further back comes without a drawback. We want to avoid this.   7...dxe5?!  8.dxe5!  Once again possible due to the queen being protected by the rook.  8...Qxd1+  9.Rxd1±  White has more space and active pieces - a typical position we want to avoid. }
8. d5
{ The move we will cover here. White pushes the e6-bishop back with tempo. For  8.Nf3  seeChapter 2.2. }
8... Bc8
{ Black gave two tempi to provoke White to play d5 and will now start undermining the centre. }
9. Nf3
{ Developing and defending the pawn on e5. One of White's strategies is to keep the black bishop on g7 as restricted as possible. }
9... c6
{ We want to undermine the d5-pawn as soon as possible.   9...O-O  10.Be2  Bg4  would be a bluff, just as9...Bg4. We aren't exactly threatening to win the e5-pawn. We do, but White gets great compensation in return for it:  11.O-O!  Bxf3  12.Rxf3  dxe5  13.f5→  with fantastic compensation for the pawn. }
10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O
{ This is more or less the critical position of the 8.d5 line. I let the computer run for a few hours to see what it would come up with. The computer evaluation is around +1 here for White, which is similar to the best lines for White in all the alternatives that I have shown. }
11... dxe5
{ A novelty. In my view, the move that gives White the most trouble. In the classical spirit of this opening, we are trying to undermine White's centre and see if our pressure can be dealt with. }
12. fxe5 cxd5 13. cxd5
{ 13.Nxd5?  isolates the e5-pawn.  13...Nc6⇆  and White has problems. } 13...
Bg4
{ Compared to9...Bg4, we have traded off the c-pawns, which greatly weakens White's pawn centre. White has two main options here.   Note that defending the e5-pawn with  14.Bd4?  drops the d5-pawn  14...Nxd5  . }
14. Qd4 { Attacking the bishop. } 14... Bxf3 15. Rxf3 e6
{ Undermining White's centre and preventing the Qh4+Rh3 idea.  15...N8d7?  16.Qh4!!  A wonderful move that overwhelms us on the kingside.  16...Nxe5  17.Rh3  h5  18.Bxh5+-  and White has a crushing mating attack. }
16. dxe6 fxe6 17. Rxf8+ Qxf8 18. Rf1 Qe7
{ The position has cleared somewhat, and now we complete our development. } 19.
Bb5
{ Preventing Black from playing ...Nc6 comfortably. This is the only move to secure an advantage. If White reached this far, he is either very good or has prepared enormously. }
19... N8d7 20. Qd6
{ The point of 19.Bb5. Now Black is forced to exchange queens on d6. } 20...
Qxd6 { We don't really have a choice:  20...Re8?  21.Bxb6+-  drops a piece. }
21. exd6 a6
{ White has a clear advantage. Yet, once again, Black is solid and can still make things very difficult. Play might continue  22.Be2  Bxc3  with ideas like ...Rc8 and ...Na4/...Nc4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Four Pawns #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ 5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  takes us to theClassic with 6.c4. } 5... g6 6. Nc3
Bg7 7. Be3 Be6 8. Nf3
{ What Caruana played against Carlsen in a rapid gameI mention in the Four Pawns section. In my opinion, this is clearly worse than the  8.d5  line covered there. White does not want to overextend the centre and instead tries to play solidly. It is pretty slow, though, and Black should go for quick development and an early break in the centre. }
8... O-O
{ 8...Bxc4??  9.Bxc4  Nxc4  10.Qa4+  and White wins the knight.   8...Nxc4?  9.Bxc4  Bxc4  10.Qa4+  b5  11.Nxb5  Bxb5  12.Qxb5+±  and White is much better, with more space and a clear target on c7 to play against. }
9. b3 dxe5 10. dxe5
{ White still has more space; therefore, trading queens is not a bad idea. The bishop on g7 is also very restricted at the moment. }
10... Nc6
{ Followed by ...f6 in most cases. This position has been reached only 6 times, according to my database  @@StartBracket@@5 wins for Black, one draw@@EndBracket@@. I tried a bunch of moves here to see how to play this position. In many cases, we break with ...f6, causing White many problems as we open up the h8-a1 diagonal for our dark-squared bishop. Let's see some examples:   11.Qe2!?Ν  f6⇆  and you can smell the danger here for White.   11.Bd3Ν  f6  opening up the h8-a1 diagonal with lots of threats.   11.Rc1Ν  f6  opening up the h8-a1 diagonal with lots of threats.   11.Ng5?!  Bf5  and ...f6 will come on the next move with good play.   11.Nd4  Nxd4  12.Qxd4  f6⇆  was played in the game Borisek,A @@StartBracket@@1916@@EndBracket@@-Luzar,E @@StartBracket@@2115@@EndBracket@@ Komenda 2018. Again, opening up the a1-diagonal with lots of threats.   11.Qxd8  Raxd8  12.Nb5  was played in the game Murzin,V  (2513)  -Demidov,M  (2551)  Sochi 2021. White threatens to take the c7-pawn.  12...f6!  We shouldn't care about the pawn, though, and open up the a1-h8 diagonal instead.  13.Nxc7  Bf5  or  13...Bg4  and White has many threats to deal with in the upcoming moves.The game Shurakov,D  (2259)  -Derbenev,A  (2338)  Kirov 2014 went  @@StartFEN@@3r1rk1/ppp1ppbp/1nn1b1p1/4P3/2P2P2/1PN1BN2/P5PP/R3KB1R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.c5?  Nd5∓  and Black was already better. ...f6 is coming. }
11. Ne4
{ Played by Caruana, but this move might be regarded as too slow. In my opinion, White needs to develop quickly in order not to get in trouble. }
11... f6 { Very thematic and in typical Alekhine spirit! } 12. Nc5 Qc8
{ Protecting the bishop on e6 and the pawn on b7. Allowing White to grab the bishop-pair is not bad for us as the queen will be very active on e6. }
13. exf6
{ 13.Be2  fxe5⇆  and Black wins a pawn.   13.Nxe6?!  Qxe6⇆  eyeing the king. }
13... Bxf6 14. Be2 { Offering the a1-rook for the strong Black bishop on f6. }
14... Rd8
{ Carlsen didn't want to take on a1 @@StartBracket@@yet@@EndBracket@@, but did make use of this threat. }
15. Qc1 Bf5 { There is no rush in taking the rook. } 16. O-O Nd7
{ Improving Black's worst piece. } 17. Nd3 Bxa1 { Now is the time to take! }
18. Qxa1 { And here Carlsen missed a chance to get a huge advantage. } 18...
Bxd3
{ The first improvement over Carlsen's wonderful play so far. The game continued  18...Nf6?  19.Nde5!  Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2835@@EndBracket@@ -Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. Suddenly, White has an enormous positional compensation with the strong knight on e5 and the weak dark squares. Carlsen did manage to win in the end. }
19. Bxd3 Nc5
{ This move, with a double attack on the d3-bishop, keeps the initiative. } 20.
Bc2 Nd3
{ And Black has a dominating position. White cannot make use of the weak dark squares, and Black's knight on d3 is currently dominating the white bishop. }
*

