[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. f4
{ White is trying to make use of postponing c4, which offers some extra options in certain situations. I am calling it 'sneaky' because in blitz games, very often, Black pre-moves ...Nd5-b6 in anticipation of  4.c4  or  4.Bc4  .   However,  4.f4  isn't very good in itself. Black has a clear way of dealing with it. }
4... dxe5 5. fxe5 c5
{ Attacking the centre.  5...Bf5  is a good alternative.  6.Nf3  e6  and after  7.c4?  Nb4!  8.Na3  Be7∓  the b4-knight is very strong - at some point, Black can grab the initiative with ...c5. If  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3nPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP3PP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  Bxd3  8.Qxd3  c5!  once again, Black is very comfortable. }
6. c4
{ The most played move here.  6.Bc4?!  is met by  6...cxd4  7.Qxd4  e6  followed by ...Nc6 with quick development. }
6... Nb4
{ 6...Nb6?  7.d5  leads us to a line we don't want to play. See theIntroduction to the Four Pawns Attack. }
7. d5 { The most played move in this position, but it is actually a mistake. }
7... Bf5 8. Na3 e6
{ With the double threat of winning the d5-pawn and playing ...Qh4. For example: }
9. Nf3 exd5 10. cxd5 Qxd5 { And Black is a full pawn up. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The sneaky 4.f4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. f4
{ White is trying to make use of postponing c4, which offers some extra options in certain situations. I am calling it 'sneaky' because in blitz games, very often, Black pre-moves ...Nd5-b6 in anticipation of  4.c4  or  4.Bc4  .   However,  4.f4  isn't very good in itself. Black has a clear way of dealing with it. }
4... dxe5 5. fxe5 c5
{ Attacking the centre.  5...Bf5  is a good alternative.  6.Nf3  e6  and after  7.c4?  Nb4!  8.Na3  Be7∓  the b4-knight is very strong - at some point, Black can grab the initiative with ...c5. If  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3nPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP3PP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  Bxd3  8.Qxd3  c5!  once again, Black is very comfortable. }
6. c4
{ The most played move here.  6.Bc4?!  is met by  6...cxd4  7.Qxd4  e6  followed by ...Nc6 with quick development. }
6... Nb4
{ 6...Nb6?  7.d5  leads us to a line we don't want to play. See theIntroduction to the Four Pawns Attack. }
7. a3 { This pawn sacrifice is the only way to play here. } 7... N4c6 8. d5
Nxe5
{ Black has won a pawn, but White has a good pawn structure in return. We have seen a similar type of pawn structure in the previous chapters. In comparison, we have more development here and enough time to execute a pawn break @@StartBracket@@e.g. with ...e6@@EndBracket@@ to gain some space for our pieces. This position has hardly been played, so here are some sample lines to get a grasp of how to play. }
9. Nc3 g6
{ I wish I could recommend  9...e6?!  , but it offers White a nasty way of developing quickly.  10.Qh5!  Bd6  11.Bg5  Qb6  12.O-O-O⇆  and we are in trouble. }
10. Bf4 Bg7 { Black can start with  10...Nbd7  , which will likely transpose. }
11. Nf3 Nbd7
{ We shouldn't take on f3 unless we have to, as White can castle long immediately after that.  11...Nxf3+?!  12.Qxf3  O-O  13.O-O-O!  is the extra option for White compared to the main line. }
12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Qd2 Bf5
{ Leaving the king on e8 for now and anticipating White's long castle. The bishop is well placed on f5. }
14. Be2 O-O 15. O-O Qb6 { And White doesn't have enough for the pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Early Bc4 lines #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Bc4
{ A line I have faced quite frequently in online chess. I think it's regarded as a surprise weapon from the white perspective @@StartBracket@@I agree@@EndBracket@@, which usually means that, if you know what you are doing, you should be more than fine. }
4... Nb6 5. Bb3 dxe5 6. Qh5
{ This move is the whole point of this line. White wants Black to make a concession with either ...g6 or ...e6 to prevent mate on f7.   If  6.dxe5?!  Qxd1+  7.Kxd1  a5⩱  Black is already better because the white king is stuck in the centre. }
6... e6
{ 6...g6?  7.Qxe5±  is what White is aiming for. We now have to make an awkward move: either  7...f6  or  7...Rg8  , which makes it impossible for us to castle short anymore. }
7. dxe5 a5
{ The move to remember in this line. We want to push the pawn to a4 if we can.   7...Nc6?!  is what I used to play in blitz games, almost automatically. But the thing is that Black's position always feels cramped after this.  8.Nf3  Nd4  to create a square on c6 for our light-squared bishop  9.Nc3!  Ignoring our knight and ensuring that the Black queen stays on d8, and now:A@@EndBracket@@  9...Be7  10.O-O  O-O   @@StartBracket@@  10...Nxb3  is hardly any better.  11.axb3  O-O  12.Rd1  Qe8  13.Be3±  and we still lack room to manoeuvre.@@EndBracket@@  11.Rd1  eyeing the queen.  11...Nxf3+  12.Qxf3  Qe8±  and Black has no room for the pieces.B@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/1n2p3/4P2Q/3n4/1BN2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nxf3+  10.Qxf3  eyeing the b7-pawn so that our light-squared bishop still cannot be developed to c6.  10...Qd4  11.Be3!  Qxe5  12.O-O-O+-  With fantastic compensation for the pawn. The engine already gives this position as winning for White. }
8. a3 a4 { Kicking the bishop back and making room for our rook. } 9. Ba2 Nc6
10. Nf3 { The most played move. } 10... Nd4
{ Yet this is very strong now - White is forced to take since the bishop on b3 is no longer protecting c2. }
11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Qe2 Bd7
{ If  12...Ra5?!  13.f4  our rook is a bit awkward on a5. } 13. O-O Ra5 14. Re1
Bb5
{ The bishop targets the white queen before landing on c6. Black is having all the fun. }
*

