[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The practical 4.c5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5
{ A line I underestimated for quite some time because I usually got very solid positions without really studying it. However, it turns out to be popular, though not quite up there with the Classical Variation, the Exchange Variation or the Four Pawns Attack. I would say it has a solid fourth place in the popularity rankings.I suspect that is because White can very often transpose to the Alapin Variation. If White has an Alapin repertoire against the Sicilian, this line might offer a practical solution - it requires White less study time. What about rankings in terms of danger? Well, compared to the other lines, this is not that dangerous for us. }
4... Nd5 5. Nc3 e6
{ The best approach. We protect our knight and develop.  5...Nxc3?!  6.dxc3!±  offers White a big advantage due to their development.   A decent alternative is  5...c6!?  Just as after 5...e6, we are planning 6...d6 to untangle ourselves. From a logical standpoint, I do think this move is inferior as it doesn't help us to develop like 5...e6 does. I offer it as analternative. }
6. d4
{ By transposition, this could lead to the Alapin Sicilian variation I'll mentionat the start of the chapter. If you have a Sicilian repertoire and play 2...Nf6 versus the Alapin, you don't need to look much further - this is perfectly fine for Black. I will offer an original alternative here if that doesn't fit your repertoire. }
6... Nxc3
{ 6...d6  7.cxd6  cxd6  8.Nf3  is a transposition to the Alapin with Nc3. } 7.
bxc3 b6 { The way to play if we don't want to transpose. } 8. cxb6
{ Played 80% of the time, but Black gets easy play. } 8... axb6 9. Nf3 Be7
{ We develop our kingside before moving our light-squared bishop.  9...Ba3!?Ν  looks like a very pleasant alternative. We have a simple development plan with ...Qe7, ...Bb7 and ...Nc6.   9...Bb7!?  is very calm and collected. We develop and then break with ...d6.  10.Bd3  Be7  11.O-O  O-O  12.Qe2  d6⇆  followed by ...Nbd7. }
10. Bd3 { The ideal place for the bishop. } 10... Ba6
{ Exchanging the strong d3-bishop. } 11. c4
{ Preserving the bishop might be the way to go for White. } 11... d5
{ A good central break. } 12. exd6 cxd6 13. O-O O-O
{ With a roughly equal position. } *

