[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The practical 4.c5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Bc4
{ This move signifies a pawn sacrifice I have often faced in blitz games. The idea is to offer the c5-pawn to speed up development. }
6... Bxc5
{ Much less played than  6...Nxc3  , yet just as good. I deliberated which line to recommend and decided this was the more practical choice, as it is newer and, therefore, less likely for White to know. }
7. Qg4
{ The most played move, yet I think it's not the best. Black has good ways to deal with this. }
7... O-O 8. d4 f5
{ This move makes the 6...Bxc5 line viable. We attack the queen before White can play Bh6, creating a defence against it, as we can now reply with ...Rf7.   Not  8...Be7?  9.Bh6  and we lose the exchange. }
9. Qg3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 d5
{ Another useful intermezzo.  10...Be7?!  would lose a valuable tempo.  11.h4=∞  with typical compensation for the pawn. }
11. Bd3 Be7
{ And I would prefer Black for sure. We are a pawn up while White doesn't have any initiative in return. We can start focusing on the queenside with moves like ...c5-...Nc6 and perhaps even ...Rb8-...b5. }
*

