[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Classic 8.Re1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3
{ This move signifies the Classic Variation in the Alekhine opening. White goes for normal development and tries to support the centre. This is by far the most frequent system. In the past 2 years, I have experimented with the Alekhine in my games and in all of them, literally, this is the move I encountered on the board. }
4... dxe5
{ My recommendation. Let's talk about the alternatives:   The classical mainline and still the most popular choice is  4...Bg4!?  . I have one issue with this move: after  5.exd6  , we transpose to the Exchange Variation, but with ...Bg4 instead of ...g6. Therefore, we are out of our repertoire.   4...c6  has been a big line as well. Yet, once again, if White plays  5.exd6  , we transpose to a line that is not congruent with our repertoire on the Exchange Variation.   I was going to recommend  4...g6!?  but after some days of working on this line, I realised that  5.Bc4  Nb6  6.Bb3  Bg7  7.Qe2  transposes to a popular line in the Modern Defence, commonly reached via the  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  Bg7  3.Nf3  d6  4.Bc4  Nf6  5.Qe2  O-O  6.e5  dxe5  7.dxe5  Nd5  move order.   For this course, I have made an effort to keep the repertoire original - that led me to opt for the  4...dxe5  line. }
5. Nxe5 g6
{ The second most popular move and my recommendation. World Champion Magnus Carlsen has recently played it in rapid online games.  5...c6!?  is the most played move in this position and certainly a viable option as well.  6.Be2  Bf5  7.O-O  Nd7  8.Nf3  e6  9.c4  N5f6  10.Nc3  Bd6  is the main line of this variation. Black has a solid pawn structure and is looking for the right time to break in the centre with either ...e5 or ...c5. This has been extensively analysed by National Master Bryan Tillis in his Chessable course on the Alekhine. }
6. Bc4 c6
{ An important move. In this position, there is a trap we need to avoid.  6...Bg7?  would lose a pawn.  7.Nxf7!  Kxf7  8.Qf3+  and White wins the piece back on d5.  8...Ke6  doesn't help due to  9.Qe4++-  picking up the knight.   6...Be6!?  is an option too, but we will have to play ...c6 later on anyway. I prefer to keep the bishop on c8 for now.  7.O-O  Bg7  8.Re1  O-O  9.Bb3!?  is possible, or  9.Nd2  Nd7  10.Nef3  and here Black's best move is still 10...c6  . }
7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Bb3
{ White is trying to play c4-Nc3 with some space advantage. In the next chapter, we will take a look at alternatives. }
9... Nd7
{ I like this simple developing move better than the alternative.  9...b5?!  is tempting, but it's not good this time - our knight gets stuck on b8.  10.Nc3!  and now after  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3±  Black still has a hard-to-develop knight on b8, and  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p3ppbp/2p3p1/1p1nN3/3P4/1BN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Be6  is met by  11.Qf3!±  putting more pressure on our position.   9...Be6!?  is the most played move and could transpose to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/6p1/3nN3/2BP4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be6  but, as I mentioned before, I have another idea in mind for the bishop. }
10. Nf3
{ White's main idea is to keep as many light pieces on the board as possible to make the best use of his slight space advantage. }
10... b5
{ We are trying to stop White's c4. Our move does involve a pawn sacrifice but, in exchange, Black gets very decent compensation.   The most played move has been  10...N7f6?!  but it doesn't challenge White's pawn advance.  Michael Adams was in trouble in a game against Garry Kasparov because he allowed  11.c4!  Nc7  12.h3!  preventing ...Bg4. White had a clear advantage and went on to win in Kasparov,G @@StartBracket@@2795@@EndBracket@@ -Adams,M @@StartBracket@@2665@@EndBracket@@ Linares 1997.   10...Re8?!  also allows  11.c4±  . }
11. Bxd5 { White chooses to take the pawn. } 11... cxd5 12. Nc3
{ Attacking the pawns on b5 and d5. } 12... a6
{ My own idea, I would rather give the d5-pawn than the b5-pawn as that would open up the diagonal for our light-squared bishop.   12...Nf6  has been played in correspondence games, though, which are hard to ignore, and I have left it as analternative for you to take a look at it if you want. Those games are tough to explain, but I found this move more 'human' and the compensation clearer. }
13. Nxd5 e6
{ The idea is to put a bishop on b7 and play ...e5 if we have the chance. In all cases, Black has very decent compensation for the pawn. For example: }
14. Nb4
{ 14.Ne3  Bb7  15.c3  h5!=∞  A nice move - White's knight is dominated and cannot move from e3.   14.Nc3  Bb7=∞  followed by ...b4 and ...Qc7.   14.Nf4  Bb7  15.c3  e5  16.dxe5  Nxe5  17.Nxe5  Bxe5=∞  with compensation similar to our mainline.   14.Bg5?  doesn't work for White either.  14...f6!  We are attacking two pieces at once now.  15.Nf4  hitting the e6-pawn  15...Nb6  Making sure we win a piece by protecting e6. Otherwise, we would be giving White an exchange back with Nxe6 followed by the capture of our f8-rook.  16.Bh4  g5  We win one of White's light pieces now.  17.Nxe6  Bxe6  18.Rxe6  gxh4  19.Nxh4  f5!∓  White overextended with 14.Bg5 and is now on the defensive with two pawns for a piece. The d4-pawn is weak and our knight has formidable squares on c4 and d5. We are in the driver's seat. }
14... Bb7 { The bishop looks lovely on b7. } 15. c3
{ A bit more accurate than  15.Be3  . } 15... e5
{ Our preferred break, opening up the position for our bishops. } 16. dxe5 Nxe5
17. Nxe5 Bxe5
{ White is a pawn up, but our bishops give us some pleasant long-term compensation. }
18. h3 Qc7 19. Bh6 Rfe8
{ We can put our rooks in the centre and start creating threats with our bishops or on the queenside with ...a5-...b4 or ...a5-...a4. A sample continuation is  20.Qg4  Rad8  21.Rad1  a5  22.Rxd8  Qxd8  23.Rd1  Qc7  24.Nd3  Bf6  White is a bit better but will have a hard time making use of the extra pawn. We have a nice bishop pair and a clear plan against White's queenside pawns. }
*

