{ White is trying to play c4-Nc3 with some space advantage. In the next chapter, we will take a look at alternatives. }
9... Nd7
{ I like this simple developing move better than the alternative.  9...b5?!  is tempting, but it's not good this time - our knight gets stuck on b8.  10.Nc3!  and now after  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3±  Black still has a hard-to-develop knight on b8, and  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p3ppbp/2p3p1/1p1nN3/3P4/1BN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Be6  is met by  11.Qf3!±  putting more pressure on our position.   9...Be6!?  is the most played move and could transpose to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/6p1/3nN3/2BP4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be6  but, as I mentioned before, I have another idea in mind for the bishop. }
10. Nf3
{ White's main idea is to keep as many light pieces on the board as possible to make the best use of his slight space advantage. }
10... b5
{ We are trying to stop White's c4. Our move does involve a pawn sacrifice but, in exchange, Black gets very decent compensation.   The most played move has been  10...N7f6?!  but it doesn't challenge White's pawn advance.  Michael Adams was in trouble in a game against Garry Kasparov because he allowed  11.c4!  Nc7  12.h3!  preventing ...Bg4. White had a clear advantage and went on to win in Kasparov,G @@StartBracket@@2795@@EndBracket@@ -Adams,M @@StartBracket@@2665@@EndBracket@@ Linares 1997.   10...Re8?!  also allows  11.c4±  . }
11. a4
{ White chooses not to take the pawn. With this move, White is trying to undermine the b5-pawn and open up the a-file for the rook.  11.c3  is covered under the order9.c3.   11.c4!?  leaves White with an inferior pawn structure. For example:  11...bxc4  12.Bxc4  N7b6  followed by ...Bg4 and Black has at least equalised. }
11... N7b6 12. a5 Nc4
{ Active play! We are threatening to take the a5-pawn. The fact that White can disrupt our pawn structure by exchanging the knight isn't a big problem. We get the bishop pair and active play in return. }
13. Bxc4 bxc4 14. Qe2 { Developing the queen with an eye on the c4-pawn. }
14... Ba6 15. c3 Qc7 { Followed by ...c5. Black has excellent play. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Classic 8.Re1 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1
O-O
{ Let's take a look at 9th move alternatives for White. Play becomes very similar to9.Bb3 lines but I thought it would be good to take a look at the slight differences. }
9. c3
{ The second most played move besides  9.Bb3  , covered in the previous lines. White is trying to solidify the centre, protecting the d4-pawn, before doing anything else. The c4 push may still be tried at some point, but it has been postponed for now. }
9... Nd7 { Developing and offering a knight trade. } 10. Nxd7
{ With a slight space advantage, it makes sense for White to keep as many pieces on the board as possible. Therefore, trading off minor pieces seems like a step in the wrong direction, and this is true for the text and for the attempts to support the knight.   10.Qe2?!  Nxe5  11.dxe5  Bf5  leaves White with a worsened pawn structure. Next, we'll push our mobile queenside pawns.   10.f4?!  is more weakening than anything. White needs to spend an extra tempo on developing the b1-knight, and the c1-bishop can no longer move to g5. For example:  10...e6  11.Qf3  protecting f4 to enable Nd2 without dropping the pawn. Now  11...c5!?  gives us interesting counterplay in the centre, but I'd go with  12.Nd2  b6  and Black has no problems here. We can easily develop with ...Bb7 and then break in the centre with ...c5. }
10... Qxd7
{ 10...Bxd7  is fine as well, followed by ...Be6-...Qc7, and ...Rad8. } 11. Nd2
b6
{ I like this rule of thumb: when White trades on d7, we play ...b6 instead of ...b5. We put our bishop on b7 and try to play ...c5 when we can. }
12. Ne4
{ Aimed at preventing ...c5. Now we have to take it slow and prepare this break. }
12... h6
{ The c1-bishop only had one square to develop actively. Therefore, we challenge it. }
13. a4 a5 14. Bd2 Bb7
{ 14...Ba6  is decent too. We still lack space, so exchanging a pair of bishops is not a bad idea.  15.Bb3  Rad8  is fine for Black. We'll follow up with ...Qc7 and ...c5. }
15. Qe2 Rad8 16. Rad1 Qc7
{ And we have zero problems. If we want to play ...c5 on the next move, we can. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Classic 7.Qf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. Qf3
{ Since f7 is under attack, we have to go for a different setup than our main lines. However, I consider this move inaccurate - the queen is not necessarily well placed on f3, and we get a free tempo to develop our bishop. }
7... Be6
{ Protecting the f7-pawn. Now play becomes a bit different, although White does have some development issues due to the queen on f3. }
8. Nc3
{ White's idea is to put some pressure on our d5-knight. Fortunately, this isn't so dangerous, and we can leave the knight as it is. }
8... Bg7 9. Nxd5 { This is not a problem. } 9... Bxd5 10. Nxf7
{ This looks scary, but it's actually fine for Black after all the exchanges.  10.Bxd5  Qxd5  11.Qxd5  cxd5=  might already be slightly better for Black. Our bishop is superior. }
10... Bxf3 11. Nxd8 Bxg2 12. Ne6 Bxh1 13. Nxg7+
{ 13.Nc7+??  backfires.  13...Kd7  14.Nxa8  Bd5  and White will be a piece down in a few moves - the knight is trapped and has no way out after ...Na6. }
13... Kd8 14. Ne6+ Kc8 15. Bf4 Nd7
{ And the position is roughly equal once again. White has great compensation for the exchange due to the active bishop pair and our unconnected rooks. Most likely, White will win back the exchange, but that leaves an about equal position. For example: }
16. O-O-O { 16.Nc7??  loses a piece.  16...e5  17.Nxa8  exf4-+  . } 16... Bd5
17. Bxd5 cxd5 18. Rd3
{ Threatening Rc3.  18.Nc7??  e5!  is once again very good for Black. } 18...
Nf6 19. Nc7
{ This is possible now that our ...e5 is no longer supported by the knight. }
19... Kd7 20. Nxa8 Rxa8 { And the position is roughly equal. } *

