6... Nb6 7. Nc3
{ Almost universally played, yet there are some small sidelines.   7.Be2  Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Nc3  c5  will transposehere.   7.Be3  Bg7  8.Nc3  c5  transposeshere. }
7... Bg7
{ Now  8.Nf3?!  would not make sense - White has wasted an extra tempo without developing.  8...Bg4  9.Be3  e6!  followed by ...Nc6 should give White some headaches. After  @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp1ppbp/1n4p1/8/2PP2b1/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9.c5  Nd5  Black is a tempo up compared to the 2...Nf6 Scandinavian line. Seethe informational for comparison.  10.Bc4  e6  and White still has to solve the problem of the d4-pawn. }
8. Be3 { 8.Be2  c5  9.Be3  O-O  transposes to 8.Be3. } 8... c5
{ We want to undermine White's centre as soon as possible.  8...O-O?!  This gives White the option to solve the problem of the d4-pawn.  9.Qb3!  and now many options as possible, such as  9...Be6!?  ,  9...Nc6!?  or  9...c5  10.Rd1  solidifying the d4-pawn.  10...cxd4  11.Bxd4  Qe8  12.c5  and I would not want to play this position. }
9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Be6
{ A move to remember. We are still targeting White's c4-pawn and keeping intact the fragile relationship between the d4-pawn and the knight on e5.   10...cxd4  11.Bxd4  gives White a solid position where Black has a hard time creating counterplay. We want to avoid this structure. For example:  11...Be6  12.b3⩲  and we really can't do much. Our b6-knight is awkward and our pressure on the h8-a1 diagonal neutralised. }
11. dxc5 { Of course, we have to consider this move again. } 11... Bxe5 12.
cxb6 Bxc3
{ We have to take here immediately as White has good options with Qb3 and Qc2 to keep its pawn structure intact:  12...axb6?  13.Qb3!±  . }
13. bxc3 axb6 { This pawn structure is absolutely fine for Black. } 14. Qb3
