Bxd5
{ This solves most of our problems.  11...Bxe5?  12.dxe6±  is not at all favourable for Black. The pawn on e6 gives Black much trouble.   11...Bc8?  12.f4  and White has a dream position with no weaknesses and a lot more space. }
12. Nxg6 { White's best move. } 12... hxg6
{ Keeping our pawn structure intact. } 13. Nxd5 e6
{ Chasing the strong knight away from d5. Trading it only benefits White.  13...Nxd5?!  14.cxd5  b6  15.Qd2  and White has a clear advantage due to the bishop pair, more space and safer king.   13...N6d7!?  is another interesting option and perhaps even the simplest way to play. This move protects the c5-pawn while still preparing ...Nc6.   13...Bxb2!?  is a bit scary - we allow the rook to enter the b-file. Yet, with all the exchanges following, this should still be fine for Black. You can see some sample continuations in thisalternative line. }
