[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Anti-Alekhine #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e5
{ After examining  3.exd5  , we are left with this move. Personally, this is the reason why I prefer to meet  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  with  2...e5  . }
3... d4
{ Basically, the only move that creates an original repertoire for Black.  3...Nfd7  4.f4  most likely transposes to a Steinitz French:  4...e6  5.d4  c5  6.Nf3  Nc6  and we have reached the Steinitz Variation of the French Defence. The usual move order to get this position is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.f4  c5  6.Nf3  Nc6  .   After  3...Ne4?!  4.Nce2!  , White will kick the knight away with d3 and get a big centre. }
4. exf6 { This often steers the game into an endgame. } 4... dxc3 5. fxg7 cxd2+
{ If we recapture on g7, we lose a pawn, so this intermezzo is necessary. } 6.
Bxd2
{ Keeping queens on the board should be beneficial for Black as we have a nice strong bishop on g7 and fast development. }
6... Bxg7 7. c3 { Protecting the b2-pawn. } 7... Nc6 8. Nf3
{ This was played in Nikologorskiy,K @@StartBracket@@2413@@EndBracket@@-Donchenko,A @@StartBracket@@2646@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020. }
8... Qd5
{ A novelty that prevents White's bishop from landing on c4 or b5, which would offer White some good activity. Now the bishop needs to go to the far less active e2-square. }
9. Be2 Be6 10. O-O O-O-O 11. Be3 Qxd1
{ This is about equal and much worse for White than the ending after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1ppPp/8/8/8/8/PPPp1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qxd2  . }
