[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Anti-Alekhine #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e5 d4 4. Nce2
{ A funny line where White does take many risks. Ideally, White wants to play Ng3/Nf4 and Bc4, followed by some smooth development. An excellent strategy for Black is to challenge that setup.   We have just seen  4.exf6  and  4.Nb1?!  Nd5⩱  gives Black an edge @@StartBracket@@the position of the knights speaks for itself@@EndBracket@@.   Finally,  4.Nb5?!  Ng4  5.f4  Nc6  and the white knight is misplaced on b5. We have an easy play with ...e6 and ...a6, while our knight can be re-routed to f5 via h6. }
4... Ng4
{ My recommendation after some consideration. We attack  e5  and force White to react. Notice  4...Nd5  isn't possible as our d4-pawn is attacked.   I'd like to avoid the pawn sacrifice  4...Nfd7  5.e6!  as much as possible. }
5. f4 Nc6
{ This is not so frequent in practice, but it strikes me as the most challenging. We quickly enter novelty-area after this move.  5...h5!?  is the main move and a decent alternative, securing a future outpost on f5 for our knight. I am not recommending this because White has no trouble getting their desired setup:  6.Nf3  Nc6  7.h3  Nh6  8.Ng3  followed by Bc4/Bb5 and White has fewer problems than after 5...Nc6, in my opinion. }
6. h3
{ It's useful for White to kick the knight away as it gives Black fewer options.   6.d3  is already a small victory for us - White did not get to develop the f1-bishop to the desired c4- or b5-square. Here I suggest the nice novelty  6...g5Ν  aiming to disrupt White's pawn chain f4-e5 and to activate our dark-squared bishop. Of course, we can already claim quite an advantage after  7.fxg5?!  Ngxe5!  followed by ...Be6, ...Qd7 and ...O-O-O, with ...h6 in the future. Relatively best is  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/2n5/4P1p1/3p1Pn1/3P4/PPP1N1PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  Ne3  8.Bxe3  dxe3  though White still has problems with their central pawns. }
6... Nh6 7. Nf3 d3
{ A recurring idea. We are disrupting White's development and pawn structure.  7...Nf5?  runs into  8.g4!  and the knight has to retreat back to h6. }
8. cxd3
{ This might be White's best try, not allowing ...Bg4.  8.Ng3  Bg4  9.Be2  e6  with very good compensation for the pawn. We'll complete our development with ...Be7, ...Qd7 and long castle. }
8... Be6
{ With the pawn on d3, our light-squared bishop has an excellent post on d5. }
9. g4 { The only move to lessen the cramp on White's position. } 9... Ng8
{ The knight is returning to its initial square, and that's OK. It wasn't doing much on h6 anymore and is now enabling an ...h5 push. Our knight manoeuvre may look time-consuming, yet I would most certainly prefer Black here. We have easy targets and a nice way of developing. For example: }
10. Nc3 h5 11. g5
{ Opening up the h-file wouldn't be a sensible idea. Even though this gives us the f5-square, it is still the lesser of two evils for White. }
11... Bd5 12. Bg2 e6 13. O-O Nge7
{ With a good position. We can develop and target White's pawn on d3 in the long run. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.1) The Exchange Variation - 7.Be3 Bg7 8.Rc1 part 1"]
[Black "Exchange - 9.b3 Bf5 10.h3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6
{ The move that signifies the Exchange Variation. By exchanging on d6, White keeps the space-advantage with the d4- and c4-pawn. Besides the Classical 4.Nf3 @@StartBracket@@covered in Section 7@@EndBracket@@ this is the most popular way to play at the moment. }
5... cxd6
{ My recommendation. Before making a repertoire on the Alekhine, I had to make a decision about how to take back here. Although in blitz games  5...exd6  scores very well, I find that objectively  5...cxd6  is the more challenging move.   5...exd6  is the main alternative to  5...cxd6  . I am not recommending it here, as I don't like the symmetrical positions that occur. In a sense, we get a worse version of the Petroff variation. Besides that, I also feel that White has more than one option to get a clear and stable advantage after  5...exd6  .   5...cxd6  offers more dynamic and complicated positions. Yet, if you're interested,  5...exd6  was the recommendation of NM Bryan Tillis in his excellent course on the Alekhine here on Chessable.  6.Nc3  Be7  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Nge2  Nc6  9.O-O  Bg4   @@StartBracket@@  9...Bf6  10.b3!±  is an accurate move to protect the c4-pawn from tricks. Notice how the d4-pawn is indirectly protected by a discovery.@@EndBracket@@  10.f3  Bh5  11.b3±  and I think White has a stable space advantage here. This is just one of the lines that I personally didn't like after 5...exd6 for Black.   5...Qxd6?  6.c5!  Qe6+  7.Be2  Nd5  8.Nf3±  and Black's pieces look very clumsy with a big lead in development for White. }
6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Rc1
{ When I was in my teens, this line was regarded as the refutation of 5...cxd6, and it's still the most popular way to play the Exchange Variation. }
8... O-O 9. b3
{ White has played a few prophylactic moves that prevent Black from playing ...Bg4 or ...d5-...Nc4, two very common ideas that you will learn about in other chapters. This forces Black to make an awkward decision. Black ideally wants to play ...Bg4 and exchange the light-squared bishop, but since there is no knight on f3, Black needs to play differently.   For  9.Nf3  seeChapter 1.7. }
9... Bf5
{ This was played in 2007 and 2008 by top GM Hikaru Nakamura. After that, the move gradually became more popular and now has very decent results. It seems that most players don't know how to deal with this move and usually either play  10.Nf3  or  10.Be2  @@StartBracket@@about 90% of the time@@EndBracket@@.However, I don't consider these the most dangerous options for White. In my opinion, the best moves consist of White either kicking the bishop away with  10.g4  , which is counter-intuitive for the prophylactic approach of this opening or to play  10.h3  and wait one more move in order to continue with Nf3 and Be2. In my database these moves have not been played often.The mainline that I have had in my files for two years hasn't been improved upon yet. In this chapter, we will focus on the less-played moves; in the next chapter, we will focus on  10.Nf3  and  10.Be2  .   9...Nc6?!  is the most played move but after  10.d5  Ne5  11.Be2  Black has problems creating counterplay. The score here is overwhelmingly in White's favour.   9...f5?!  This is a move I regarded as Black's best try for a while, but after  10.g3  I'm really not sure what Black has accomplished.   9...d5!?  This move was recently recommended by French GM Christian Bauer in a Chessbase magazine. I knew the move existed, but wasn't as excited about it as Christian, who has given this line a better look than me.  10.c5  e5!  The point. We sacrifice the piece for incredible activity. For example:  11.cxb6  Nc6  and now  12.dxe5?!  d4  wins us back the piece, and  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3pbp/1Pn3p1/3pp3/3P4/1PN1B3/P4PPP/2RQKBNR w K - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nf3  Bg4  and d4 is still under attack. White should go for  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3pbp/1Pn3p1/3pp3/3P4/1PN1B3/P4PPP/2RQKBNR w K - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nge2  exd4  13.Nxd4  Bxd4!  The move to remember.  14.Bxd4  Qh4  hitting the d4-bishop. ...Re8+ aiming at the exposed king, and ...axb6 are in the cards. This is the key position for the 9...d5 sacrifice. At first, my engine likes White, yet soon it turns and assesses this position as only slightly better for White. So, this line is definitely worth a closer look. And, if anything, White will have a hard time finding all the defensive moves. }
10. h3
{ According to my database, this has not been played in the past two years. The idea is to play another prophylactic move in order to finally be able to go Nf3 and Be2 without allowing Black's ...Bg4. Initially, the engine likes this move a lot but slowly turns around later. }
10... d5
{ Breaking in the centre is the way to go.  10...e5!?  is also a move to consider as compared to9...e5 Black now has ...Bf5 and with that, an extra development move. }
11. g4 Bd7 12. cxd5
{ Grabbing the pawn is not dangerous at all. The pawns are isolated and easy targets.  12.c5  Nc8  transposes to the 11.c5 Nc8 12.g4 Bd7 line. }
12... Nxd5
{ Yet this is even more convincing than slowly trying to collect the pawn back. The tactic works. }
13. Nxd5 Bc6 { And Black wins the pawn back with a great position. } 14. Rxc6
Qxd5 { And Black would win the exchange. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.1) The Exchange Variation - 7.Be3 Bg7 8.Rc1 part 1"]
[Black "Exchange - 9.b3 Bf5 10.h3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6
{ The move that signifies the Exchange Variation. By exchanging on d6, White keeps the space-advantage with the d4- and c4-pawn. Besides the Classical 4.Nf3 @@StartBracket@@covered in Section 7@@EndBracket@@ this is the most popular way to play at the moment. }
5... cxd6
{ My recommendation. Before making a repertoire on the Alekhine, I had to make a decision about how to take back here. Although in blitz games  5...exd6  scores very well, I find that objectively  5...cxd6  is the more challenging move.   5...exd6  is the main alternative to  5...cxd6  . I am not recommending it here, as I don't like the symmetrical positions that occur. In a sense, we get a worse version of the Petroff variation. Besides that, I also feel that White has more than one option to get a clear and stable advantage after  5...exd6  .   5...cxd6  offers more dynamic and complicated positions. Yet, if you're interested,  5...exd6  was the recommendation of NM Bryan Tillis in his excellent course on the Alekhine here on Chessable.  6.Nc3  Be7  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Nge2  Nc6  9.O-O  Bg4   @@StartBracket@@  9...Bf6  10.b3!±  is an accurate move to protect the c4-pawn from tricks. Notice how the d4-pawn is indirectly protected by a discovery.@@EndBracket@@  10.f3  Bh5  11.b3±  and I think White has a stable space advantage here. This is just one of the lines that I personally didn't like after 5...exd6 for Black.   5...Qxd6?  6.c5!  Qe6+  7.Be2  Nd5  8.Nf3±  and Black's pieces look very clumsy with a big lead in development for White. }
6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Rc1
{ When I was in my teens, this line was regarded as the refutation of 5...cxd6, and it's still the most popular way to play the Exchange Variation. }
8... O-O 9. b3
{ White has played a few prophylactic moves that prevent Black from playing ...Bg4 or ...d5-...Nc4, two very common ideas that you will learn about in other chapters. This forces Black to make an awkward decision. Black ideally wants to play ...Bg4 and exchange the light-squared bishop, but since there is no knight on f3, Black needs to play differently.   For  9.Nf3  seeChapter 1.7. }
9... Bf5
{ This was played in 2007 and 2008 by top GM Hikaru Nakamura. After that, the move gradually became more popular and now has very decent results. It seems that most players don't know how to deal with this move and usually either play  10.Nf3  or  10.Be2  @@StartBracket@@about 90% of the time@@EndBracket@@.However, I don't consider these the most dangerous options for White. In my opinion, the best moves consist of White either kicking the bishop away with  10.g4  , which is counter-intuitive for the prophylactic approach of this opening or to play  10.h3  and wait one more move in order to continue with Nf3 and Be2. In my database these moves have not been played often.The mainline that I have had in my files for two years hasn't been improved upon yet. In this chapter, we will focus on the less-played moves; in the next chapter, we will focus on  10.Nf3  and  10.Be2  .   9...Nc6?!  is the most played move but after  10.d5  Ne5  11.Be2  Black has problems creating counterplay. The score here is overwhelmingly in White's favour.   9...f5?!  This is a move I regarded as Black's best try for a while, but after  10.g3  I'm really not sure what Black has accomplished.   9...d5!?  This move was recently recommended by French GM Christian Bauer in a Chessbase magazine. I knew the move existed, but wasn't as excited about it as Christian, who has given this line a better look than me.  10.c5  e5!  The point. We sacrifice the piece for incredible activity. For example:  11.cxb6  Nc6  and now  12.dxe5?!  d4  wins us back the piece, and  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3pbp/1Pn3p1/3pp3/3P4/1PN1B3/P4PPP/2RQKBNR w K - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nf3  Bg4  and d4 is still under attack. White should go for  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3pbp/1Pn3p1/3pp3/3P4/1PN1B3/P4PPP/2RQKBNR w K - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nge2  exd4  13.Nxd4  Bxd4!  The move to remember.  14.Bxd4  Qh4  hitting the d4-bishop. ...Re8+ aiming at the exposed king, and ...axb6 are in the cards. This is the key position for the 9...d5 sacrifice. At first, my engine likes White, yet soon it turns and assesses this position as only slightly better for White. So, this line is definitely worth a closer look. And, if anything, White will have a hard time finding all the defensive moves. }
10. h3
{ According to my database, this has not been played in the past two years. The idea is to play another prophylactic move in order to finally be able to go Nf3 and Be2 without allowing Black's ...Bg4. Initially, the engine likes this move a lot but slowly turns around later. }
10... d5
{ Breaking in the centre is the way to go.  10...e5!?  is also a move to consider as compared to9...e5 Black now has ...Bf5 and with that, an extra development move. }
11. c5 { White kicks our knight back with tempo, but that is okay. } 11... Nc8
{ The knight can be re-routed to e7 at some point. The knight looks awkward for the moment, but certainly has a future. }
12. Nf3 Nc6 13. Be2 Be4
{ Quite a nice move. White cannot take the bishop as it will leave d4 vulnerable and that means that we can exchange the f3-knight with our normal way of counterplay. }
*

