{ Undermining the centre. We want to open the e-file for our rook, amongst other things. If  10...e5?!  White doesn't need to take en passant now. Therefore, this move is not opening up the position, which I would really like to do as the White king is still in the centre. }
11. g4
{ Trapping the bishop on f5. Yet, we have a way to deal with this. It leads to a forcing sequence. }
11... Bxc3+ { Creating a square for our bishop on e4. } 12. Rxc3 Be4 13. f3
{ Our bishop is trapped again. } 13... Bxd5
{ Sacrificing the bishop for two pawns. } 14. Rd3
{ This leaves our bishop alive. } 14... Bc6 15. Rxd6 Qh4+ 16. Bf2 Qe7
{ And even though White has the bishop-pair, it is more important that Black is much faster with development. }
