{ A solid approach that could easily be underestimated. With this move White solves a lot of tactical problems. }
10... Bxd3 11. Qxd3 d5 { As usual, we want to undermine the centre. } 12. c5
Nc8 13. Nf3 Nc6
{ 13...b6?  doesn't do much, unfortunately. Taking on c5 is not a good idea at the moment, as White can start pushing passed pawns on the queenside.  14.O-O  bxc5?!  15.dxc5±  . }
14. O-O e6 { Making room for our knight to jump to f5. } 15. Rb1
{ With the same idea as  15.a3  , namely to play b4. This might even be better as the rook will be put on the soon-to-be-opened b-file. }
15... b6
{ 15...N8e7?!  16.b4  a6  is OK for Black, yet the rook on b1 enables White to push even more on the queenside:  17.a4!  Followed by b5 with problems for Black. }
16. b4 bxc5 17. bxc5 N8e7 18. Bf4 Nf5
{ Now after  19.Ne2  White is a bit better, with more space and harmonious pieces. Yet Black's position is solid, and we can start thinking about pushing in the centre with ...e5 at some point. }
*

