1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Rc1
O-O 9. b3 Bf5
{ In this second chapter, we are going to take a look at the more natural way of playing for White, focusing on quick development. }
10. Nf3 { White can also start with this move, of course. } 10... d5
{ As usual, we break in the centre.   If  10...Bg4!?  had transposed to10.Be2, then I would have been content recommending this move, yet White has extra options with a quick  11.h3!?  Bxf3  12.Qxf3  Nc6  13.d5  Nd4  14.Qd1⩲  and White has a very comfortable position with the bishop pair and more space. We also still have to solve the problem of our d4-knight.   @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp2ppbp/1n1p2p1/8/2PP2b1/1PN1BN2/P4PPP/2RQKB1R w K - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Be2  d5  12.h3!  is also quite strong for White.  12...Bxf3  13.Bxf3  e6   @@StartBracket@@  13...dxc4?  14.Bxb7  loses us the exchange.@@EndBracket@@  14.cxd5!  exd5  15.O-O  Nc6  16.g3±  It seems like Black is doing fine, but White actually has a pretty significant advantage here. }
11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Bc4 Qd6
{ And Black has no problems. The position is about equal. } *

