[Black "Exchange - 10.Be2 d5 11.c5 Nc8 12.g4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Rc1
O-O 9. b3 Bf5
{ In this second chapter, we are going to take a look at the more natural way of playing for White, focusing on quick development. }
10. Be2 d5 11. c5 Nc8 12. g4
{ Only played a handful of times, yet it is always an interesting idea for White to kick our bishop back from its good post on f5. }
12... Bd7
{ Now  13.Nxd5??  loses a piece again to  13...Bc6!  .   For  13.f4!?  Nc6  14.h4  seethe 13.h4 line. }
13. h4 { Very aggressive play by White on the kingside. } 13... Nc6
{ 13...e5!?  14.dxe5  d4?!  was tried by the young player Daniil Yuffa, who we can also consider an Alekhine expert. This pawn sacrifice is not good, although it worked out in the game:  15.Bxd4  Nc6  16.f4!  and Black should not have enough compensation for the two pawns. After  16.Be3?!  Nxe5∞  Black had counterplay again in the game: Corrales Jimenez,F  @@StartBracket@@2532@@EndBracket@@-Yuffa,D @@StartBracket@@2594@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020@@EndBracket@@. }
14. f4 b6
{ If we can't break in the centre, then ...b6 is always a move to consider. }
15. Na4
{ To protect c5, making sure that exchanging there is inconvenient as White's knight will be quite powerful on that square.   15.Nxd5?!  Be6  is fine for Black.   15.cxb6?!  axb6⩱  was played in the game: Baklan, V  (2605)  -Manea,A  (2347)  Sovata 2018. Black suddenly has a lot of play, especially thanks to the d6-square being available for the c8-knight. }
15... bxc5 { Allowing the knight on c5 is worth it, though. } 16. Nxc5 Nd6
{ And we have good counterplay. White's king is exposed, and we have chances to strike in the centre with a move like ...Ne4. }
