1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Rc1
O-O 9. b3 Bf5
{ In this second chapter, we are going to take a look at the more natural way of playing for White, focusing on quick development. }
10. Be2 d5 11. c5 Nc8 12. Bf3 { The most played move. } 12... e5
{ I had the pleasure of playing this move in a recent blitz game. It leads to a complex position that is very hard to deal with from the White side if you haven't seen it before. I managed to win the game quite convincingly.  12...e6?!  13.g4  Be4  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Bxe4±  was the game Corrales Jimenez,F @@StartBracket@@2559@@EndBracket@@-Zhao,J @@StartBracket@@2610@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2019. }
13. Bxd5
{ White's best move. White attacks b7 with the bishop, creating a threat. }
13... exd4 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 Nc6 { Developing with tempo. } 16. Qf4
{ The queen is well placed here as it prevents Black from playing ...Nb4, attacking both the bishop on d5 and the d3-square. }
16... Ne5 { Yet this is a good way to continue the initiative. } 17. Bc4
{ 17.Qxe5?  Re8∓  and White loses the queen. } 17... Nxc4 18. bxc4
{ 18.Qxc4!?  Bd3  19.Qf4  Ne7  20.Nge2  Nd5!  and White still has trouble castling. }
18... Bd3 { Undermining the c4-pawn and making it hard for White to castle. }
19. Nge2 { If  19.Rd1  we have  19...Qe7+  . } 19... Bxe2 20. Nxe2 Re8
{ Black clearly has enough compensation for the pawn. The c-pawns are very weak and White still needs to find a way to castle/activate the h1-rook. }
21. Qd2 { This was played in a recent game. } 21... Qe7
{ White still cannot castle. } 22. Rc2 Qxc5
{ We have been following the game: Brewer,C @@StartBracket@@2140@@EndBracket@@ -Cornette,M @@StartBracket@@2612@@EndBracket@@ England 2018. Black got the pawn back with a dominant position. }
