[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.3) The Exchange Variation - 7.Nf3 Bg7 8.h3 part 1"]
[Black "Exchange - 9.Be2 Nc6 10.O-O Bf5 11.Bf4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3
{ The line  7.Be3  Bg7  8.Rc1  was the subject of chapters1.1 and1.2.   7.h3  Bg7  8.Nf3  transposes to 7. Nf3. }
7... Bg7 8. h3
{ This move intends to prevent us from pinning the f3-knight with ...Bg4. Despite its good score, in the past two years, this line has been much less popular than the prophylactic @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pp1p/1n1p2p1/8/2PP4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be3  Bg7  8.Rc1  , which we discussed in our two previous chapters.However, I personally consider  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pp1p/1n1p2p1/8/2PP4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nf3  Bg7  8.h3  the most dangerous option. }
8... O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Bf5
{ Developing our bishop to a good square and preparing to play ...d5 on our next move. Now, the most played move is by far  11.Be3  . The percentage is about 70% if you include that the 2nd most played choice is  11.Bg5  h6  and then  12.Be3  . I don't consider developing the bishop to e3 White's best option, though.   In this chapter, we will take a look at less frequent yet still very dangerous alternatives, while inthe next chapter,  we will take a look at  11.Be3  . }
11. Bf4 { Another computer suggestion. } 11... e5
{ This makes sense - we are attacking the bishop on f4. } 12. Bg5
{ 12.Be3?!  is met by  12...d5  . } 12... Qd7 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. c5
{ A move White should play if he wants to play for an advantage. } 14... Qxd1
{ 14...h6!?  is perhaps a useful in-between move as White certainly doesn't want to trade the dark-squared bishop for our knight. }
15. Rfxd1 Nd7
{ This line is very comparable to @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/1nnp2p1/5b2/2PP4/2N2N1P/PP2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 5 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Re1  Rc8  12.Bf1  e5  13.Bg5  coveredhere. The biggest difference is that Black has no rook on c8 and White hasn't played Bf1 and Re1. The positions are very similar, as is the evaluation. }
16. Be3
{ White needs to protect the c5-pawn.  16.g4  Be6  is not a problem for Black. }
16... Nd4
{ Disconnecting the e3-bishop from the pawn on c5. If we don't play this, we will get quite a cramped position. Therefore, I prefer the following exchanges.   After  16...h6?!  17.Rac1  Rfd8  18.Nb5±  I would very much prefer White as the knight can jump to strong squares on d6 and c7. }
17. Nxd4 exd4 18. Bxd4 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Nxc5
{ White is slightly better, but the draw margin is very high in this symmetrical position. We will activate our rooks and ensure that White can't win any of our pawns. }
