{ My recommendation, although it's not the only interesting move here. Also possible is  13...Rc8!?  14.Rc1  Na5  pushing the c4-pawn forward.  15.c5  Nbc4  Threatening to exchange the white bishop on e3.  16.Bf4!  b6  The position is still complicated, and White still needs to find a good move or two in order to claim an advantage.Black was doing very well after  @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/pp2ppbp/6p1/n1P2b2/2nP4/2N1BN1P/P3BPP1/2RQ1RK1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Qa4?  Bd7!  17.Qc2  Nxe3  18.fxe3  in the game: Iliaguev,D @@StartBracket@@1813@@EndBracket@@-Klein,D @@StartBracket@@2505@@EndBracket@@ Jerusalem 2015 and after  18...Bh6!  19.Qd2  b6⩱  I would very much prefer Black due to the bishop pair and active possibilities.   13...Na5!?  14.c5  Nbc4  15.Bf4  b6  is similar to the 13...Rc8  line I have just shown. }
14. d5 Na5 15. c5 e4
{ An important move. White attacked our knight on b6, and now we are counterattacking the white knights on c3 and f3. With this, we force exchanges that lead to a different type of position.   If  15...Nbc4?!  16.Bxc4  Nxc4  17.Qe2  Nxe3  18.Qxe3±  White has two very strong pawns on d5 and c5 which outshine our bishop pair by quite a margin. }
