{ A complicated position, but one where I feel Black has enough counterplay.  17.Bb5!?  h6  18.Be3  Rfd8⇆  isn't much of a problem for Black.   One correspondence game went as follows:  17.Nd5  e4  18.Bb5!  A fantastic computer move.   @@StartBracket@@  18.Nd2?!  Nxc5  19.Be7  Nd3!  20.Bxd3  exd3  21.Bxf8  Kxf8=∞  and Black has great compensation for the exchange.  @@EndBracket@@  18...exf3!?  The start of a simplifying sequence that leads to a roughly equal ending.  19.Bxc6  Rxc6  20.Ne7+  Kh8  21.Nxc6   @@StartBracket@@Black has no problems after  21.Nxf5  Nxc5=  .@@EndBracket@@  21...bxc6  22.g4  Be6  23.Rxe6  fxe6  24.Rxd7  Bxb2  25.Rxa7  Bd4=  Material is equal. White's a-pawn scares me a little, yet Black should objectively be fine. The f2-pawn is quite a liability for White. }
