[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. h3
O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Bf5 11. Be3
{ Overwhelmingly the most played move here. It makes a lot of sense to develop the bishop to e3, as it is well positioned. Yet, in this case I would regard it as an inaccuracy because it helps with our ...d5 break. }
11... d5 12. c5
{ Almost always played, but this is not the best move here.  12.b3!  is probably White's best move and transposes to11.b3 in the previous chapter. }
12... Nc4
{ And now it is clear why the bishop isn't too well placed on e3: it is targeted by our knight on c4. }
13. Bxc4 { White decides to take the strong knight off the board. } 13... dxc4
14. d5 { It's a bit scary to push the pawn forward. } 14... Nb4
{ With a bunch of threats. } 15. Bd4 Bd3
{ 15...f6!?  Illogical as this might look, it might actually be worth blocking our bishop temporarily in order to target the d5-pawn. For example:  16.Qa4  Nxd5  17.Qxc4  Be6  18.Rad1  Bf7=∞  and White has the more active pieces, yet Black is solid and has the bishop pair. Notice also how the f6-pawn makes sure the f3-knight can't jump forward. }
16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Re1 Nc2
{ Black wins the exchange, although White has excellent compensation thanks to the strong pawn duo.   17...Nxd5  is the safe option, just taking the pawn off the board.  18. Nxd5 Qxd5 19. Rxe7 Qxc5 20. Rxb7 Rfe8=  , and Black is certainly not worse. }
18. Ne5 { White needs to play actively and targets the d3-bishop. } 18... Nxa1
{ Taking this rook makes sure that White's queen stays off-side for one move.   18...Nxe1  19.Qxe1=∞  0-1 @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Boricsev, O @@StartBracket@@2375@@EndBracket@@-Paal, A @@StartBracket@@2125@@EndBracket@@ Gyongyos 1998 }
19. Qxa1 f6 { There isn't much else to do. } 20. Nxd3 cxd3 21. Qd1 Qa5
{ If we do nothing, we will get in trouble:  21...Re8?  22.Qxd3  and White has a dominant position with more than enough compensation for the exchange. }
22. Rxe7+ Rf7 23. Rxf7+ Kxf7
{ And White needs to be very careful. Black can put a rook on the open file, and the pawns on c5 and d5 are still targeted and not easy to protect. }
*

