{ 14.Re1  Bd3  15.Qa4  transposes, while  15.Ne2?  was played in Sebag,M @@StartBracket@@2510@@EndBracket@@ -Zhukova,N @@StartBracket@@2499@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2010. Black is better after  15...Nb4!∓  . }
14... Bd3
{ Protecting the c4-pawn. Instead, if  14...Nxd4?  15.Nxd4  Bxd4  16.Rfd1  e5  17.Qxc4  Be6  18.Qb4+-  White will win a pawn at the very least due to the pin on the d4-bishop. }
15. Rfd1 { Here Black has an important move to make. } 15... Qe8
{ A wonderful multi-purpose move played already in 2004 by Shabalov. It protects the knight on c6, supports an ...e5-push, makes room for the rook on d8, and sets up potential tricks with the white queen on a4.   15...Nxd4??  doesn't work for Black, unfortunately. It's a trick that many players have fallen for.  16.Nxd4  Bxd4  17.Rxd3!+-  This occurred, for example, in the game: Nepomniachtchi,I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ -Riazantsev,A @@StartBracket@@2638@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020. The idea is that if we take back the rook, White will win the d4-bishop with a dominating position. The two pieces are much better than the rook.   15...Qd7?!  and the knight would be temporarily pinned to the queen on d7.   15...Qc7?  16.Ne1!  and we will lose at least a pawn. }
16. Qb5 { An annoying attack on our b7-pawn. } 16... e5
{ Allowing the capture of the b7-pawn is not a good idea:  16...Rd8?!  17.Qxb7  Rb8  18.Qa6  Rxb2  19.Nd5  and Black has to deal with both short and long-term threats.   16...f5!?  is a move I haven't really checked, but my engine thinks it's OK, with the threat of kicking the bishop on e3 back with ...f4.   16...Rb8!?  17.d5!  One of the points of 16.Qb5.  17...Bxc3  18.bxc3  and now, compared to 16. b5, we cannot play  18...Nd4  as the queen on b5 is protected after  19.Nxd4  , so we should go  @@StartFEN@@1r2qrk1/pp2pp1p/2n3p1/1QPP4/2p5/2PbBN1P/P4PP1/R2R2K1 b - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Ne5  19.Qxe8  Nxf3+  20.gxf3  Rfxe8⇆  with a roughly equal opposite-coloured bishop position. White has a very weak pawn on d5, yet there should be enough compensation for that. }
17. d5 e4
{ 17...Nd4!?  is also very much possible. It puts the knight on an active square and poses White lots of problems:  18.Qxb7!  White needs to go for the repetition here:  18...Rb8  19.Qxa7  Ra8  We also don't have much of a choice, as two pawns is simply too much material.  20.Qb7  Rb8  21.Qa7=  With a repetition.Note that after  @@StartFEN@@1r2qrk1/pQ3pbp/6p1/2PPp3/2pn4/2NbBN1P/PP3PP1/R2R2K1 w - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Qa6?!  Nc2  20.Rac1  Nxe3  21.fxe3  e4!  White is in big trouble. Black has a lot of threats that White should address, e.g.  22.Nd2  Rxb2  . }
18. Qxb7 { Counter-attacking our knight on c6. } 18... Na5 19. Qa6 exf3 20.
Qxa5 fxg2
{ With a double-edged position. White has two very strong pawns on c5 and d5, yet we have a weak kingside to play against. }
