{ A wonderful multi-purpose move played already in 2004 by Shabalov. It protects the knight on c6, supports an ...e5-push, makes room for the rook on d8, and sets up potential tricks with the white queen on a4.   15...Nxd4??  doesn't work for Black, unfortunately. It's a trick that many players have fallen for.  16.Nxd4  Bxd4  17.Rxd3!+-  This occurred, for example, in the game: Nepomniachtchi,I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ -Riazantsev,A @@StartBracket@@2638@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020. The idea is that if we take back the rook, White will win the d4-bishop with a dominating position. The two pieces are much better than the rook.   15...Qd7?!  and the knight would be temporarily pinned to the queen on d7.   15...Qc7?  16.Ne1!  and we will lose at least a pawn. }
16. Ne1
{ The most played move. White immediately targets the strong bishop on d3. }
16... Nxd4 { This is only possible thanks to the queen on e8. } 17. Qxe8
{ Slightly less accurate than  17.Nxd3  , which we will seenext. It is better for White to let Black take on a4 as the knight on a4 supports the weak pawn on c5. You will see later that White has to play Na4 anyway. }
17... Rfxe8 18. Nxd3 cxd3 19. Rxd3 Nc2
{ The most straightforward, yet not the only move in this position.  19...Rad8  20.Rad1  Nc6=  is equal.   19...Nf5  20.Rad1  Rac8  21.Na4  Nxe3  transposes to 19...Nc2. }
20. Rad1 Rac8
{ We can wait a move before taking on e3; first, we target the pawn on c5. }
21. Na4 Nxe3 22. Rxe3 b5
{ I like this move very much. Black hasn't equalised completely yet, due to White's space advantage on the queenside and the control of the d-file, but this solves the first problem. Soon after  22...Rc7  a draw was agreed in the game Sankalp,G @@StartBracket@@2254@@EndBracket@@ -Aravindh,C @@StartBracket@@2579@@EndBracket@@ Ahmedabad 2017. }
23. cxb6 axb6 24. Nxb6 Rc2
{ We win the pawn back and, thanks to our strong bishop, White's remaining a-pawn @@StartBracket@@most likely@@EndBracket@@, will not be that dangerous. }
