1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. h3
O-O
{ In this chapter, we are taking a look at 9th move alternatives where White doesn't play a quick Be2. This chapter confused the hell out of me, as many transpositions to the previous chapters occur, but there are also often slight differences. }
9. Be3 { For  9.Be2  seeChapter 1.3. } 9... Nc6 10. b3 f5
{ Usually, this move is not good, but here it is as we can follow it up with ...e5 immediately.   10...d5!?  is interesting here.  11.c5  Nd7  12.Nxd5  Nxc5!  13.dxc5  Bxa1  14.Qxa1  Qxd5  and we have won the exchange. White does have a lot of compensation with the dark-square domination.  15.Bc4  Qh5  16.Ke2!=∞  with excellent compensation for the exchange. Most likely, we'll have to give some material back.   Alternatively,  10...e5!?  11.d5  Ne7⇆  is possible, intending ...Nf5. }
11. Qd2 e5 { With very nice play for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
