1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. h3
O-O
{ In this chapter, we are taking a look at 9th move alternatives where White doesn't play a quick Be2. This chapter confused the hell out of me, as many transpositions to the previous chapters occur, but there are also often slight differences. }
9. Be3 { For  9.Be2  seeChapter 1.3. } 9... Nc6 10. Qd2
{ A move I faced when I was 11 years old! I wish I could tell you to play as I did in that game but, unfortunately, I didn't play the best line. }
10... e5
{ 10...d5?!  11.c5  Nc4  12.Bxc4  and as the light-squared bishop hasn't moved before, White has saved a valuable tempo by taking the knight off the board in one move.  12...dxc4  13.O-O  b6  14.d5±  and White has a good version ofour previous chapter with Qd2 being preferred over Rc1.   10...Bf5!?  was the move I played in Groeneweg,B-Pruijssers,R Dieren 2001. It is decent and White's main reply is still  11.Be2  , after which  11...d5  is once again quite strong.Unfortunately, White can also play  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/1nnp2p1/5b2/2PP4/2N1BN1P/PP1Q1PP1/R3KB1R w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.g4!  Bd7  12.Bh6Ν  followed by O-O-O, and enjoy a nice attacking position. }
11. dxe5
{ 11.O-O-O!?  Qe7⇆  followed by ...f5 in almost all situations. The position is complicated, but not necessarily worse for Black. }
11... dxe5 12. Qxd8
{ In case of  12.c5  e4!  13.Nxe4  Qxd2+  14.Nfxd2  Na4⩱  we win back the b2-pawn with very active pieces. }
12... Rxd8 13. c5
{ This looks good for White if we had to move our knight back or occupy the d5-square. }
13... Nb4
{ Yet this thwarts White's plans, as taking the knight on b6 would lead to White losing an exchange. }
14. Rc1 N6d5
{ And Black has no problems. The bishop on e3 can be taken off the board soon, and Black will have the advantage of the bishop pair. }
