[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. h3
O-O
{ In this chapter, we are taking a look at 9th move alternatives where White doesn't play a quick Be2. This chapter confused the hell out of me, as many transpositions to the previous chapters occur, but there are also often slight differences. }
9. Be3 { For  9.Be2  seeChapter 1.3. } 9... Nc6 10. Rc1
{ You could call this a hybrid system, as it combines ideas from our previous chapters: a quick h3, together with a quick Be3-Rc1. }
10... e5
{ Just asagainst 10. Qd2, this move makes a lot of sense here. Since White is postponing Be2, we simply could not play ...d5 at all. }
11. dxe5 Nxe5
{ I think this is a very clean way of playing. We temporarily have the weaker pawn structure @@StartBracket@@two islands for White versus three islands for Black@@EndBracket@@, yet we can solve that quite quickly. }
12. Nxe5
{ 12.b3  Nxf3+  13.Qxf3  Be6  14.Be2  d5=  and Black has comfortably equalised. With White's king in the centre, @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp3pbp/1n1pb1p1/8/2P5/1PN1BQ1P/P4PP1/2R1KB1R_w_K_-_0_14@@EndFEN@@ 14. Qxb7? d5  is extremely dangerous for White. }
12... Bxe5 { Play for Black is quite simple: ...Be6-...d5 and it's equal. } 13.
Qd2
{ A clever way to defend everything.  13.b3  Be6=  Followed by ...d5.   13.Be2  Be6  14.b3  d5⇆  and Black was very comfortable in the game: Azarov,S @@StartBracket@@2577@@EndBracket@@-Luch,M  @@StartBracket@@2432@@EndBracket@@ Czech Republic 2017. }
13... Be6 14. Nb5 { Intending to cover the d4-square. } 14... d5 15. c5
{ If we had to move our knight back to d7 or c8, White could nicely blockade our d5-pawn with the knight on b5 moving to d4. }
15... Nc4 { However, this disrupts White's plan. } 16. Bxc4 dxc4 17. Nd6
{ Loxine,J  @@StartBracket@@2408@@EndBracket@@-Heinz,J @@StartBracket@@2258@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2012. }
17... b6
{ This is a long-term pawn sacrifice offering Black significant compensation. }
18. Nxc4 Qxd2+ 19. Kxd2 Bf6 20. cxb6 axb6
{ And Black will already regain the pawn as White cannot defend b2 and a2. } *

