1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. h3
O-O
{ In this chapter, we are taking a look at 9th move alternatives where White doesn't play a quick Be2. This chapter confused the hell out of me, as many transpositions to the previous chapters occur, but there are also often slight differences. }
9. Be3 { For  9.Be2  seeChapter 1.3. } 9... Nc6 10. Rc1
{ You could call this a hybrid system, as it combines ideas from our previous chapters: a quick h3, together with a quick Be3-Rc1. }
10... d5
{ Yet this actually still works fine. In comparison tothe line after 10.Qd2 we can make use of the c1-rook. }
11. c5
{ 11.b3?!  e5↑  White's king is in the centre, so opening up the e-file is a good idea. }
11... Nc4 12. Bxc4
{ White has cleverly won a tempo compared toChapter 1.4. Yet it turns out that White's extra move Rc1 isn't enough to claim an advantage. }
12... dxc4 13. O-O
{ Compare this position to the one after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/1n1p2p1/8/2PP4/2N2N1P/PP3PP1/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Be2  Nc6  10.O-O  Bf5  11.Be3  d5  12.c5  Nc4  . The only difference is that White has saved a tempo by playing Rc1 instead of Be2-Bxc4.   This tempo matters, as now  13...Bf5  doesn't work for Black. }
13... b6
{ This, however, is still perfectly satisfactory. By undermining the c5-pawn, we take out one of White's positional assets. Indirectly we are also making sure we do not lose material. For example:   13...Bf5?  is exactly what White wants:  14.Qa4!  Nxd4?  This still doesn't work.  15.Nxd4  Bxd4  16.Rfd1  e5  17.Qxc4+-  and White will win a pawn as the bishop on d4 stays pinned and cannot be defended.  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n3p1/2P2b2/Q1pP4/2N1BN1P/PP3PP1/2R2RK1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Bd3  15.Rfd1±  and the fact that the rook is already on c1 protecting the knight on c3 means that the complications simply work out for White. For example:  15...Qe8?  16.b3!  e5  17.d5  Nd4   @@StartBracket@@  17...e4?  18.dxc6  exf3  19.cxb7+-  is simply winning for White. The c- and b-pawn decide the game.@@EndBracket@@  18.Qxe8  Rfxe8  19.bxc4  Notice again how the rook on c1 makes all the difference.  19...Bxc4  20.Nxd4  exd4  21.Bxd4+-  and White is a pawn up with a dominant position. }
14. Qa4 { White can of course try to win the c4-pawn anyway. } 14... Nxd4
{ And here we see the point. We are able to take on d4 now. } 15. Bxd4
{ This doesn't really improve matters for White. } 15... Bxd4 16. cxb6
{ This was played in a game, yet I think it helps Black.  16.c6  is more interesting - the pawn could give us tactical problems with Nb5, for example. Therefore, it makes sense to eliminate the knight on c3.  16...Bxc3  17.Rxc3  Be6⇆  The position is still quite interesting, yet with a pawn up and the threats under check, we should not feel disheartened to go into this. }
16... Bxc3 17. Rxc3 Qxb6
{ And Black went on to win in the game: Luldachev,S @@StartBracket@@2456@@EndBracket@@-Xu,X @@StartBracket@@2585@@EndBracket@@ Hamedan 2018. White is still a pawn down and with b2 under attack and the c4-pawn easily protected with a move like ...Be6 or ...Ba6, White will struggle to win it back. }
*

