[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.6) The Exchange Variation - 7.Nf3 Bg7 8.Be3 0-0 9.Be2"]
[Black "Exchange - 10.b3!? #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be3
O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. b3
{ Another slight difference from our previous chapters. Now we can play ...Bg4 but it's not that strong here. }
10... d5
{ 10...Bg4?!  11.h3!  Bxf3  12.Bxf3⩲  and we have a hard time putting our pawns on light squares to undermine White's strong light-squared bishop. }
11. c5 { 11.O-O  Bg4  transposes to10. O-O, the mainline in this chapter. }
11... Nd7
{ We are threatening ...Nxc5 as the knight on c3 is unprotected. If White defends against that threat, we can push ...e5. }
12. Nxd5 Nxc5 { Attacking the knight. } 13. dxc5
{ Otherwise, White is just clearly worse. } 13... Bxa1 14. Qxa1 Qxd5 15. Bh6
{ Black is simply an exchange up after  15.Bc4?  Qh5  followed by ...Be6, as White cannot create threats. }
15... e5
{ White wins back the exchange but has weaker pieces and a pawn on c5 to protect. }
