1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be3
O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. d5 Na5
{ 10...Ne5?  doesn't work here as White will be castled very shortly.  11.Nxe5  Bxe5  12.Bd4!  This is the type of position we really want to avoid.  12...Bxd4  13.Qxd4±  White has a solid space advantage, and we are not in time to comfortably break in the centre with ...e6, as our d6-pawn will be weak, and we would open ourselves up to Ne4-f6 shenanigans. }
11. Nd2 Bd7
{ Now White will have to make a big concession in order not to lose the c4-pawn. }
12. Rc1 Rc8 13. b3
{ This doesn't work but after  13.Bxb6  Qxb6⩱  Black has a grip on the dark squares, and the b2-pawn is attacked. The knight on a5 is still stuck, which will still require some attention. }
13... Bxc3 14. Rxc3 Nxd5
{ And since the rook on c3 is unprotected, we win a pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.6) The Exchange Variation - 7.Nf3 Bg7 8.Be3 0-0 9.Be2"]
[Black "Exchange - 10.d5!? #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be3
O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. d5 Na5
{ 10...Ne5?  doesn't work here as White will be castled very shortly.  11.Nxe5  Bxe5  12.Bd4!  This is the type of position we really want to avoid.  12...Bxd4  13.Qxd4±  White has a solid space advantage, and we are not in time to comfortably break in the centre with ...e6, as our d6-pawn will be weak, and we would open ourselves up to Ne4-f6 shenanigans. }
11. Bd4 Bxd4
{ 11...Naxc4!?  12.Bxg7  Kxg7  13.Qd4+  and White wins back the pawn.  13...Ne5  14.Nxe5  dxe5  15.Qxe5+  I would say White is slightly better. If White castles short, they will have the safest king. }
12. Qxd4 e5
{ Necessary, making use of the weak c4-pawn. If we do nothing, our knight on a5 is stuck. }
13. dxe6 { Otherwise, White loses the pawn on c4. } 13... Bxe6 14. b3 d5
{ This should be about equal. } 15. c5
{ The only critical move.  15.cxd5  Nxd5  is just equal. } 15... Nc6
{ Yet this works well for Black. } 16. Qf4
{ After  16.Qd2  Nd7  , White has to take on d5 or otherwise protect c5 with the awkward  17.Na4  and we get counterplay with  17...Qf6  18.Rd1  Rfd8  19.O-O  d4!  taking the d4-square away from the white knight to follow up with ...Nde5. }
16... Nd7 17. b4 d4
{ Disrupting the connection between the white queen and the d4-pawn. } 18. Nxd4
Nxb4
{ Play is still difficult, yet I wouldn't say White has an advantage here. }
19. O-O Nd5
{ And Black has no problems, while White has to take care of the c5-pawn. } *

