1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be3
O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. d5 Na5
{ 10...Ne5?  doesn't work here as White will be castled very shortly.  11.Nxe5  Bxe5  12.Bd4!  This is the type of position we really want to avoid.  12...Bxd4  13.Qxd4±  White has a solid space advantage, and we are not in time to comfortably break in the centre with ...e6, as our d6-pawn will be weak, and we would open ourselves up to Ne4-f6 shenanigans. }
11. Bd4 Bxd4
{ 11...Naxc4!?  12.Bxg7  Kxg7  13.Qd4+  and White wins back the pawn.  13...Ne5  14.Nxe5  dxe5  15.Qxe5+  I would say White is slightly better. If White castles short, they will have the safest king. }
