{ It's best to take the pawn. In this case, I prefer taking with the b6-knight as the other knight can kick the queen away on d4 with ...Nc6.   14...Bxc4?!  leads to some problems:  15.Bxc4  Naxc4  16.Ne4  f5  17.Neg5⩲  and we have some problems on the d- and e-files.   14...Naxc4!?  15.Ne4  Ne5  16.Nxe5  dxe5  17.Qxe5  Nd7  18.Qf4  Qb8! =  A nice move that allows us to exchange queens without problems or land our queen on e5 if White moves theirs away. In both cases, the position is about equal. }
15. Ne4 f6
{ Sellos,D @@StartBracket@@2425@@EndBracket@@-Santo Roman,M @@StartBracket@@2375@@EndBracket@@ Chanac 1989. Black is a pawn up, but White should have enough compensation for the pawn to obtain equality. }
16. Bxc4 Nxc4 { The knight will find an outpost on the e5-square. } *

