O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. Rc1
{ This could be considered a small trap. White wants to get into a better version ofthe 10.d5 line by including the moves Rc1 and ...Bg4. }
10... d5
{ Yet this is once again fine.  10...Bg4?!  11.d5  Na5  12.b3!  +- is the point of 10.Rc1, leaving White with a close-to-winning position already, as the black knights are useless. After  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/1nnp2p1/3P4/2P3b1/2N1BN2/PP2BPPP/2RQK2R b K - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bxf3  12.gxf3!  Ne5  13.b3±  White has a very nice position with the bishop pair, more space and better pieces, making up for a slightly weakened king. }
11. c5 Nc4 12. Bxc4 dxc4
{ This is almost identical to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/1n1p2p1/8/2PP4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h3  O-O  9.Be3  Nc6  10.Rc1  variation, with the only difference that White hasn't played h3 yet. }
13. O-O Bf5
{ Alternatively, after  13...b6  I can refer you toour previous chapter. } 14.
Qa4 Bg4
{ A charming extra option now, and Black is just fine.   14...Bd3?  15.Rfd1  Seethe previous chapter on why this is bad for Black. }
15. Rfd1 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Nxd4
{ White has good pieces, but his weakened kingside compensates us for that. } *

