1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be3
O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O
{ We delve into one of the most basic variations. White has played the most natural moves possible. }
10... Bg4
{ The main reason why the previous chapters are popular from the white side. }
11. b3
{ Defending against our threat of ...Bxf3.  11.h3?  Bxf3  12.gxf3  d5∓  and White's kingside structure is crippled. }
11... d5
{ Again, this is the right move to play. This should be as familiar as your neighbour's face by now. }
12. c5 { 12.cxd5  Nb4  is very pleasant for Black. } 12... Nc8
{ This is a position where white players often go wrong. Black's plan is to play ...e6-...N8e7-...Nf5 @@StartBracket@@perhaps even ...Qf6@@EndBracket@@ and collect the d4-pawn. White's correct plan is to play on the queenside. }
13. Ne1
{ Though almost never played, this is a contender for the best move here. By not allowing Black to exchange on f3, White will have an easier time protecting d4. After the exchange on f3, the white bishop on f3 very often turns out to be a problem piece. }
13... Bxe2 14. Nxe2 e6
{ 14...b6!?  15.cxb6?!  only helps Black after  15...Qxb6⩱  when we can regroup our c8-knight to the good d6-square. Better is  @@StartFEN@@r1nq1rk1/p3ppbp/1pn3p1/2Pp4/3P4/1P2B3/P3NPPP/R2QNRK1 w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Rc1  e6  16.Qd2  bxc5  17.Rxc5  We have been following the game: Huebner,R @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@-Timman,J @@StartBracket@@2630@@EndBracket@@ Sarajevo 1991.  17...N6e7! =  followed by ...Nd6 with a roughly equal position. }
15. Rb1 a5
{ Since White doesn't have a light-squared bishop anymore, there is no drawback to preventing b4 temporarily. }
16. a3 N8e7 17. b4 axb4 18. axb4 Nf5
{ We have the a-file and the more active pieces, while White has potential on the queenside. The position is about equal. Notice how b5 allows us to get an outpost on c4 for our knight. If White postpones b5, then we can search for counterplay in the centre with ...e5. }
*

