{ 15...Bf5!?  Keeping bishops on the board kind of makes sense here, especially since we attack the rook on b1.  16.Bd3?  Nxd4  and Black wins a pawn. White should try  @@StartFEN@@r1nq1rk1/1p3pbp/p1n1p1p1/2Pp1b2/1P1P4/2N1B3/P3BPPP/1R1QNRK1 w - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Rb2  g5!  making sure we don't trap our bishop on f5.  17.a4  N8e7  18.Qd2  h6⇆  with a messy position. Black's plan is to eventually break in the centre with ...e5 while ensuring that White cannot exploit our weakened kingside.   Note that after something like @@StartFEN@@r1nq1rk1/1p3pbp/p1n1p1p1/2Pp1b2/1P1P4/2N1B3/PR2BPPP/3QNRK1 b - - 3 16@@EndFEN@@  16...e5  17.Nf3  exd4  18.Nxd4⩲  White has nullified most of our counterplay. }
16. Nxe2 N8e7
{ White has a small advantage because of their extra space. Black is solid, though, and it will be very hard to break through for White. An idea to remember is to counter a4-b5 by playing ...b5 ourselves. Sometimes it's useful to play ...b6 in order to create some counterplay over the b-file with ...Rb8. For example:   17.Nf3⩲  Nf5  18.Qd2  was played in Bohm,H-Cafferty,B Amsterdam 1972 and now  18...Qd7  19.Rfd1  b5!  20.cxb6?!  gives us some play after  20...Rfb8↑  while after  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/3q1pbp/p1n1p1p1/1pPp1n2/1P1P4/4BN2/P2QNPPP/1R1R2K1 w - b6 0 20@@EndFEN@@  20.a3  Rad8⩲  once again, White enjoys a slightly better position. }
