[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.6) The Exchange Variation - 7.Nf3 Bg7 8.Be3 0-0 9.Be2"]
[Black "Exchange - 11.b3 d5! 12.c5 Nc8 13.b4! #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be3
O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O
{ We delve into one of the most basic variations. White has played the most natural moves possible. }
10... Bg4
{ The main reason why the previous chapters are popular from the white side. }
11. b3
{ Defending against our threat of ...Bxf3.  11.h3?  Bxf3  12.gxf3  d5∓  and White's kingside structure is crippled. }
11... d5
{ Again, this is the right move to play. This should be as familiar as your neighbour's face by now. }
12. c5 { 12.cxd5  Nb4  is very pleasant for Black. } 12... Nc8
{ This is a position where white players often go wrong. Black's plan is to play ...e6-...N8e7-...Nf5 @@StartBracket@@perhaps even ...Qf6@@EndBracket@@ and collect the d4-pawn. White's correct plan is to play on the queenside. }
13. b4
{ White's best move. If  13.Rc1?!  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  e6  we can go for our usual plan of ...Ne7-...Nf5.   13.a3?!  is a waste of time - White wants to play b4-b5 as quickly as possible.  13...e6  14.b4  a6  was played in Zhu,J  (2424)  -Nakamura,H  (2749)  chess.com INT 2019. White cannot advance further because of the pressure on the b4-pawn. }
13... a6
{ A very calm and straightforward answer aimed at preventing White's b5.   13...Nxb4?!  only helps White:  14.Rb1  Nc6  15.Rxb7  White has an active and potentially annoying rook on b7. Also, our knight on c6 is undefended and can become a target with Qa4 or Bb5 at certain points. }
14. Rb1
{ 14.a3?!  does not support the a4-b5 plan. We continue with our standard play.  14...Bxf3  15.Bxf3  e6=  . }
14... e6 15. Ne5 { This is not a worry. } 15... Nxe5 16. dxe5
{ This loses a pawn. Better is  16.Bxg4  but after  16...Nc4↑↑  we have a fantastic knight on c4. We can take on e3 at an opportune moment and start undermining White's centre as usual. }
16... Bxe2
{ And no matter how White takes back, we take the e5-pawn with our bishop on the next move. }
*

