{ This is interesting even though White's f1-bishop hasn't moved yet. Still, my recommendation is  9...Nc6!?  . }
10. c5
{ 10.b3  Nc6  and after White plays  11.Be2  ,  11.h3  or  11.c5  we transpose to other lines. }
10... Nc4 11. Bxc4 dxc4 12. O-O Nc6
{ And White is a tempo up compared to10.Rc1 in Chapter 1.6, yet it is not clear how White should spend that extra tempo. }
13. b3
{ The move with which White can fight for the advantage.  13.h3  transposes toChapter 1.5 after  13...b6!  . }
13... Bg4
{ 13...cxb3?!  14.Qxb3  Nxd4  15.Nxd4  Bxd4  16.Bxd4  Qxd4  17.Rfd1=∞  and White has fantastic compensation for the pawn. }
14. d5 Ne5 15. bxc4 e6
{ Followed by ...Qf6. White is better but their position is very difficult to play as it has many weaknesses. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.8) The Exchange Variation - 7.h4"]
[Black "Exchange - 8.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. h4
{ A move that coincidentally was played against me in an online chess game a few days before writing this chapter. It is pretty logical, as allowing h5 is dangerous for us. If you look at the database, this move is rarely played. Therefore, most of the analysis here is preliminary and original. However, I suspect this move might become more popular in the future. }
7... h5
{ The only good response. We cannot allow White's pawn to reach h5. From this point, White has a wide range of available setups.   7...Bg7?!  8.h5!  gives White all sorts of extra options: they can push h6 when the time is right or, if we castle short, open the h-file and start creating threats. }
8. Be3
{ Let's check what happens when White still goes for the Rc1-b3 setup as in our first two chapters. }
8... Bg7 9. Qd2 Nc6 10. Nf3 Bg4 11. Ng5
{ This is another reasonable setup for White, making use of the now available g5-square. Notice how this was enabled by not allowing the knight to be pinned on f3. }
11... d5 { As usual, this is a good response. } 12. c5 e5
{ This leads to complicated lines similar to ouralternative 9...d5 in chapter 1.7. It's a strong move, as our b6-knight cannot be taken. Let's see some examples.   12...Nc4!?  is certainly playable as well.  13.Bxc4  dxc4  14.d5  Ne5  15.O-O  Nd3!⇆  On the next few moves we can castle and target White's c5-pawn. This position, of course, needs testing, but I think Black has enough play to compensate for White's centre. }
13. Nb5
{ One of the best moves here. White tries to counter us by putting a knight on d6 with check.   13.cxb6?  exd4∓  and we win back the piece with interest.   13.dxe5  d4  14.cxb6  Bxe5⇆  on the next move, we take back the piece with a more than fine position. }
13... O-O
{ It makes sense to get out of the check. The knight on b6 still can not be taken. }
14. f3
{ 14.cxb6?  exd4  15.Nxd4  Nxd4  16.Bxd4  Re8+  17.Be3  Qxb6  Followed by ...d4 on the next move, and White is already lost. We have too many threats. }
14... Qe7
{ We put the queen on the e-file, as the rook on e8 can potentially be attacked by the white knight. }
15. Kf2 f6 16. Nh3
{ 16.cxb6  exd4  17.Nxd4  fxg5⇆  with a mess, but I prefer Black because of our safe king. }
16... Bxh3 17. Rxh3 exd4 18. Nxd4 Nd7
{ With a messy position where both players have chances. We want to target the c5-pawn and activate our dark-squared bishop by playing ...f5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.8) The Exchange Variation - 7.h4"]
[Black "Exchange - 8.Be3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. h4
{ A move that coincidentally was played against me in an online chess game a few days before writing this chapter. It is pretty logical, as allowing h5 is dangerous for us. If you look at the database, this move is rarely played. Therefore, most of the analysis here is preliminary and original. However, I suspect this move might become more popular in the future. }
7... h5
{ The only good response. We cannot allow White's pawn to reach h5. From this point, White has a wide range of available setups.   7...Bg7?!  8.h5!  gives White all sorts of extra options: they can push h6 when the time is right or, if we castle short, open the h-file and start creating threats. }
8. Be3
{ Let's check what happens when White still goes for the Rc1-b3 setup as in our first two chapters. }
8... Bg7 9. Rc1 O-O 10. b3 Nc6
{ This move now makes a lot of sense. One of the problems in the original line @@StartBracket@@without h4 and h5 included@@EndBracket@@ is that the c6-knight is unstable on e5 if pushed away by White's d-pawn. Yet, in this case, the knight has a nice outpost available on g4, making the e5-square very stable.   10...Bf5  If we play normally, White gets an extra option.  11.Be2  d5  12.c5  Nc8  13.g4!  →  and suddenly White gets a dangerous initiative on the kingside. }
11. d5
{ 11.Nf3  makes no sense, as after  11...Bg4!  we have a much better version than in the original Rc1-b3 lines. }
11... Ne5 { As I said, the knight is quite stable here. } 12. Nf3 Nxf3+
{ We can just take the knight and play ...e6 next with a good position as White's king is still in the centre. }
