{ The only good response. We cannot allow White's pawn to reach h5. From this point, White has a wide range of available setups.   7...Bg7?!  8.h5!  gives White all sorts of extra options: they can push h6 when the time is right or, if we castle short, open the h-file and start creating threats. }
8. Be3
{ Let's check what happens when White still goes for the Rc1-b3 setup as in our first two chapters. }
8... Bg7 9. Rc1 O-O 10. b3 Nc6
{ This move now makes a lot of sense. One of the problems in the original line @@StartBracket@@without h4 and h5 included@@EndBracket@@ is that the c6-knight is unstable on e5 if pushed away by White's d-pawn. Yet, in this case, the knight has a nice outpost available on g4, making the e5-square very stable.   10...Bf5  If we play normally, White gets an extra option.  11.Be2  d5  12.c5  Nc8  13.g4!  →  and suddenly White gets a dangerous initiative on the kingside. }
