1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. h4
{ A move that coincidentally was played against me in an online chess game a few days before writing this chapter. It is pretty logical, as allowing h5 is dangerous for us. If you look at the database, this move is rarely played. Therefore, most of the analysis here is preliminary and original. However, I suspect this move might become more popular in the future. }
7... h5
{ The only good response. We cannot allow White's pawn to reach h5. From this point, White has a wide range of available setups.   7...Bg7?!  8.h5!  gives White all sorts of extra options: they can push h6 when the time is right or, if we castle short, open the h-file and start creating threats. }
8. a4
{ As I'll explain ina later chapter, this move is quite new even without h4 and h5 included. Yet, with this inclusion, we need to analyze a few extra options for White now that the g5-square is readily available for White's bishop. }
8... Bg7
{ This time, we have to allow White's a5. Now 8... a5?  is very bad for us, unfortunately:   9.c5!  and the available g5-square is very harmful. Notice how in the previous chapter, we were able to chase the bishop away with ...h6-...g5.  9...dxc5  10.Bb5+  N6d7   @@StartBracket@@  10...N8d7??  11.dxc5  and the b6-knight is trapped.@@EndBracket@@  11.Nd5!  and there is no satisfactory way to stop all the incoming threats. It is amazing how the inclusion of h4 and ...h5 can make such a big difference in the evaluation. The computer already gives White a +3 advantage.For example, after  11...Nc6  12.Bf4  e5  13.dxe5  White has won back the pawn and now e6 is a threat together with Bg5. White is winning. Or  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1npp2/6p1/pBpN3p/P2P3P/8/1P3PP1/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bg7  12.Bg5!  Bf6  There is hardly a better way to defend e7.  13.Bf4!  O-O  14.Bc7  Qe8  15.Nf3+-  Black is cramped and after White plays O-O and Re1, we are in dire straits. }
9. a5 N6d7 10. d5
{ This has been played in a real game, yet with a knight on d7 this really does not make a lot of sense. We have nice options to develop our knight. For example: }
10... Ne5 { The knight is very stable here now with the g4-square available. }
11. Be2 O-O 12. Ra3
{ We have been following the correspondence game: Prochazka, D @@StartBracket@@2284@@EndBracket@@-Oorebeek,E @@StartBracket@@2069@@EndBracket@@ IECG email 1996. }
12... Nbd7
{ I like this move best. Next, we will play ...b6 and start playing actively on the queenside or potentially even in the centre. }
