1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. h4
{ A move that coincidentally was played against me in an online chess game a few days before writing this chapter. It is pretty logical, as allowing h5 is dangerous for us. If you look at the database, this move is rarely played. Therefore, most of the analysis here is preliminary and original. However, I suspect this move might become more popular in the future. }
7... h5
{ The only good response. We cannot allow White's pawn to reach h5. From this point, White has a wide range of available setups.   7...Bg7?!  8.h5!  gives White all sorts of extra options: they can push h6 when the time is right or, if we castle short, open the h-file and start creating threats. }
8. Bg5
{ This move makes most sense in my opinion. The bishop is well-placed on g5, and if White plays normally, like in the mainlines we have already covered, then you will see that the inclusion of h4 and h5 is most often beneficial for Black. }
8... Bg7 9. Nf3
{ We meet this move with our usual pin which can now not be contested with an h3-move by White. }
9... Bg4 10. Be2 Nc6 11. O-O O-O
{ 11...Bxf3?!  12.Bxf3  Nxd4  Grabbing the pawn is not good for us:  13.Re1  Ne6  14.Bxb7±  and the exchange of White's d-pawn and Black's b-pawn is only beneficial for White due to the bishop pair and Black's king still in the centre. }
12. Rc1 { In this position we can't play as we usually would with ...d5. }
12... Bxf3
{ This is the right way now. The d4-pawn on d4 can be exchanged for our b7-pawn.   12...d5?  13.c5  Nc4  Notice how there is no bishop on e3 for us to exchange.  13...Nc8?!  14.Qb3!  And we are in a lot of trouble.  14.Nxd5!  This is not the only move for White to claim a clear advantage. I do think this is the cleanest one - White simply wins a pawn now.  14...Qxd5  15.Bxc4±  and White is a pawn up, or  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppb1/2n3p1/2PN2Bp/2nP2bP/5N2/PP2BPP1/2RQ1RK1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Nxb2  15.Qb3  and the knight is trapped on b2, while e7 and b7 are still under target for White. The forced variations go a bit further than this, but it's enough for me that the computer evaluation is at the very least +2.5 for White. }
13. Bxf3 Nxd4 14. Bxb7 Rb8
{ Suddenly, White has problems to solve. The c4-pawn is under attack, as well as the bishop on b7. }
15. Bd5
{ Protecting c4. Instead,  15.Ba6?!  Ne6!  intending ...Nc7 or ...Nc5 next. }
15... Qd7 { If  15...Nxd5  16.Nxd5  we have a problem with the e7-pawn. } 16.
b3 e6 17. Be4 d5 { Taking more control of the centre. } 18. cxd5 exd5 19. Bd3
Ne6
{ White has the bishop pair, but we have well-placed pieces in return and active ideas connected with the d-pawn. }
