{ This move makes most sense in my opinion. The bishop is well-placed on g5, and if White plays normally, like in the mainlines we have already covered, then you will see that the inclusion of h4 and h5 is most often beneficial for Black. }
8... Bg7 9. Rc1 { White still goes for the b3 setup. } 9... Nc6
{ I like this move very much. I want to target the d4-pawn as soon as possible, and with the g4-square now at our disposal the knight is very stable on the e5-outpost. }
10. Nf3 Bg4 11. Be2 Bxf3
{ An extra option since White hasn't castled.  11...O-O  transposeshere in the 9.Nf3 mainline. }
12. Bxf3 Nxd4 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Be4 O-O 15. b3
{ At first glance, this position looks quite nice for White. White has the bishop pair, a solid pawn structure, and no threats to be concerned about. However, White needs a good plan, and we will restructure our pieces so that White has no clear way to proceed. }
15... Ne6 16. Be3 Nd7
{ This move is quite excellent. The knight wasn't doing anything on b6, while on c5 or e5, the knight suddenly has a lot of potential. }
17. O-O Nec5 18. Bf3 Ne5 19. Be2
{ White correctly tries to hold on to the bishop pair. } 19... Nc6 20. Qd2 Re8
{ All our pieces are well-positioned. I consider White a bit better due to the bishop pair, yet, for the moment White has no active ideas and if we stay solid then it will be very hard for White to make use of that advantage. We are very deep in novel territory now, as the last known move was played a while ago. Therefore this position does need some practice, but my feeling is that Black is fine here. The computer agrees, as it claims a very small advantage for White. }
