7. Qd4 { Otherwise, an early d5 wouldn't make too much sense. } 7... e5 8. dxe6
{ 8.Qd1?  Bg7∓  would give us two very valuable tempi. } 8... f6
{ This looks horrible from a pawn structure/positional point of view, yet from a development perspective, it is wonderful for Black. Next, we can play ...Nc6 and ...d5 after virtually every move White plays, with active piece play. This has been played by Alekhine expert GM Alexander Fier from Brazil, who is also mentioned in the Four Pawns Attack chapter. }
9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Qh4 Bxe6 11. Nf3 Bg7 12. Bh6
{ Or  12.Be2  O-O  13.O-O  g5  14.Qe4  Qd7=∞  with great compensation for the slightly damaged pawn structure. }
12... Bxh6 13. Qxh6 Qe7 14. O-O-O O-O-O
{ Followed by ...Rhe8 and ...d5 with an equal position.   The attempt to physically stop ...d5 by going  15.Nd5?!  backfires as after  15...Bxd5  16.cxd5  Nb4  we have too many threats:  17.Qd2  is forced but  17...Qe4!  threatening mate on a2 provokes some further weakening.  18.b3  Kb8  and ...Rc8 is coming. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.9) The Exchange Variation - 6th move alternatives"]
[Black "Exchange - 6.d5!? g6! 7.Qd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. d4 d6 5. exd6 cxd6
{ In this chapter, we will cover White's main alternatives  6.d5!?  and the very serious  6.a4!?  . After  6.b3?!  g6  7.Bb2  Bg7  we can play similarly to the Exchange Variation, and White will find the bishop on b2 to be misplaced. }
6. d5 { White aims to prevent ...g6. } 6... g6
{ However, it is perfectly alright to play it anyway! Instead, after  6...e6!?  7.Nc3  Be7  8.Nf3  O-O  9.Be2⩲  White is a bit better due to the slight space advantage.   6...e5!?  has been the most played move and we get a position similar to the 6.Nd5 Variation in the Sveshnikov. I like this less than the 6...g6 line - in comparison, we still have a knight on b6 that isn't doing too much. For example,  7.Nc3  and now  7...g6!?  is again interesting but after  7...Be7  8.Bd3  O-O  9.Nge2  f5  10.b3⩲  and I think White is slightly better due to Black's lack of space. }
7. Qd4 { Otherwise, an early d5 wouldn't make too much sense. } 7... e5 8. dxe6
{ 8.Qd1?  Bg7∓  would give us two very valuable tempi. } 8... f6
{ This looks horrible from a pawn structure/positional point of view, yet from a development perspective, it is wonderful for Black. Next, we can play ...Nc6 and ...d5 after virtually every move White plays, with active piece play. This has been played by Alekhine expert GM Alexander Fier from Brazil, who is also mentioned in the Four Pawns Attack chapter. }
9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Qf4 d5 { Breaking free! } 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5
{ This only helps Black because White can't take the f6-pawn. For  12.Qe4  Nxc3  13.bxc3  Qa5  seethe 10.Qe3 d5 11.cxd5 Nxd5 12.Qe4 line. }
12... Qxd5 13. Qxf6 Bb4+ 14. Ke2 Rf8 { And Black is winning. } *

