[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.9) The Exchange Variation - 6th move alternatives"]
[Black "Exchange - 6.a4!? a5 7.Nc3 g6 8.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. d4 d6 5. exd6 cxd6
{ In this chapter, we will cover White's main alternatives  6.d5!?  and the very serious  6.a4!?  . After  6.b3?!  g6  7.Bb2  Bg7  we can play similarly to the Exchange Variation, and White will find the bishop on b2 to be misplaced. }
6. a4
{ A line that hasn't been played much, but I expect it to be played a lot more often after this course has been published. After studying the aggressive 4.a4, which is discussed ina later chapter,  I realised that here  6.a4  might be a very serious option for White. For the next couple of moves, Black needs to play very precisely in order not to be overrun. }
6... a5
{ If  6...g6?!  7.a5  N6d7  8.Nf3±  , compared to the normal Exchange Variation, we have no counterplay whatsoever to compensate for White's space advantage. }
7. Nc3 g6 8. Nf3
{ If White plays a normal Exchange Variation, you'll find that a4 and ...a5 has been a useful inclusion for Black, as in many lines White wants to advance on the queenside with b4. }
8... Bg7 9. h3
{ 9.Be3  O-O  10.Be2  and a4 and ...a5 have only been beneficial for Black. }
9... O-O 10. Be2 Nc6 11. O-O { 11.d5  Nb4  is quite pleasant for Black. } 11...
Bf5
{ This gives Black a lot less to worry about since  12.d5  , in the style of the most dangerous variation in the Exchange Variation @@StartBracket@@seeChapter 1.3@@EndBracket@@ is met with  12...Nb4  once again. }
12. Be3 d5 13. c5 Nc4
{ This could be a bit scary - the knight is stuck on c4 now, as it has no retreat square on a5 anymore. However, it all works out. }
14. Bc1 { 14.Bxc4  dxc4  is just great for Black. } 14... Nb4 15. Ne1
{ 15.b3?  Bc2  wins the b3-pawn. } 15... e5
{ And Black is clearly better. White is not in time to trap our c4-knight. } *

[Event "?"]
