6... a5
{ If  6...g6?!  7.a5  N6d7  8.Nf3±  , compared to the normal Exchange Variation, we have no counterplay whatsoever to compensate for White's space advantage. }
7. Nc3 g6 8. c5
{ This move signifies the danger of 6.a4. Without it, it is hard to see what the inclusion of  a4  and  ...a5  has given White, other than a weak b4-square for our knight to occupy. For instance,  8.Be3  Bg7  9.Rc1  O-O  10.b3  Nc6!?  and it's not clear what a4 a5 has gotten White. }
8... dxc5 9. dxc5
{ This has only been tried once, yet this might objectively be better than the main move  9.Bb5+  . }
9... Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1
{ 10.Nxd1?  Nd5∓  and Black is faster to the b4-square than the white knight is to the b5-square. Black has very easy development with ...Bf5 and ...Nc6. }
10... N6d7 11. Nd5 { 11.Nb5?  Na6  and the c5-pawn is very weak. } 11... Ra7
{ Saving the rook from the fork on c7.  11...Na6??  12.Bxa6  is the reason why the knight jumped on d5 instead of b5.  12...Rxa6  13.Nc7++-  Winning the exchange. }
12. Bb5
{ 12.Nc7+?!  Kd8  13.Nb5  Ra6  and it's not clear what White has accomplished.   12.Nf3  Bg7  13.Bb5  Nc6  transposes. Notice we can't play  @@StartFEN@@1nb1kb1r/rp1npp1p/6p1/p1PN4/P7/5N2/1P3PPP/R1BK1B1R b k - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nxc5??  13.Be3  e6  14.Nb6  and White will win at least a piece due to the pressure on the e3-a7 diagonal - the c5-knight can't move. }
12... Bg7 13. Nf3 Nc6
{ Followed by ...O-O and ...e5-...f5. Notice how taking the pawn on c5 leads to material loss due to Be3. White can create problems in many ways, but he has no clear road to an advantage. Black ideally wants to castle and gain space by either exchanging light pieces or pushing the e5-pawn. It is a complicated position that certainly needs testing. }
