{ This move signifies the danger of 6.a4. Without it, it is hard to see what the inclusion of  a4  and  ...a5  has given White, other than a weak b4-square for our knight to occupy. For instance,  8.Be3  Bg7  9.Rc1  O-O  10.b3  Nc6!?  and it's not clear what a4 a5 has gotten White. }
8... dxc5 9. Bb5+ { Played 69 out of 70 times. } 9... N6d7
{ 9...Bd7?  10.dxc5  Nc8  11.Qd4  f6  12.Nf3+-  leaves Black with a cramped position.   9...N8d7??  10.dxc5  and we lose our b6-knight. }
10. Bf4 Bg7
{ 10...cxd4?  offers White a tremendous initiative:  11.Qxd4  hitting the h8-rook and White is already close to winning. }
11. Nd5
{ Threatening a double attack on c7. White needs to be fast. If Black consolidates, the initiative will fizzle out. For instance,  11.Nf3?!  O-O  and White still has to prove the compensation. }
11... e5
{ Giving back the pawn temporarily is the best policy.  11...Na6!?  is a decent alternative, but  11...O-O ?  is not good:  12.Bc7!  Qe8  13.Nb6  and we lose material - the rook has to move, and the d7-knight is pinned, so the b8-knight is doomed. }
12. Bxe5 O-O
{ Not  12...Bxe5?  13.dxe5  O-O  14.f4!  and we can't comfortably untangle due to the hole on f6.  14...Nb6  15.Nf6+  Kg7  16.Nf3±  and White has a big advantage. }
13. Bd6 { Baiting Black into moving the rook to e8. } 13... cxd4
{ Daring White to take the rook on f8.  13...Re8+?!  14.Ne2  cxd4  15.Nc7±  wins White an exchange. In comparison to the text, White is offering a knight instead of a bishop for the rook. As Black, I would much rather grab White's bishop. }
14. Bxf8
{ This gives Black some options. If  14.Ne2  Nc6!  ⇆  the complications continue. }
14... Qxf8 15. Ne2 Qd6 16. Ndf4 Na6 17. O-O Nb4
{ And Black has a pawn and fantastic compensation for the exchange. } *

