13. Bxg7 { 13.Bc7?!Ν  Qg5  leads to some problems for White. } 13... Kxg7 14.
dxc5 Nc6
{ 14...Re8+?!  places the rook in a pin while White wanted to play  15.Ne2  anyway.   14...Nxc5??  15.Qd4+  loses a piece. }
15. Qc1
{ My suggestion for White to improve over earlier games. The idea is to protect c1 and b2. }
15... Nde5
{ Attacking the d5-knight.  15...Nf6?  doesn't work anymore due to  16.Nb6  Rb8  17.Ne2±  and White is a comfortable pawn up. }
16. Nb6 Nd3+
{ 16...Nb4??  17.Qc3  loses material.   16...Rb8!?  17.Qc3  Qg5  still gives some counterplay, yet it seems that White has a good way of dealing with Black's threats.   16...Re8?  17.Qc3  Kg8  18.Ne2  Rb8  19.O-O  +-  and White has a dominant position. }
17. Bxd3 Qxd3 18. Qc3+ Qxc3+ 19. bxc3 Re8+ 20. Ne2 Rb8 21. f3
{ Stopping ...Bg4. Instead,  21.f4?!  would prevent our ...Re5 manoeuvre but  21...Bg4  forces  22.Ra2  and now both  22...Re3  and  22...Re4  are very annoying. Black is too active, and the f4-pawn is a new addition to White's collection of weak pawns. }
21... Re5 { Black wins back the pawn with a roughly equal position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.9) The Exchange Variation - 6th move alternatives"]
[Black "Exchange - 10.Bf4 Bg7 11.Nd5 e5! 12.Bxe5 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. d4 d6 5. exd6 cxd6
{ In this chapter, we will cover White's main alternatives  6.d5!?  and the very serious  6.a4!?  . After  6.b3?!  g6  7.Bb2  Bg7  we can play similarly to the Exchange Variation, and White will find the bishop on b2 to be misplaced. }
6. a4
{ A line that hasn't been played much, but I expect it to be played a lot more often after this course has been published. After studying the aggressive 4.a4, which is discussed ina later chapter,  I realised that here  6.a4  might be a very serious option for White. For the next couple of moves, Black needs to play very precisely in order not to be overrun. }
6... a5
{ If  6...g6?!  7.a5  N6d7  8.Nf3±  , compared to the normal Exchange Variation, we have no counterplay whatsoever to compensate for White's space advantage. }
7. Nc3 g6 8. c5
{ This move signifies the danger of 6.a4. Without it, it is hard to see what the inclusion of  a4  and  ...a5  has given White, other than a weak b4-square for our knight to occupy. For instance,  8.Be3  Bg7  9.Rc1  O-O  10.b3  Nc6!?  and it's not clear what a4 a5 has gotten White. }
8... dxc5 9. Bb5+ { Played 69 out of 70 times. } 9... N6d7
{ 9...Bd7?  10.dxc5  Nc8  11.Qd4  f6  12.Nf3+-  leaves Black with a cramped position.   9...N8d7??  10.dxc5  and we lose our b6-knight. }
10. Bf4 Bg7
{ 10...cxd4?  offers White a tremendous initiative:  11.Qxd4  hitting the h8-rook and White is already close to winning. }
11. Nd5
{ Threatening a double attack on c7. White needs to be fast. If Black consolidates, the initiative will fizzle out. For instance,  11.Nf3?!  O-O  and White still has to prove the compensation. }
11... e5
{ Giving back the pawn temporarily is the best policy.  11...Na6!?  is a decent alternative, but  11...O-O ?  is not good:  12.Bc7!  Qe8  13.Nb6  and we lose material - the rook has to move, and the d7-knight is pinned, so the b8-knight is doomed. }
12. Bxe5 O-O
{ Not  12...Bxe5?  13.dxe5  O-O  14.f4!  and we can't comfortably untangle due to the hole on f6.  14...Nb6  15.Nf6+  Kg7  16.Nf3±  and White has a big advantage. }
13. Bxg7 { 13.Bc7?!Ν  Qg5  leads to some problems for White. } 13... Kxg7 14.
dxc5 Nc6
{ 14...Re8+?!  places the rook in a pin while White wanted to play  15.Ne2  anyway.   14...Nxc5??  15.Qd4+  loses a piece. }
15. Qc1
{ My suggestion for White to improve over earlier games. The idea is to protect c1 and b2. }
15... Nde5
{ Attacking the d5-knight.  15...Nf6?  doesn't work anymore due to  16.Nb6  Rb8  17.Ne2±  and White is a comfortable pawn up. }
16. Nb6 Nd3+
{ 16...Nb4??  17.Qc3  loses material.   16...Rb8!?  17.Qc3  Qg5  still gives some counterplay, yet it seems that White has a good way of dealing with Black's threats.   16...Re8?  17.Qc3  Kg8  18.Ne2  Rb8  19.O-O  +-  and White has a dominant position. }
17. Bxd3 Qxd3 18. Qe3
{ A position I have given to some students to solve. If you have some time, it might be a good exercise for you as well. White wants to exchange queens and simply be a pawn up. If we retreat the queen, then White has no problems. So, what do we do? }
18... Re8
{ This double rook-sacrifice forces a draw. Instead, after  18...Qxe3+?!  19.fxe3  Rb8  20.Nf3⩲  we still have to get the pawn back somehow. }
19. Qxe8 Be6 { White needs to take the second rook. There is no other option. }
20. Qxa8 { 20.Nxa8  Nd4  is similar. } 20... Nd4
{ Threatening mate with ...Nc2. } 21. f3
{ 21.Rc1  Qe4+  22.Kf1  Qd3+=  is also a perpetual. } 21... Qe3+ 22. Kf1 Qd3+
{ And Black has a perpetual. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.10) The Exchange Variation - without c4 part 1"]
[Black "Exchange - 9.a4!? #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. exd6 cxd6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Bc4
{ A very solid and, in my opinion, underappreciated line. White doesn't play c4 and instead goes for a c3-setup to support the d4-pawn. Play becomes more static instead of the dynamic complications seen in the previous chapters. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. a4
{ White threatens a possible a5 and provides a retreat square for the bishop on b3. This move has not been played too many times, but my engine likes it. }
9... Nc6 { We ignore the a-pawn for now. } 10. a5 { This doesn't help White. }
10... Nd7
{ Not as harmful as it looks, and the White pawn on a5 is now a nice target. }
11. Qd2 { Protecting the a5-pawn. } 11... e5
{ White has lost time with the a4-a5 manoeuvre, and now his pieces are awkwardly placed. Therefore ...e5 offers Black a lot of activity. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.10) The Exchange Variation - without c4 part 1"]
[Black "Exchange - 9.a4!? #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. exd6 cxd6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Bc4
{ A very solid and, in my opinion, underappreciated line. White doesn't play c4 and instead goes for a c3-setup to support the d4-pawn. Play becomes more static instead of the dynamic complications seen in the previous chapters. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. a4
{ White threatens a possible a5 and provides a retreat square for the bishop on b3. This move has not been played too many times, but my engine likes it. }
9... Nc6 { We ignore the a-pawn for now. } 10. a5 { This doesn't help White. }
10... Nd7
{ Not as harmful as it looks, and the White pawn on a5 is now a nice target. }
11. a6 bxa6 12. Re1 Nf6 13. h3 Rb8
{ And we shouldn't be too unhappy. Our knight looks good on f6 and we can continue our development with ...e6 and ...Bb7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.10) The Exchange Variation - without c4 part 1"]
[Black "Exchange - 9.a4!? #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. exd6 cxd6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Bc4
{ A very solid and, in my opinion, underappreciated line. White doesn't play c4 and instead goes for a c3-setup to support the d4-pawn. Play becomes more static instead of the dynamic complications seen in the previous chapters. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. a4
{ White threatens a possible a5 and provides a retreat square for the bishop on b3. This move has not been played too many times, but my engine likes it. }
9... Nc6 { We ignore the a-pawn for now. } 10. h3
{ The threat of a5 is stronger than the execution in this case. } 10... Bd7
{ This is the most useful move here, preparing ...Na5, as after the immediate  10...Na5?!  11.Ba2  unfortunately, Black cannot take the pawn:  11...Nxa4?  12.Bd5!  Black loses material, as the knight on a4 doesn't have a good retreat square.   10...e5?!  This position was reached in the game Firouzja,A @@StartBracket@@2749@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2862@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2021 through a different move order. Now  11.Bg5!  would have been very strong for White. For example,  11...Qc7?!  12.a5  Nd7  13.Nc3!±  or  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3pbp/1nnp2p1/4p1B1/P2P4/1B3N1P/1PP2PP1/RN1Q1RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bf6  12.Bxf6  Qxf6  13.a5  Nd7  14.Nc3!±  and White has the initiative. Black can win a pawn on d4, but it doesn't take long for White to win it back with a much better position. }
11. c3
{ To meet ...Na5 with Bc2. If  11.Re1  Na5  we take the pawn on a4 if White moves his bishop to a2.   White can't exploit our setup with  11.a5  because after  11...Nc8  the a5-pawn is again a target.  12.a6  bxa6  is harmless - our knight can jump back to b6. If  @@StartFEN@@r1nq1rk1/pp1bppbp/2np2p1/P7/3P4/1B3N1P/1PP2PP1/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Qd2  e6  we can eventually regroup our knight via e7. }
11... Na5 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nbd2 Rc8 14. Re1 Bc6
{ With a very decent position for Black. All our pieces are on active squares, and we are very much ready for an ...e5-break. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
