[White "1.10) The Exchange Variation - without c4 part 1"]
[Black "Exchange - 9.c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. exd6 cxd6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Bc4
{ A very solid and, in my opinion, underappreciated line. White doesn't play c4 and instead goes for a c3-setup to support the d4-pawn. Play becomes more static instead of the dynamic complications seen in the previous chapters. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. c3 Nc6
{ This usually transposes to the mainline after White plays Re1 at some point. }
10. Bg5
{ A logical move that deserves a bit of attention.  10.a4  Na5  11.Bc2  Bd7  12.Re1  transposes to9.a4. }
10... h6 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bxg5 { This piece sacrifice is not dangerous. } 12...
hxg5 13. Nxg5 Bf5 { And White has no threats. } *

