[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.10) The Exchange Variation - without c4 part 1"]
[Black "Exchange - 9.Re1 Nc6 10.d5!? #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. exd6 cxd6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Bc4
{ A very solid and, in my opinion, underappreciated line. White doesn't play c4 and instead goes for a c3-setup to support the d4-pawn. Play becomes more static instead of the dynamic complications seen in the previous chapters. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ By far, the main move, putting the rook on the semi-open file.  9.h3!?  Nc6  10.Nc3  Na5  11.Re1  transposes toChapter 1.10. }
9... Nc6 10. d5
{ I recommended this move to a student of mine. I tried to refute this idea over the board, yet I didn't manage to succeed. It took me some home analysis to figure out a good way for Black to play against this line. }
10... Na5
{ 10...Ne5?!  11.Nxe5  Bxe5  12.c3±  gives White a comfortable edge because of the space advantage and the weak black pawn on e7. }
11. c3
{ This position has been reached twice in Grandmaster practice. White's strategy is to create a favourable pawn structure where Black has no chance of counterplay. This is nicely illustrated in the two games played after  11...Nxb3  and  11...Re8  . }
11... a6
{ This little waiting move is my recommendation. Instead,  11...Nxb3?!  12.axb3  h6?!  is kind of useless, as White's main idea is Be3-Bd4.  13.Be3  Re8  Kovchan,A @@StartBracket@@2558@@EndBracket@@-Nevednichy,B @@StartBracket@@2185@@EndBracket@@ Iasi 2014. Now, after  14.Bd4±  , Black struggles to get counterplay as the break ...e5/...e6 leaves a weak pawn on d6 after White captures dxe6. Therefore, White has a solid space advantage.   11...Re8  12.h3  Bf5  13.Na3  Rc8  14.Be3  a6  15.Qd2  Nac4  16.Nxc4  Nxc4  17.Bxc4  Rxc4  18.Bd4±  We are following the game: Yu,Y @@StartBracket@@2675@@EndBracket@@-Ma,Q @@StartBracket@@2559@@EndBracket@@ China 2013. Once again, White has a superior pawn structure and Black struggles to find counterplay. }
12. Be3 Nac4
{ With a double attack on the b2-pawn and the e3-bishop. Black will gladly take that bishop off the board. }
*

