6... Nb6 7. Bb3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ By far, the main move, putting the rook on the semi-open file.  9.h3!?  Nc6  10.Nc3  Na5  11.Re1  transposes toChapter 1.10. }
9... Nc6 10. c3 { Or  10.a4?!  Bg4  11.c3  e5  . } 10... e5
{ The right way to play, in my opinion. White is behind in development, so now is the time to break in the centre. Also note that White isn't able to play Nc3 anymore which would be a great square for the white knight now.   10...Bf5!?  , for example, was played in the game: Grischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2747@@EndBracket@@-Bortnyk,O @@StartBracket@@2579@@EndBracket@@ ICC INT 2016.  11.d5!  Na5  12.Na3Ν  with a similar position to the variationafter 10.d5 - the only difference is that Black has played ...Bf5 and White has played c3. I think c3 is more useful and therefore I'm not recommending 10...Bf5.   10...Na5!?  is also an interesting possibility. }
11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Qxd8
{ If White doesn't exchange, we can simply develop.  12.Na3Ν  Bf5  followed by perhaps ...Na5. }
12... Rxd8 13. Bg5 Rd6
{ 13...Re8  and  13...Rd7  are fine too. I prefer ...Rd6 for two reasons: to keep the rook on the d-file and to be able to develop the c8-bishop quickly. }
14. Nbd2 { 14.Na3  Bf5  . } 14... Bf5 15. Ne4 Bxe4 16. Rxe4 Na5
{ And Black has good play. The pawn on e5 can't be taken, and if the bishop moves to c2, then Black can play ...f5 and ...Na5-...Nb6/...Nc4, two very active moves that will cause White problems. }
17. Nxe5 Nxb3 18. axb3 f6 { Black wins a piece. } *

