{ An interesting setup which has been played by Grischuk. The idea is to prevent ...Bg4 and therefore allow the b1-knight to develop to c3. }
10... Na5
{ The one downside of 10.h3 is that Black can exchange the b3-bishop. You might notice that I'm trying to avoid  10...Bf5!?  in many lines. In many cases, this is a very decent move nonetheless.The reason why I avoid it is because I think other moves serve more of a purpose and a long-term plan, as the f5-bishop can be kicked away in multiple ways.  11.Nc3  Rc8  12.Bg5  h6  13.Be3  d5  14.Ne2  This was fairly easy to play for White in the game Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2670@@EndBracket@@-Timman,J  @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@ Linares 1992. The bishop on f5 feels a bit awkward to me and White's plan is to play Ng3 followed by c3-Bc2.   10...e5?  is not the right move this time.  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.Nc3!±  With this clever move order, White has solved one of the big problems inChapter 1.9, the knight on b1, which is now very active. }
