{ One of two ways for White to win the pawn.  15.Bxc4!?  Nxc4  16.b3  Na5  17.Rxe7  Otherwise, Black plays ...Be6.  17...Rxe7  18.Bxe7  Nc6  19.Bxd6  Nxd4  20.Nxd4  Bxd4  21.c3  Bg7  22.Bb4  Be6=∞  With typical compensation - two bishops versus being a pawn down. Black should be fine here. }
15... Nc6 { Attacking the bishop on a4. } 16. Nc3 h6 17. Bc1 Be6
{ This is absolutely fine for Black, as  18.d5  can be met with  18...Bxc3  and ...Bxd5 winning a pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.11) The Exchange Variation - without c4 part 2"]
[Black "Exchange - 11.Bg5 Re8 12.Qd2!? Nbc4 13.Qb4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. exd6 cxd6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Bc4 Nb6 7. Bb3 Bg7 8.
O-O O-O 9. Re1 Nc6 10. h3
{ An interesting setup which has been played by Grischuk. The idea is to prevent ...Bg4 and therefore allow the b1-knight to develop to c3. }
10... Na5
{ The one downside of 10.h3 is that Black can exchange the b3-bishop. You might notice that I'm trying to avoid  10...Bf5!?  in many lines. In many cases, this is a very decent move nonetheless.The reason why I avoid it is because I think other moves serve more of a purpose and a long-term plan, as the f5-bishop can be kicked away in multiple ways.  11.Nc3  Rc8  12.Bg5  h6  13.Be3  d5  14.Ne2  This was fairly easy to play for White in the game Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2670@@EndBracket@@-Timman,J  @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@ Linares 1992. The bishop on f5 feels a bit awkward to me and White's plan is to play Ng3 followed by c3-Bc2.   10...e5?  is not the right move this time.  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.Nc3!±  With this clever move order, White has solved one of the big problems inChapter 1.9, the knight on b1, which is now very active. }
11. Bg5 { The mainline.  11.Nc3  Re8  12.Bg5  should transpose to 11.Bg5. }
11... Re8 12. Qd2
{ This has only been played once. White is trying to force the trade on b3, activating his rook on a1 and keeping the option open to still play Nc3. The Nc3-idea is quite annoying here and we have to find a plan other than ...e5. }
12... Nbc4
{ With this move we have an active idea in ...b5 and ...Bb7.  12...Nac4!?  is a decent alternative, but once again after  13.Qc1  I struggle to find an active plan for Black. White will play a4-a5 and Nc3 with a very easy position to play.   12...Nxb3?!  13.axb3±  is very pleasant for White and Black will struggle to find an active plan. }
13. Qb4
{ 13.Qc1?!  b5!  illustrates why we played the b6-knight to c4. Black can put the bishop on b7, which leads to active possibilities. The text stops ...b5. }
13... Qb6 14. Qxb6 axb6
{ This trade has spoilt our structure, but we get some active ideas on the queenside. }
15. Ba4
{ One of two ways for White to win the pawn.  15.Bxc4!?  Nxc4  16.b3  Na5  17.Rxe7  Otherwise, Black plays ...Be6.  17...Rxe7  18.Bxe7  Nc6  19.Bxd6  Nxd4  20.Nxd4  Bxd4  21.c3  Bg7  22.Bb4  Be6=∞  With typical compensation - two bishops versus being a pawn down. Black should be fine here. }
15... Nc6 { Attacking the bishop on a4. } 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. b3
{ White saves the b-pawn. } 17... Na5 18. Rxe7 Rxe7 19. Bxe7 Bf5
{ Once again, we have compensation for the pawn. } *

