1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. exd6 cxd6 5. Nf3 g6
{ In this chapter, we are going to have a look at rare 6th move alternatives for White. Keep in mind that most of these lines haven't really been tried in practice yet. White almost always goes forthe 6.Bc4 Variation. }
6. Bb5+
{ The idea of this move is to get the bishop out as soon as possible in order to follow up with c4. }
6... Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. O-O Bg7 9. c4
{ 9.c3?!  does not make sense here. The fight is taking place on the light squares. }
9... Nc7
{ Now that there are hardly any tactics involved, it is best to put the knight on c7, where it supports the potential ...d5 and ...b5 breaks.   In case of  9...Nb6?!  10.b3  , the knight is misplaced on b6. }
10. Nc3 O-O 11. Re1 Re8 { To protect the pawn on e7 and prepare ...d5. } 12.
Bg5 { 12.Be3  d5!  is absolutely fine for Black. } 12... d5
{ This loses a pawn, but only temporarily. } 13. c5 Nc6
{ This is once again fine for Black. } *

