1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. exd6 cxd6 5. Nf3 g6
{ In this chapter, we are going to have a look at rare 6th move alternatives for White. Keep in mind that most of these lines haven't really been tried in practice yet. White almost always goes forthe 6.Bc4 Variation. }
6. Be2
{ This transposes very often to the chapters where White plays with c4. } 6...
Bg7 7. O-O O-O
{ Usually White transposes to the lines with c4 after  8.c4  , as other moves don't make too much sense. }
8. Re1
{ The only move with some independent value. If Black now plays  8...Nc6  without too much thought, then White will kick the knight away with c4 and d5, with a good position. }
8... Nc7
{ Anticipating c4 and preparing for ...e5. I like this idea a lot.   An interestingalternative is  8...e5!?  .   Worse is  8...Nc6?  9.c4!  Nb6  10.d5  Ne5   @@StartBracket@@  10...Na5?  11.Na3!  is very bad for Black - the knight on a5 is awfully misplaced.@@EndBracket@@  11.Nxe5  Bxe5  We have seen this type of pawn structure before. Now White's plan is to develop quickly and anticipate Black's ...e6-break. For example:  12.a4!  A useful move, and now:A@@EndBracket@@  12...e6?  13.a5  Nd7  14.dxe6  fxe6+-  And White has a big advantage already.B  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2pp1p/1n1p2p1/3Pb3/P1P5/8/1P2BPPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nd7?!  13.Ra2!  ±  Followed by b4, and we will have trouble regaining our activity.C@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2pp1p/1n1p2p1/3Pb3/P1P5/8/1P2BPPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...a5  13.Nc3  e6  Trying to break free.  14.Be3  exd5  15.cxd5  Nd7  16.Bb5±  And White's pieces are way more active than Black's. }
9. Nc3 e5
{ Sponsored by our knight on c7, which makes sure the c3-knight isn't free to move actively. }
10. Bg5 { Provoking Black into playing ...f6. } 10... f6
{ Unfortunately, we have to. } 11. Be3 Nc6 12. Bc4+
{ This looks dangerous, but it's not all that bad. } 12... Kh8
{ 12...d5?  13.Bb3  And the d5-pawn is hard to defend. } 13. Qd2 d5 14. Bb3 e4
{ And White loses the knight. } *

