[Black "Exchange - Alternative to 8...Nc7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. exd6 cxd6 5. Nf3 g6
{ In this chapter, we are going to have a look at rare 6th move alternatives for White. Keep in mind that most of these lines haven't really been tried in practice yet. White almost always goes forthe 6.Bc4 Variation. }
6. Be2
{ This transposes very often to the chapters where White plays with c4. } 6...
Bg7 7. O-O O-O
{ Usually White transposes to the lines with c4 after  8.c4  , as other moves don't make too much sense. }
8. Re1
{ The only move with some independent value. If Black now plays  8...Nc6  without too much thought, then White will kick the knight away with c4 and d5, with a good position. }
8... e5
{ This is still interesting, although this time it entails a pawn sacrifice. My recommendation is the novelty  8...Nc7  . }
9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Nxe5 Re8
{ 10...Bxe5  11.Bf3!  is White's point. White wins back the pawn as  11...Bxh2  would be a positional disaster for Black, leaving the dark squares exposed. }
11. Nf3 Nc6 { And Black has decent compensation for the pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.1) The Four Pawns Attack - Part 1"]
[Black "Four Pawns - The Classical 5...dxe5 & 9...Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ 5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  takes us to theClassic with 6.c4. } 5... dxe5
{ The classical way to play. Unfortunately, I think that all the lines here have been studied too much, and White gets an advantage too easily. }
6. fxe5 Bf5
{ 6...Nc6  is a different move order.  7.Nf3?!  Bg4!  pinning the knight and undermining the centre, but  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp1pppp/1nn5/4P3/2PP4/8/PP4PP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be3!  Bf5  8.Nc3  e6  9.Nf3  transposes to the mainline.   6...c5?  involves a trick. If White doesn't fall for it, Black is kind of screwed.  7.d5  e6  8.Nc3   @@StartBracket@@  8.d6??  Qh4+  is the trick - Black wins material.  @@EndBracket@@  8...exd5  9.cxd5  c4  Black wants to play ...Bb4 and, after White plays Nf3, also ...Bg4.  10.d6!  disrupts Black's play entirely, unfortunately. White almost has a winning advantage.  10.Nf3  is not as strong but also secures White a large advantage. }
7. Nc3 e6 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Be3 Be7
{ The classic line. I played  9...Bg4?!  a lot in my early teens. Unfortunately, it doesn't work either.  10.Be2  Bxf3  11.gxf3  Qh4+  12.Bf2  Qf4  13.c5±  White has zero problems, the bishop pair and a lot of extra space.   I was slightly tempted to recommend  9...Bb4  because it has been played a few times with good results. Unfortunately, I also think this line is not complicated enough.  10.Be2  Na5!?  and if  11.O-O?!  Black can actually take the pawn:  11...Naxc4  12.Bxc4  Nxc4  13.Qa4+  Qd7  14.Qxb4  Nxe3  15.Qxb7  O-O  With good play for Black, thanks to our active pieces.The problem is  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp2ppp/1n2p3/n3Pb2/1bPP4/2N1BN2/PP2B1PP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.c5  Nd5  12.Bd2±  Once again, White have zero problems and a clear advantage thanks to enjoying more space. }
10. Be2
{ 10.d5  has been played more than 10.Be2, yet I think it is worse.  10...exd5  11.cxd5  Nb4  12.Nd4  Bd7!  threatening to win the pawn on d5 and preventing White from checking with Bb5.  13.e6  The best move.  13...fxe6  14.dxe6  Bc6  and Black's position was very close to equal in the game: Grischuk,A  (2748)  -Svidler,P  (2726)  Odessa 2009, where Black went on to win. }
10... O-O 11. O-O f6 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Qd2 Qe7 14. Rad1 Rad8
{ The most played line against the Four Pawns Attack. White has a significant advantage, and Black's only active idea is to play ...e5 at some point. I wanted to recommend this, but it's hard to play active. Since this line has been played very often, I don't see much practical value either. Here is a good example, between two of America's strongest players, of how Black can easily get outplayed. }
15. Kh1 h6 16. h3
{ White has no rush. Therefore, making slight improvements is fine. } 16... Rd7
17. Qc1 Re8 18. Rd2 Qd8 19. Rfd1 Kh8 20. b3 Bh7 21. Bg1
{ White has played a lot of prophylactic moves to prevent Black from getting ...e5 comfortably. }
21... Nc8
{ And Black collapsed due to the lack of activity. Relocating the knight would be good, but unfortunately, Black doesn't have the time for it. }
22. d5 exd5 23. Nxd5
{ And White went on to win the game convincingly. Robson,R @@StartBracket@@2669@@EndBracket@@-Naroditsky,D @@StartBracket@@2623@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2021. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.1) The Four Pawns Attack - Part 1"]
[Black "Four Pawns - 9.c5?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ 5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  takes us to theClassic with 6.c4. } 5... g6
{ A line that Magnus Carlsen more or less re-introduced in rapid online games. The idea is to develop our dark-squared bishop to g7, followed by short castle. This line is relatively new; therefore, all the analysis here is fresh, with lots of novelties and new ideas. Because of its freshness and complicated positions, I chose this line as my recommendation. White needs to make some difficult decisions, and even if White manages to get a clear advantage, we can still pose problems. }
6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3
{ Connecting the queen on  d1  with the rook on  a1  . For  7.Nf3?!  seeChapter 2.3. }
7... Be6
{ My recommendation, played by Magnus Carlsen in a Chess24 online rapid game. The idea is to provoke d5 and start undermining White's centre.   7...O-O?!  8.c5!  Very strong and good because White has connected the queen on d1 with the a1-rook, meaning that if we take on c5 and then exchange the queen on d1, White has control over the d-file and pushing the b6-knight even further back comes without a drawback. We want to avoid this.   7...dxe5?!  8.dxe5!  Once again possible due to the queen being protected by the rook.  8...Qxd1+  9.Rxd1±  White has more space and active pieces - a typical position we want to avoid. }
8. d5
{ The move we will cover here. White pushes the e6-bishop back with tempo. For  8.Nf3  seeChapter 2.2. }
8... Bc8
{ Black gave two tempi to provoke White to play d5 and will now start undermining the centre. }
9. c5 { This only helps black. } 9... N6d7
{ Taking on c5 is what White wants; keeping pressure on the e5-pawn is more principled. }
10. cxd6 exd6 11. e6
{ We are following a game where White tried to push his pawns too far and eventually lost this pawn.  11.exd6?!  cxd6  . }
11... fxe6 12. dxe6 Nf6 13. Qb3 Qe7 14. O-O-O Qxe6
{ Securing the queen trade. } 15. Qxe6+ Bxe6
{ And Black was a full pawn up in the game: Arribas Lopez,A @@StartBracket@@2334@@EndBracket@@-Navarro Cia,M @@StartBracket@@2318@@EndBracket@@ Pamplona 2008. }
*

