11... N6d7
{ This was my second choice besides11...dxe5.   11...Bg4  runs into  12.e6!  The best move and what disappointed me, since I had faith in the other variations here. The e6 thrust is a typical idea, not that hard to find; therefore, I didn't want to recommend this even from a practical standpoint. For example:A@@EndBracket@@  12...Bxf3  13.exf7+  Rxf7  14.Rxf3  N8d7  15.Ne4!  threatening Ng5-e6 with a big initiative for White.B@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp2ppbp/1nppP1p1/3P4/2P2Pb1/2N1BN2/PP2B1PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...fxe6  13.Ng5!  The knight is trying to access e6. I analysed this line quite thoroughly, but in the end, I concluded that White was having all the fun. }
12. Bd4
{ Leela's recommendation, but there are many pleasant options for White:   12.exd6  exd6  13.f5!±  with initiative for White.   12.e6?!  fxe6  13.dxe6  Nf6?!  14.Ng5  is just horrible for Black. Instead, after  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp1np1bp/2ppP1p1/8/2P2P2/2N1BN2/PP2B1PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nc5  White needs to make a concession; otherwise, the pawn on e6 will be lost without anything in return.  14.Bxc5  dxc5  15.Qe1!  Bxe6  16.Rd1  Qc8  17.Ng5±  White has the initiative, but certainly the strong and uncontested g7-bishop is an asset for Black. }
12... c5
{ Or  12...cxd5  13.cxd5  dxe5  14.fxe5±  and I struggled to find active ideas for Black. }
13. Bf2 dxe5 14. fxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxc5 Nxf3+ 16. Rxf3
{ This is just clearly better for White. White has the more active pieces and a superior pawn structure. }
