[White "2.1) The Four Pawns Attack - Part 1"]
[Black "Four Pawns - Main line 14.Qd4!? #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ 5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  takes us to theClassic with 6.c4. } 5... g6
{ A line that Magnus Carlsen more or less re-introduced in rapid online games. The idea is to develop our dark-squared bishop to g7, followed by short castle. This line is relatively new; therefore, all the analysis here is fresh, with lots of novelties and new ideas. Because of its freshness and complicated positions, I chose this line as my recommendation. White needs to make some difficult decisions, and even if White manages to get a clear advantage, we can still pose problems. }
6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3
{ Connecting the queen on  d1  with the rook on  a1  . For  7.Nf3?!  seeChapter 2.3. }
7... Be6
{ My recommendation, played by Magnus Carlsen in a Chess24 online rapid game. The idea is to provoke d5 and start undermining White's centre.   7...O-O?!  8.c5!  Very strong and good because White has connected the queen on d1 with the a1-rook, meaning that if we take on c5 and then exchange the queen on d1, White has control over the d-file and pushing the b6-knight even further back comes without a drawback. We want to avoid this.   7...dxe5?!  8.dxe5!  Once again possible due to the queen being protected by the rook.  8...Qxd1+  9.Rxd1±  White has more space and active pieces - a typical position we want to avoid. }
8. d5
{ The move we will cover here. White pushes the e6-bishop back with tempo. For  8.Nf3  seeChapter 2.2. }
8... Bc8
{ Black gave two tempi to provoke White to play d5 and will now start undermining the centre. }
9. Nf3
{ Developing and defending the pawn on e5. One of White's strategies is to keep the black bishop on g7 as restricted as possible. }
9... c6
{ We want to undermine the d5-pawn as soon as possible.   9...O-O  10.Be2  Bg4  would be a bluff, just as9...Bg4. We aren't exactly threatening to win the e5-pawn. We do, but White gets great compensation in return for it:  11.O-O!  Bxf3  12.Rxf3  dxe5  13.f5→  with fantastic compensation for the pawn. }
10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O
{ This is more or less the critical position of the 8.d5 line. I let the computer run for a few hours to see what it would come up with. The computer evaluation is around +1 here for White, which is similar to the best lines for White in all the alternatives that I have shown. }
11... dxe5
{ A novelty. In my view, the move that gives White the most trouble. In the classical spirit of this opening, we are trying to undermine White's centre and see if our pressure can be dealt with. }
12. fxe5 cxd5 13. cxd5
{ 13.Nxd5?  isolates the e5-pawn.  13...Nc6⇆  and White has problems. } 13...
Bg4
{ Compared to9...Bg4, we have traded off the c-pawns, which greatly weakens White's pawn centre. White has two main options here.   Note that defending the e5-pawn with  14.Bd4?  drops the d5-pawn  14...Nxd5  . }
14. Qd4 { Attacking the bishop. } 14... Bxf3 15. Rxf3 e6
{ Undermining White's centre and preventing the Qh4+Rh3 idea.  15...N8d7?  16.Qh4!!  A wonderful move that overwhelms us on the kingside.  16...Nxe5  17.Rh3  h5  18.Bxh5+-  and White has a crushing mating attack. }
16. dxe6 fxe6 17. Rxf8+ Qxf8 18. Rf1 Qe7
{ The position has cleared somewhat, and now we complete our development. } 19.
Qd6
{ We don't want to exchange queens on d6. That would expose our e6-pawn, and it would be hard to attack the white pawn on d6. }
19... Nc6 20. Bg4 Re8 21. Bc5 { Now we must decide what to do. } 21... Qg5
{ We need to stay active. } 22. Bxe6+ Kh8
{ Threatening to win the pawn back on e5 with tempo. } *

