Bg4
{ Compared to9...Bg4, we have traded off the c-pawns, which greatly weakens White's pawn centre. White has two main options here.   Note that defending the e5-pawn with  14.Bd4?  drops the d5-pawn  14...Nxd5  . }
14. e6
{ A very strong thrust, grabbing the initiative. I do think this move is hard to find over the board, and it very often leads to a long-term pawn sacrifice. Black needs to be quite careful for the next moves. }
14... Bxf3
{ Taking the dangerous knight off the board.  14...fxe6?  is a mistake. White will get tremendous pressure here.  15.Ng5!  Aiming for the e6-square and exchanging the bishop. For example:  15...Rxf1+  16.Qxf1  Bxe2  17.Qxe2  exd5  18.Ne6  Qd7  19.Nxg7  Kxg7  20.Bd4+  Kg8  21.Qe5  and Black can resign due to the mating attack. }
15. Bxf3
{ Now Black can take on e6 as there are no longer knight jumps to g5. } 15...
fxe6 16. dxe6
{ Covering the e6-square is not in White's interest. White should keep the door open to checks on the a2-g8 diagonal. }
16... Nc6 { We have completed our development and have nothing to fear. } *

