1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ 5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  takes us to theClassic with 6.c4. } 5... g6 6. Nc3
Bg7 7. Be3 Be6 8. Be2 { This gives us an opportunity. } 8... Nxc4
{ White was playing for the Qa4 double attack, but that doesn't win a piece.  8...O-O?!  9.b3  transposes to8.b3. }
9. Bxc4
{ 9.Qa4+??  b5!  10.Qxb5+  c6  and we attack both the white queen and the e3-bishop. White will lose material. }
9... Bxc4 10. Qa4+ b5
{ Again, this is our defensive resource. We give back the pawn. } 11. Nxb5 Bxb5
12. Qxb5+ Nd7
{ With a roughly equal position. We have less space but have exchanged some minor pieces, so that space advantage isn't such a big deal. For example,  13.Nf3  O-O  14.O-O  e6  15.Rfc1  Nb6=  followed by ...Nd5 and we have no problems. }
