1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ 5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  takes us to theClassic with 6.c4. } 5... g6 6. Nc3
Bg7 7. Be3 Be6 8. Rc1
{ Sebastian Mikhajlov's recommendation in his Energetic 1.e4 course here on Chessable. Also, a very interesting move and not yet played by a top GM, according to my database. The idea is similar to8.b3, yet White postpones that move for now because the c4-pawn is tactically defended.   8...Nxc4?!  is worse without a previous exchange on e5:  9.Bxc4?!  Bxc4  10.Qa4+  b5  11.Nxb5  Bxb5  12.Qxb5+  Nd7  is actually decent for Black - a better version of the mainlineafter 8...dxe5, as now our c-pawn isn't isolated, which could work in our favour. However, the problem is  @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp1ppbp/3pb1p1/4P3/2nP1P2/2N1B3/PP4PP/2RQKBNR w Kkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Qa4+  and now:A@@EndBracket@@  9...b5  10.Nxb5  Nxe3  11.Nxc7+  Kf8  12.Nxa8  and we no longer have the ...Bh6 resource and, therefore, our compensation is insufficient, and White is close to winning.B@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp1ppbp/3pb1p1/4P3/Q1nP1P2/2N1B3/PP4PP/2R1KBNR b Kkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qd7  10.Bxc4  Qxa4  11.Nxa4  Bxc4  12.Rxc4  b5  winning back the piece with the fork.  13.Rxc7  Na6  Not allowing Rc8.  14.Rc1  bxa4  15.Rc4!±  ensuring that White will be a pawn up in the ending. White still has to convert this into a win, but with the active rook on c4, I feel it's easier than8...dxe5. }
8... dxe5 { 8...O-O  is an interestingalternative. } 9. fxe5 Nxc4
{ I think this is a decent option. White has this pawn tactically defended, so we are not winning a pawn.  9...c5  10.d5!  Bc8  11.Nf3±  or  @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/pp2ppbp/1n2b1p1/2pPP3/2P5/2N1B3/PP4PP/2RQKBNR b Kkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bf5  11.Be2  and we have no better move than  11...O-O  , transposing once again to8.b3 O-O.   9...O-O  10.b3  c5  transposes to8...O-O. }
10. Qa4+ { This doesn't work for White. } 10... b5 { The typical resource. }
11. Nxb5 Nxe3 12. Nxc7+ Kf8 13. Nxa8 Bh6
{ An amazing move. White is actually in deep trouble. For example: } 14. Ne2
{ Defending the c1-rook.  14.Nc7  Nxf1  and we win back the piece. } 14... Nxf1
15. Rxf1 Bxc1 16. Nxc1 Qc8 { Winning a tempo to trap the cornered knight. } 17.
Ne2 Qb7 { And we win a piece because the knight is trapped on a8. } *

