{ I think this is a decent option. White has this pawn tactically defended, so we are not winning a pawn.  9...c5  10.d5!  Bc8  11.Nf3±  or  @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/pp2ppbp/1n2b1p1/2pPP3/2P5/2N1B3/PP4PP/2RQKBNR b Kkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bf5  11.Be2  and we have no better move than  11...O-O  , transposing once again to8.b3 O-O.   9...O-O  10.b3  c5  transposes to8...O-O. }
10. Bxc4 { This is safer. } 10... Bxc4 11. Qa4+ b5
{ The only way to save our piece. } 12. Nxb5 Bxb5 13. Qxb5+ Nd7
{ Completing our development. } 14. Nf3 O-O 15. O-O Nb6
{ White's position is better, as our c7-pawn is very vulnerable. However, I also think it is tough for White to convert this into a win - our knight is excellently placed on d5. In some scenarios, we can even give up the c-pawn - the knight on d5 will give us enough compensation. There is no clear way to win for White. Basically, it requires technique, which is one of the hardest skills to learn in chess.A sample continuation is  16.b3  making sure the pawn cannot be attacked along the b-file.  16...Nd5  17.Bd2  e6  18.Rc5  h6  denying the g5-square to White's minor pieces.  19.h3  Re8  followed by ...Bf8 with a solid position, or  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/p1p2pb1/4p1pp/1QRnP3/3P4/1P3N2/P2B2PP/5RK1 w - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Qc4  Qd7  and again, we have a very solid position. In the long term, we want to play ...a5 and ...a4 to get some counterplay on the queenside. If White prevents that, we need to stay solid and play around with our pieces. We shouldn't try to push ...f6 here - that only makes things easier for White. }
