Bg7 7. Be3 Be6 8. b3
{ Recently played by Bulgarian top GM Veselin Topalov, and also suggested by Dutch top GM Anish Giri in his recent Chessable LTR: 1.e4 part 2. This move has a subtle point: White aims to get a better version of the Caruana-Carlsen game discussedunder 8.Nf3. First of all, by postponing Nf3, and secondly, by means of a dangerous pawn sacrifice. }
8... dxe5
{ Suggested by one of the beta testers from the Chessable community as an improvement, to which I agreed.  8...O-O?!  9.Be2!  is an excellent prophylaxis by White. The point is to deny us the pin on an f3-knight. Compare this line to  @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp1ppbp/1n1pb1p1/4P3/2PP1P2/2N1B3/PP4PP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nf3  O-O  9.b3  dxe5  10.fxe5?!  , coveredhere, where Black is not worse at all.After  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/ppp1ppbp/1n1pb1p1/4P3/2PP1P2/1PN1B3/P3B1PP/R2QK1NR b KQ - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...dxe5  10.fxe5!  c5  this seems wonderful for Black - there is no knight on f3 protecting the e5-pawn.  11.d5!  Yet White simply doesn't care about it.  11...Bxe5  and now both  12.Qd2!?  and  12.Rc1  Bf5  are good and lead to similar conclusions. If we could pin a knight on f3, we would have an easier time.  13.Nf3+-  White is going to enjoy some fantastic play on the kingside, and that is well worth a pawn. }
9. fxe5
{ White's only good option is to sacrifice the e-pawn.  9.dxe5?!  Nc6  and play will most likely become similar to the 8.Nf3 mainline. For example,  10.Nf3  f6!⇆  Breaking in the centre quickly with good counterplay along the h8-a1 diagonal, followed by ...O-O, and  10...O-O  transposes tothis line. }
9... c5
{ Forcing White's hand, as after  10.Nf3?  cxd4  White will not be able to hold on to the e5-pawn anyways.   10.dxc5?  runs into  10...N6d7  11.Rc1  Nc6-+  Next, we will take on e5 and have a fantastic position due to our development and active pieces. }
10. d5 Bf5
{ Taking the e5-pawn is a trap. We do want to take it, but ideally with our knight to get a smoother development.  10...Bxe5?  11.Qd2  Bf5  12.Nf3!  and White gets an excellent development in return for the pawn.  12...Bd6  Otherwise, we lose the c5-pawn.  13.Bd3  This position was reached in the correspondence game Rosenlechner,G @@StartBracket@@2006@@EndBracket@@-Soar,T @@StartBracket@@1610@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2021.  13...Bxd3  14.Qxd3  N8d7  15.O-O±  followed by Rae1 and Bh6, and White will soon pile up some pressure on the kingside. }
11. Be2 { Once again, this move is clever. We can't develop our knight to d7. }
11... Bxe5
{ Unfortunately, we have no choice.  11...N8d7?  12.g4!  and our bishop is trapped on f5. }
12. Qd2
{ If  12.Rc1  we can go  12...Na6  to cover the c-pawn and continue development with ...O-O next. }
12... N8d7
{ The difference between this line and8...O-O is visible again. If I had the choice, I would always play ...N8d7 here instead of ...O-O. }
13. Rd1
{ Played in a correspondence game. White is threatening to win material with g4. Normal development with  13.Nf3  is harmless.  13...Bf6  Not allowing any Nh4 ideas.  14.O-O  Nc8!  An instructive move. Our knight wasn't doing much on b6 - on d6, the knight will be well-positioned. }
13... h5 { Preventing White's g4. } 14. Nf3 Bg7
{ My improvement over a correspondence game.  14...Bf6?!  only helps White:  15.Bd3  Bxd3  16.Qxd3  Nc8  17.Ne4  Nd6  18.O-O  Having our bishop on f6 makes things a bit more awkward for Black. For example,  18...Qb6  19.Nxd6+!  exd6  20.Qe4++-  and compared to the text, we are in dire straits because on f6 our bishop is a liability after  20...Ne5  . Or  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1npp2/3n1bp1/2pP3p/2P1N3/1P1QBN2/P5PP/3R1RK1 b kq - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Nf5  19.h3!  A great move which that prepares a kingside attack. If now  19...Nxe3  20.Qxe3  O-O  21.g4!  hxg4  22.hxg4  Bg7  23.Nfg5+-  we are not in time to defend against White's attack - Qh3-Qh7 is a lethal threat.The game went  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1npp2/5bp1/2pP1n1p/2P1N3/1P1QBN1P/P5P1/3R1RK1 b kq - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Qb6  20.Rfe1  Bg7  and Black felt the need to put the bishop on g7 anyways. After a complicated battle, White went on the win in Binas,J @@StartBracket@@2450@@EndBracket@@-Schmidt,L @@StartBracket@@2408@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018. }
15. Nh4 e6 { This move makes the exchange on f5 not so bad. } 16. Nxf5 exf5
{ And our kingside is very hard to break through. White now needs to find other means to keep the initiative going. For example: }
17. O-O O-O 18. d6 a6
{ Preventing Nb5 the position is less threatening for us. } *

