15... Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Nc8 { The knight needs to go to d6 as soon as possible. }
17. O-O
{ 17.Ne4  Nd6  18.O-O  should transpose.  18.Nxd6+?!  exd6  19.O-O  O-O⩱  leads White nowhere. The c5-pawn is off-limits:  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1nppb1/3n2p1/2pP3p/2P1N3/1P1QBN2/P5PP/3RK2R w Kkq - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Nxc5??  Qa5+-+  drops a piece. }
17... Nd6 18. Ne4
{ White's best option. The knight needs to get into the game. } 18... Qb6
{ Protecting the c5-pawn. It's not our only move, but it does keep a bunch of options open. The engine thinks White has a clear advantage, but a human needs to take into account many defensive resources for Black.  18...Nf5!?  is the main alternative and  18...O-O?!  19.Nxc5±  drops the pawn. }
19. Nxd6+ exd6 20. Qe4+
{ This check seems unpleasant, yet we have a good defence. } 20... Ne5 21. Nxe5
Bxe5 22. Bf4 f5 { And White will not win the pawn back. } 23. Qe3
{ Funnily enough,  23.Qf3  is the best choice.  23...O-O-O  24.Rfe1  Rhe8  and White has good compensation for the pawn.  25.Qg3=∞  can put some pressure on our weaknesses, which makes this position roughly equal. Trading bishops and ...Qb4 is an idea. }
23... Kf7 24. Bxe5 Rae8
{ And we can start playing for the win, as we will emerge a pawn up! } *

