[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.2) The Four Pawns Attack - Part 2"]
[Black "Four Pawns - 8.Nf3?! O-O 9.d5?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ 5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  takes us to theClassic with 6.c4. } 5... g6 6. Nc3
Bg7 7. Be3 Be6 8. Nf3
{ What Caruana played against Carlsen in the rapid gameI mentioned in the previous chapter. In my opinion, this is clearly worse than the  8.d5  line covered there. White does not want to overextend the centre and instead tries to play solidly. It is pretty slow, though, and Black should go for quick development and an early break in the centre. }
8... O-O
{ 8...Bxc4??  9.Bxc4  Nxc4  10.Qa4+  and White wins the knight.   8...Nxc4?  9.Bxc4  Bxc4  10.Qa4+  b5  11.Nxb5  Bxb5  12.Qxb5+±  and White is much better, with more space and a clear target on c7 to play against. }
9. d5 { This does not make sense now. } 9... Bg4
{ Undermining White's centre very quickly. In the previous chapter, I showed some lines where we played ...Bg4 being a tempo down. I refer you tothose lines if you want to have a feel for how to play with it. }
*

