{ Instead,  15...fxe6!?  16.g3  gives White good compensation for the pawn. With the text, we can still exploit the white queen's vulnerability. }
16. Bxc4 Nxc4 17. Qe4 Nd6
{ Black has won a pawn and can start attacking on the queenside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.3) The Four Pawns Attack - Early Deviations"]
[Black "Four Pawns - 9.d5 - 11.h3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ 5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  takes us to theClassic with 6.c4. } 5... g6
{ In this chapter of sidelines, we are taking a look at different move orders from White. A general tip is that when White doesn't play themain line with Nc3 and Be3, Black should take on e5. }
6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 { Not an accurate move order. } 7... dxe5 8. fxe5 c5 9. d5
{ White's main reaction. } 9... Bg4 { Putting pressure on the e5-pawn. } 10.
Bf4 { Protecting the pawn. } 10... O-O 11. h3
{ There isn't another useful move for White. } 11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 N8d7 13. Qe4
{ Strangely enough, a novelty, yet the best position for the queen. } 13... Qb8
14. e6
{ Play becomes similar to certain lines in Chapter 2.1. Yet this version is a lot worse for White. In comparison, Black has much more development and tactics for White to worry about.  14.O-O-O?  Bxe5∓  and Black wins a pawn. }
14... Ne5
{ Stronger than  14...Be5?  15.Bxe5  Nxe5  16.O-O-O  fxe6  17.Re1  Nf7  18.Qxe6±  and White has a huge structural advantage. }
15. O-O-O f5
{ The queen has no good square, so White will have to give up the bishop pair.  15...fxe6?!  16.Kb1!  exd5  17.Nxd5±  Black has trouble with the pin. }
16. Qe3 Nexc4 { Black wins a pawn. } *

