[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) The sneaky 4.f4"]
[Black "The sneaky 4.f4 - 5.dxe5?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. f4
{ White is trying to make use of postponing c4, which offers some extra options in certain situations. I am calling it 'sneaky' because in blitz games, very often, Black pre-moves ...Nd5-b6 in anticipation of  4.c4  or  4.Bc4  .   However,  4.f4  isn't very good in itself. Black has a clear way of dealing with it. }
4... dxe5 5. dxe5
{ This is totally inconsistent with 4.f4. The principled recapture, andWhite's main move in this chapter, is  5.fxe5  . }
5... Bf5
{ We now have an easy time to develop, and White needs to watch out for ...Nb4 ideas. For example: }
6. c4 Nb4 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Na3 e6
{ And Black is much better - we can put our king very nicely on c7 after playing ...c6 and ...Nd7. }
*

