{ White is trying to make use of postponing c4, which offers some extra options in certain situations. I am calling it 'sneaky' because in blitz games, very often, Black pre-moves ...Nd5-b6 in anticipation of  4.c4  or  4.Bc4  .   However,  4.f4  isn't very good in itself. Black has a clear way of dealing with it. }
4... dxe5 5. fxe5 c5
{ Attacking the centre.  5...Bf5  is a good alternative.  6.Nf3  e6  and after  7.c4?  Nb4!  8.Na3  Be7∓  the b4-knight is very strong - at some point, Black can grab the initiative with ...c5. If  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3nPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP3PP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  Bxd3  8.Qxd3  c5!  once again, Black is very comfortable. }
6. dxc5 Bf5 7. Nf3
{ If  7.c4?  Nb4  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  9.Na3  e6∓  despite our king no longer able to castle, we once again will have a much easier time developing. For example,  10.Bg5+  Be7  11.Rd1+  Nd7  12.Nf3  a6  to prevent Nb5  13.Be2  Ke8  14.O-O  Nxc5∓  and Black has much better pieces and no weaknesses. Our pieces are eyeing the d3-square and ...Rc8 is coming. The a3-knight is miserable and soon we'll kick White's only active piece with ...h6. }
7... e6 { And we will win back the c5-pawn with a dominant position. } *

