4... dxe5 5. fxe5 c5
{ Attacking the centre.  5...Bf5  is a good alternative.  6.Nf3  e6  and after  7.c4?  Nb4!  8.Na3  Be7∓  the b4-knight is very strong - at some point, Black can grab the initiative with ...c5. If  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3nPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP3PP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  Bxd3  8.Qxd3  c5!  once again, Black is very comfortable. }
6. c3
{ The most played move according to the club-player database on Lichess. This move simply isn't good, though, as we will get a very healthy development while White doesn't. }
6... Nc6 7. Bc4
{ Not often played, but perhaps one of White's most challenging options. I say this with a grain of salt, as Black's position is already excellent after 6.c3. }
7... e6
{ 7...Bf5?!  8.Qb3!  leads to some complications I'd like to avoid. White can meet  8...Na5  with  9.Bb5+  . }
8. Nf3 cxd4 9. cxd4 Bb4+ 10. Kf2
{ White's best option, since  10.Bd2  and  10.Nbd2  would allow our knight to jump to e3. }
10... O-O 11. Rf1 b5
{ A very nice move. We sacrifice a pawn for quick development. } 12. Bxb5 Qb6
13. Bxc6
{ After  13.Bc4?  Nxd4  14.Nxd4  Bc5  we win back the piece with a dominant position. }
13... Qxc6 14. a3 Be7 15. Kg1 Ba6
{ With overwhelming compensation for the pawn. Notice how White has a hard time developing the queenside. }
*

