{ White is trying to make use of postponing c4, which offers some extra options in certain situations. I am calling it 'sneaky' because in blitz games, very often, Black pre-moves ...Nd5-b6 in anticipation of  4.c4  or  4.Bc4  .   However,  4.f4  isn't very good in itself. Black has a clear way of dealing with it. }
4... dxe5 5. fxe5 c5
{ Attacking the centre.  5...Bf5  is a good alternative.  6.Nf3  e6  and after  7.c4?  Nb4!  8.Na3  Be7∓  the b4-knight is very strong - at some point, Black can grab the initiative with ...c5. If  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3nPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP3PP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  Bxd3  8.Qxd3  c5!  once again, Black is very comfortable. }
6. Nf3 { This is not dangerous at all. } 6... cxd4 7. Qxd4 Nc6 8. Bb5
{ Pinning our knight and developing the light-squared bishop. Many moves lead to an equal game here. }
8... Bf5
{ Next, we can play ...e6-...Be7 and enjoy our position. Instead, after  8...Qa5+?!  White can prevent losing a piece.  9.Nc3  Nxc3  10.Bxc6+!  bxc6  11.Bd2!  ⩲  This pin leaves White with a small advantage due to their more active pieces. White can take with the piece on c3 now, keeping the pawn structure intact. }
9. Nc3 e6 10. Nxd5
{ This is probably the best move.  10.O-O?  Nb4!  is, as usual, very strong, attacking c2 and protecting c6 at the same time. }
10... exd5 11. O-O Be7
{ With chances for both sides, as both players have weak pawns. Objectively, the evaluation is about equal, yet our king will be much safer on g8 than White's monarch on g1. Therefore, I slightly prefer the black position. }
