{ Leaving the king on e8 for now and anticipating White's long castle. The bishop is well placed on f5. }
14. O-O-O Qb6 15. Re1 f6 16. h3 h5
{ Preventing White's g4, which would kick our light-squared bishop away from the formidable f5-square. White doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn, and we have many ways to make progress. Notice, first of all, how ...Bh6 becomes an idea for us if White exchanges the f4-bishop for our e5-knight. Otherwise, we can play ...Qb3 to attack White's c4-pawn; depending on how White reacts, we can decide to castle short or long or even put our king on f7. In the long term, we could prepare a ...b5 break to launch a queenside attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) The sneaky 4.f4"]
[Black "The sneaky 4.f4 - 6.c4 Nb4 7.a3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. f4
{ White is trying to make use of postponing c4, which offers some extra options in certain situations. I am calling it 'sneaky' because in blitz games, very often, Black pre-moves ...Nd5-b6 in anticipation of  4.c4  or  4.Bc4  .   However,  4.f4  isn't very good in itself. Black has a clear way of dealing with it. }
4... dxe5 5. fxe5 c5
{ Attacking the centre.  5...Bf5  is a good alternative.  6.Nf3  e6  and after  7.c4?  Nb4!  8.Na3  Be7∓  the b4-knight is very strong - at some point, Black can grab the initiative with ...c5. If  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3nPb2/3P4/5N2/PPP3PP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  Bxd3  8.Qxd3  c5!  once again, Black is very comfortable. }
6. c4
{ The most played move here.  6.Bc4?!  is met by  6...cxd4  7.Qxd4  e6  followed by ...Nc6 with quick development. }
6... Nb4
{ 6...Nb6?  7.d5  leads us to a line we don't want to play. See the Introduction to the Four Pawns Attack. }
7. a3 { This pawn sacrifice is the only way to play here. } 7... N4c6 8. d5
Nxe5
{ Black has won a pawn, but White has a good pawn structure in return. We have seen a similar type of pawn structure in the previous chapters. In comparison, we have more development here and enough time to execute a pawn break @@StartBracket@@e.g. with ...e6@@EndBracket@@ to gain some space for our pieces. This position has hardly been played, so here are some sample lines to get a grasp of how to play. }
9. Nc3 g6
{ I wish I could recommend  9...e6?!  , but it offers White a nasty way of developing quickly.  10.Qh5!  Bd6  11.Bg5  Qb6  12.O-O-O⇆  and we are in trouble. }
10. Bf4 Bg7 { Black can start with  10...Nbd7  , which will likely transpose. }
11. Nf3 Nbd7
{ We shouldn't take on f3 unless we have to, as White can castle long immediately after that.  11...Nxf3+?!  12.Qxf3  O-O  13.O-O-O!  is the extra option for White compared to the main line. }
12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Qd2 Bf5
{ Leaving the king on e8 for now and anticipating White's long castle. The bishop is well placed on f5. }
14. Be2 O-O 15. O-O Qb6 { And White doesn't have enough for the pawn. } *

