[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.1) White plays an early Bc4 - 4.Bc4"]
[Black "Early Bc4 lines - 6.Qf3!? #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Bc4
{ A line I have faced quite frequently in online chess. I think it's regarded as a surprise weapon from the white perspective @@StartBracket@@I agree@@EndBracket@@, which usually means that, if you know what you are doing, you should be more than fine. }
4... Nb6 5. Bb3 dxe5 6. Qf3
{ I doubt you will get this on the board. In my online games,  6.Qh5  was the only move I faced. Still, it is good to know a little bit here. }
6... e6 7. dxe5 Nc6 8. Qg3
{ Putting the queen on g3 is still annoying as we cannot develop our f8-bishop. }
8... Nd4
{ The knight is useful on d4. Yet, not to exchange the bishop on b3, which, for the moment, doesn't contribute too much to White's position. }
9. Nf3 Nf5 10. Qf4 Bd7 11. O-O h6
{ We have seen this idea before. White will place a rook on d1 and try to undermine our queen's position. We are preparing ...g5 to put our bishop on g7 and create a nice outpost for our queen on e7. The position is roughly equal. Personally, I like Black because we have very active pieces, not at all because I am biased. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.1) White plays an early Bc4 - 4.Bc4"]
[Black "Early Bc4 lines - 6.Qf3!? - Alternative to 8...Nd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Bc4
{ A line I have faced quite frequently in online chess. I think it's regarded as a surprise weapon from the white perspective @@StartBracket@@I agree@@EndBracket@@, which usually means that, if you know what you are doing, you should be more than fine. }
4... Nb6 5. Bb3 dxe5 6. Qf3
{ I doubt you will get this on the board. In my online games,  6.Qh5  was the only move I faced. Still, it is good to know a little bit here. }
6... e6 7. dxe5 Nc6 8. Qg3
{ Putting the queen on g3 is still annoying as we cannot develop our f8-bishop. }
8... a5 { Also a good move to play, like in our mainline. } 9. c3
{ To prevent ...Nd4, as well as creating a retreat-square for White's bishop.   9.a4  Nd4  to exchange the bishop on b3 and make room on c6 for our light-squared bishop. }
9... Ne7
{ A very nice idea. We want our knight on f5 and develop our light-squared bishop to c6. }
10. Bc2
{ 10.Nf3  has a drawback now.  10...Nf5  11.Qf4  Qd3  and White cannot castle for the time being. }
10... Nf5
{ We shouldn't mind White taking on f5. Then, we'd have a very powerful light-squared bishop for the rest of the game. }
11. Qf4
{ After  11.Bxf5  exf5  we can develop and will most likely castle long with a good position. }
11... Bd7 12. Nf3 Bb5
{ And we prevent White from castling, with a good position. White can grab the pawn on f5 but we shouldn't care about it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.1) White plays an early Bc4 - 4.Bc4"]
[Black "Early Bc4 lines - 6.Qh5 e6 7.dxe5 a5 8.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Bc4
{ A line I have faced quite frequently in online chess. I think it's regarded as a surprise weapon from the white perspective @@StartBracket@@I agree@@EndBracket@@, which usually means that, if you know what you are doing, you should be more than fine. }
4... Nb6 5. Bb3 dxe5 6. Qh5
{ This move is the whole point of this line. White wants Black to make a concession with either ...g6 or ...e6 to prevent mate on f7.   If  6.dxe5?!  Qxd1+  7.Kxd1  a5⩱  Black is already better because the white king is stuck in the centre. }
6... e6
{ 6...g6?  7.Qxe5±  is what White is aiming for. We now have to make an awkward move: either  7...f6  or  7...Rg8  , which makes it impossible for us to castle short anymore. }
7. dxe5 a5
{ The move to remember in this line. We want to push the pawn to a4 if we can.   7...Nc6?!  is what I used to play in blitz games, almost automatically. But the thing is that Black's position always feels cramped after this.  8.Nf3  Nd4  to create a square on c6 for our light-squared bishop  9.Nc3!  Ignoring our knight and ensuring that the Black queen stays on d8, and now:A@@EndBracket@@  9...Be7  10.O-O  O-O   @@StartBracket@@  10...Nxb3  is hardly any better.  11.axb3  O-O  12.Rd1  Qe8  13.Be3±  and we still lack room to manoeuvre.@@EndBracket@@  11.Rd1  eyeing the queen.  11...Nxf3+  12.Qxf3  Qe8±  and Black has no room for the pieces.B@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/1n2p3/4P2Q/3n4/1BN2N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nxf3+  10.Qxf3  eyeing the b7-pawn so that our light-squared bishop still cannot be developed to c6.  10...Qd4  11.Be3!  Qxe5  12.O-O-O+-  With fantastic compensation for the pawn. The engine already gives this position as winning for White. }
8. a3 a4 { Kicking the bishop back and making room for our rook. } 9. Ba2 Nc6
10. Nf3 { The most played move. } 10... Nd4
{ Yet this is very strong now - White is forced to take since the bishop on b3 is no longer protecting c2. }
11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. O-O Ra5 13. Re1 Bd6
{ And we win the e5-pawn as the rook pins the pawn on a5. } *

