[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.2) White plays an early Bc4 - 3.Bc4"]
[Black "Early Bc4 lines - Transposition to Alapin Sicilian"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Bc4
{ A small sideline that could transpose to an Alapin Sicilian.  3.Nf3  d6  4.Bc4  Nb6  5.Bb3  transposes. }
3... Nb6 4. Bb3 d6
{ Undermining White's centre as usual.  4...d5!?  is a decent alternative. After  5.d4  Bf5  6.Ne2  e6  we have a decent Caro-Kann-like position. We can start undermining White's centre with ...c5 and ...Nc6. }
5. Nf3
{ 5.exd6  exd6  and Black has no problems whatsoever. Our next moves are ...d5, ...Be7 and ...O-O.   For  5.d4  dxe5  6.Qh5  seeChapter 4.1. }
5... c5 { Threatening to trap the white bishop. } 6. c3 c4
{ Pushing the bishop back. Now we can take the d-pawn en passant if White pushes d2-d4. }
7. Bc2 Nc6 8. exd6 Qxd6
{ And we have transposed to one of the current mainlines of the Alapin Sicilian. Seethe beginning of this Chapter for that move order. }
*

