[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5
{ A line I underestimated for quite some time because I usually got very solid positions without really studying it. However, it turns out to be popular, though not quite up there with the Classical Variation, the Exchange Variation or the Four Pawns Attack. I would say it has a solid fourth place in the popularity rankings.I suspect that is because White can very often transpose to the Alapin Variation. If White has an Alapin repertoire against the Sicilian, this line might offer a practical solution - it requires White less study time. What about rankings in terms of danger? Well, compared to the other lines, this is not that dangerous for us. }
4... Nd5 5. Nc3 e6
{ The best approach. We protect our knight and develop.  5...Nxc3?!  6.dxc3!±  offers White a big advantage due to their development.   A decent alternative is  5...c6!?  Just as after 5...e6, we are planning 6...d6 to untangle ourselves. From a logical standpoint, I do think this move is inferior as it doesn't help us to develop like 5...e6 does. I offer it as analternative. }
6. Nxd5 { Not the most ambitious move. } 6... exd5 7. d4 d6 8. cxd6 cxd6 9. Nf3
{ This is also very similar to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/8/3nP3/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  line we will cover ina later chapter. }
9... Nc6 10. Be2
{ The most played move.   10.Bb5??  Qa5+-+  would be lovely for us.   10.exd6?!  Bxd6⩱  helps us with our development. }
10... dxe5 11. dxe5 Bb4+
{ Not the only good move.   11...Bc5!?  12.O-O  O-O  13.Bg5  is a bit annoying - we have to give up a pawn here in order to keep our development going.  13...Qb6!  14.Qxd5  Siaperas, T-Czerniak,M Zagreb 1969, and now  14...Bf5!Ν  with fantastic compensation for the pawn. Black will most certainly win the pawn back.   11...Bf5!?  with the idea of putting our queen on d7 without blocking our bishop.  12.O-O  Bc5  13.a3  O-O  14.b4  Bb6  15.Bb2  led to an interesting battle between a young Richard Rapport and his opponent: Rapport,R @@StartBracket@@2323@@EndBracket@@-Tanacs, A @@StartBracket@@2031@@EndBracket@@ Hungary 2009. I have a small improvement here.  15...d4⇆  with chances for both sides. }
12. Bd2 Bxd2+
{ This has fewer games in the database than  12...Qa5  , yet I think it is a bit easier to equalise completely. After  13.a3  Bxd2+  14.Qxd2  Qxd2+  15.Kxd2  Bg4  16.Rhe1  perhaps White can claim a very slight advantage in this ending due to the isolated black pawn. }
13. Qxd2 O-O 14. Rd1 { This isn't a problem. } 14... Re8 15. Qxd5 Qxd5 16. Rxd5
Be6 { And we win back the pawn on a2. } *

