[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.1) The Practical 4.c5 - Part 1"]
[Black "The practical 4.c5 - 6.d4 & 8.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5
{ A line I underestimated for quite some time because I usually got very solid positions without really studying it. However, it turns out to be popular, though not quite up there with the Classical Variation, the Exchange Variation or the Four Pawns Attack. I would say it has a solid fourth place in the popularity rankings.I suspect that is because White can very often transpose to the Alapin Variation. If White has an Alapin repertoire against the Sicilian, this line might offer a practical solution - it requires White less study time. What about rankings in terms of danger? Well, compared to the other lines, this is not that dangerous for us. }
4... Nd5 5. Nc3 e6
{ The best approach. We protect our knight and develop.  5...Nxc3?!  6.dxc3!±  offers White a big advantage due to their development.   A decent alternative is  5...c6!?  Just as after 5...e6, we are planning 6...d6 to untangle ourselves. From a logical standpoint, I do think this move is inferior as it doesn't help us to develop like 5...e6 does. I offer it as analternative. }
6. d4
{ By transposition, this could lead to the Alapin Sicilian variation mentionedat the start of this chapter. If you have a Sicilian repertoire and play 2...Nf6 versus the Alapin, you don't need to look much further - this is perfectly fine for Black. I will offer an original alternative here if that doesn't fit your repertoire. }
6... Nxc3
{ 6...d6  7.cxd6  cxd6  8.Nf3  is a transposition to the Alapin with Nc3. } 7.
bxc3 b6 { The way to play if we don't want to transpose. } 8. Nf3
{ This is better, but leads to a pawn sacrifice. } 8... bxc5 9. d5
{ Played in a correspondence game.  9.Rb1Ν  is an interesting approach for White, focusing on development.  9...Be7  and at the right moment, we can break in the centre with ...d6 or ...d5. }
9... exd5
{ With this move, we clarify that we have no interest in White getting compensation for the pawn. We want to break free!  9...d6?  10.Ng5!  leads to great trouble for Black. A game continued:  10...Qe7  11.Bb5+  Bd7  12.Bc4  h6  13.Ne4  dxe5  14.Be3±  and White had all the fun in: Bokros,J @@StartBracket@@1695@@EndBracket@@-Sadler,K @@StartBracket@@1587@@EndBracket@@ LSS email 2009.   9...Be7!?  10.h4!  h6  11.Rb1=∞  offers White great compensation for the pawn. }
10. Qxd5 c6 11. Qd3 { This makes our task a bit easier. } 11... d5 12. exd6
Qxd6
{ White still has compensation, but we are at least well able to develop without much trouble. }
*

