[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.1) The Practical 4.c5 - Part 1"]
[Black "The practical 4.c5 - Alternative to 5...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5
{ A line I underestimated for quite some time because I usually got very solid positions without really studying it. However, it turns out to be popular, though not quite up there with the Classical Variation, the Exchange Variation or the Four Pawns Attack. I would say it has a solid fourth place in the popularity rankings.I suspect that is because White can very often transpose to the Alapin Variation. If White has an Alapin repertoire against the Sicilian, this line might offer a practical solution - it requires White less study time. What about rankings in terms of danger? Well, compared to the other lines, this is not that dangerous for us. }
4... Nd5 5. Nc3 c6
{ A decent alternative. Just as after  5...e6  , we are planning 6...d6 to untangle ourselves. From a logical standpoint, I do think this move is inferior as it doesn't help us to develop like  5...e6  does. That's why this is not my main recommendation. }
6. Bc4
{ 6.Nf3  d6  7.Nxd5  cxd5  8.Bb5+  Bd7Ν   @@StartBracket@@  8...Nc6?!  9.b4Ν  is an interesting attempt to complicate things. White wants to hinder Black's development.@@EndBracket@@  9.Bxd7+  Qxd7  10.cxd6  exd6  11.O-O  is perhaps slightly better for White, but it shouldn't be much. }
6... d6 7. Qb3
{ White puts pressure on the knight pinning it due to the indirect attack on f7. This is the most common line. Yet, Black is fine after all the exchanges.   7.cxd6  is the more sensible line.  7...exd6  8.Nxd5  cxd5  9.Bxd5  dxe5  10.Qb3  Qc7  With a roughly equal position. White has some initiative and can solve the pawn structure problem in the next couple of moves.Other moves pose fewer problems:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2pp4/3nP3/2B5/2N5/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nf3  Be6=  allows Black to develop smoothly.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/2pp4/3nP3/2B5/2N5/PP1P1PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.exd6?!  even helps Black's development.  8...Bxd6!  This pawn sacrifice is more than justified.  9.Nxd5  cxd5  10.Bxd5  O-O=∞  . }
7... dxe5 8. Nxd5 cxd5 9. Bxd5
{ Attacking both f7 and b7. White wins a pawn here, but it's not for free. }
9... e6 10. Bxb7 Bxb7 11. Qxb7 Nd7
{ With fantastic compensation for the pawn. Most likely, we will win the pawn back due to the weakness of c5. }
12. b4
{ 12.Nf3  Bxc5⩱  and Black is clearly better due to the better development and pawn structure.   12.c6?!  Nc5  eyeing the d3-square. }
12... a5 13. c6 Nf6 14. c7 Qc8 15. Qc6+ Nd7
{ And we will win the pawn back soon. } *

