[White "5.2) The Practical 4.c5 - Part 2"]
[Black "The practical 4.c5 - Alternative to 6...Bxc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Bc4
{ This move signifies a pawn sacrifice I have often faced in blitz games. The idea is to offer the c5-pawn to speed up development. }
6... Nxc3
{ The mainline, which has been played much more often thanmy recommendation,  which is  6...Bxc5!?  . }
7. dxc3
{ 7.bxc3?!  d5!  It is the perfect time for this move.  8.cxd6  cxd6  9.exd6  Bxd6  10.Nf3  O-O  with a very good version of the Alapin for Black.Instead,  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/4p3/2P1P3/2B5/2P5/P2P1PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bxc5  8.d4=∞  leads to your typical compensation for White. }
7... Nc6
{ 7...Bxc5?!  is what White is hoping for.  8.Qg4!=∞  and White gets tremendous compensation for the pawn. It didn't take me long to figure out that we should avoid this line. }
8. Nf3 { This blocks the Qg4 sortie. } 8... Bxc5 9. O-O a5
{ Black has no problems, while White still needs to prove the compensation. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
