[White "5.3) The Practical 4.c5 - Part 3"]
[Black "The practical 4.c5 - Alapin Sicilian move order"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 { This move signifies the Sicilian Alapin. } 2... Nf6 3. e5 Nd5
4. d4 cxd4 5. cxd4 e6 6. Bc4 d6
{ And here White can play Nf3, which could transpose to lines in this Chapter. }
7. Nf3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.3) The Practical 4.c5 - Part 3"]
[Black "The practical 4.c5 - 5.d4?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. d4
{ This makes it very easy for us. } 5... d6 6. cxd6 exd6
{ And we have a very pleasant version of the Alapin. } 7. Nf3 dxe5 8. dxe5
{ 8.Nxe5  Nd7⩱  offers us a very comfortable isolated pawn position. We are already able to exchange some minor pieces. }
8... Be7 9. Bc4 Nb6 10. Qxd8+ Bxd8 11. Bb3 O-O 12. O-O Nc6
{ With the fragile e5-pawn, I much prefer the Black pieces. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.3) The Practical 4.c5 - Part 3"]
[Black "The practical 4.c5 - 5.Bc4 e6 6.d4 b6 7.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Bc4 e6 6. d4
{ White tries to play without Nc3. This could lead, by transposition and just as in part 1, tothe Alapin variation mentioned at the start of this chapter. If you have a Sicilian repertoire and play 2...Nf6 versus the Alapin, then you don't need to look much further - that's perfectly fine for Black. If you don't have such a repertoire, I'll offer an original alternative.   6.Bxd5?!  exd5  7.d4  d6⩱  leaves Black with a powerful light-squared bishop. A potential pin to a knight on f3 would be annoying.   For  6.Nc3  see5.Nc3 e6 6.Bc4. }
6... b6
{ Once again, the way to play if we want to avoid the Alapin.  6...d6  7.cxd6  cxd6  8.Nf3  transposes tothe Alapin Sicilian mentioned at the beginning of this chapter. }
7. Nf3 { Not a pawn sacrifice, yet it leads to some exchanges. } 7... bxc5 8.
Bxd5 { 8.O-O?!  would lose a pawn after  8...Bb7⩱  . } 8... exd5 9. dxc5 c6
{ 9...Bxc5?  would be beneficial for White.  10.Qxd5  Bb4+  11.Bd2  Bxd2+  12.Nbxd2  Nc6  13.O-O±  White has regained the pawn with a more dominant position and better structure. }
10. Qd4 { Protecting the c5-pawn. White is in trouble after  10.b4  a5⇆  . }
10... a5
{ With a complicated game in Potkin,V @@StartBracket@@2493@@EndBracket@@-Chigladze,I @@StartBracket@@2149@@EndBracket@@ Batumi 2002. Black should be fine, and our development plan is to get our b8-knight to c7, followed by ...Ba6, after which all of our pieces are well positioned. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.3) The Practical 4.c5 - Part 3"]
[Black "The practical 4.c5 - 5.Bc4 e6 6.d4 b6 7.Bxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Bc4 e6 6. d4
{ White tries to play without Nc3. This could lead, by transposition and just as in part 1, tothe Alapin variation mentioned at the start of this chapter. If you have a Sicilian repertoire and play 2...Nf6 versus the Alapin, then you don't need to look much further - that's perfectly fine for Black. If you don't have such a repertoire, I'll offer an original alternative.   6.Bxd5?!  exd5  7.d4  d6⩱  leaves Black with a powerful light-squared bishop. A potential pin to a knight on f3 would be annoying.   For  6.Nc3  see5.Nc3 e6 6.Bc4. }
