{ Once again, the way to play if we want to avoid the Alapin.  6...d6  7.cxd6  cxd6  8.Nf3  transposes tothe Alapin Sicilian mentioned at the beginning of this chapter. }
7. Bxd5
{ It is a bit of a concession for White to give up the light-squared bishop. White tries to get some space in return. }
7... exd5 8. Nc3
{ For  8.cxb6  axb6  see7.cxb6.   For  8.Nf3  bxc5  see7.Nf3.   8.b4  bxc5  9.dxc5  a5⇆  with big problems for White, or  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p1pp1ppp/8/2ppP3/1P1P4/8/P4PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.bxc5  d6  10.exd6  cxd6  and Black has zero problems. }
8... c6
{ 8...bxc5!?  is a solid alternative. After  9.dxc5  c6  10.b4  a5⇆  White has problems to solve, but better is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p1pp1ppp/8/2ppP3/3P4/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nxd5Ν  c6  10.Nc3  d5!  @@StartBracket@@Breaking free.@@EndBracket@@  11.exd6  Bxd6  Black will get a slightly worse pawn structure, but our bishop pair nicely compensates for that. We can also make use of the b-file in the long run. For example:  12.dxc5  Qe7+  Removing the queen from the d-file, thus securing our ability to castle.  13.Nge2  Bxc5  14.O-O  O-O=  This is roughly equal. White has a slightly better pawn structure, yet Black has the bishop pair in an open position. We will continue with ...Bf5, ...Nd7 and ...Rb8. }
9. b4 { For  9.cxb6  axb6  see7.cxb6. } 9... Na6 10. Rb1 Nc7
{ All our pieces will be nicely positioned now. White has more space, but we have no problems and keep the advantage of the bishop pair. For example: }
11. Be3 Be7 12. Nge2
{ Breuer,R @@StartBracket@@2047@@EndBracket@@-Ward,A @@StartBracket@@2068@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2008. }
12... Ba6 { This would have been very comfortable for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.3) The Practical 4.c5 - Part 3"]
[Black "The practical 4.c5 - 5.Bc4 e6 6.d4 b6 7.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Bc4 e6 6. d4
{ White tries to play without Nc3. This could lead, by transposition and just as in part 1, tothe Alapin variation mentioned at the start of this chapter. If you have a Sicilian repertoire and play 2...Nf6 versus the Alapin, then you don't need to look much further - that's perfectly fine for Black. If you don't have such a repertoire, I'll offer an original alternative.   6.Bxd5?!  exd5  7.d4  d6⩱  leaves Black with a powerful light-squared bishop. A potential pin to a knight on f3 would be annoying.   For  6.Nc3  see5.Nc3 e6 6.Bc4. }
6... b6
{ Once again, the way to play if we want to avoid the Alapin.  6...d6  7.cxd6  cxd6  8.Nf3  transposes tothe Alapin Sicilian mentioned at the beginning of this chapter. }
7. Nc3 { Hardly every played, yet more interesting than it looks. } 7... Nxc3
8. bxc3 Bb7
{ A useful inclusion. After  8...bxc5?!  9.d5  Bb7  10.Nh3!Ν  the knight can jump to f4, in combination with Qg4, which is very dangerous for Black. }
9. Nf3 bxc5 10. O-O cxd4 11. cxd4 Be7 12. d5 O-O
{ White has enough counterplay for the pawn. Yet, it's not enough for an advantage. A sample continuation is  13.Rb1  Bxd5  14.Bxd5  exd5  15.Qxd5  Nc6  16.Rd1  Qc8  17.Qxd7  Rd8  18.Qxc8  Raxc8  with an equal position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.3) The Practical 4.c5 - Part 3"]
[Black "The practical 4.c5 - 5.Bc4 e6 6.d4 b6 7.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Bc4 e6 6. d4
{ White tries to play without Nc3. This could lead, by transposition and just as in part 1, tothe Alapin variation mentioned at the start of this chapter. If you have a Sicilian repertoire and play 2...Nf6 versus the Alapin, then you don't need to look much further - that's perfectly fine for Black. If you don't have such a repertoire, I'll offer an original alternative.   6.Bxd5?!  exd5  7.d4  d6⩱  leaves Black with a powerful light-squared bishop. A potential pin to a knight on f3 would be annoying.   For  6.Nc3  see5.Nc3 e6 6.Bc4. }
6... b6
{ Once again, the way to play if we want to avoid the Alapin.  6...d6  7.cxd6  cxd6  8.Nf3  transposes tothe Alapin Sicilian mentioned at the beginning of this chapter. }
7. Nc3 { Hardly every played. Yet more interesting than it looks. } 7... Nxc3
8. bxc3 Bb7
{ A useful inclusion. After  8...bxc5?!  9.d5  Bb7  10.Nh3!Ν  the knight can jump to f4, in combination with Qg4, which is very dangerous for Black. }
9. Nf3 bxc5 10. d5
{ 10.Rb1  attacking our bishop is met by  10...Be4  attacking the rook in return, followed by quick development. }
10... exd5 11. Bxd5 Bxd5 12. Qxd5 Nc6 13. O-O Qe7
{ The queen has a very nice square on e6, where it doesn't hinder our development.  13...Be7?!  leads us to problems.  14.Rd1  O-O  15.Be3±  and White will, at the very least, win back the pawn on c5 with a more dominant position. Our queen is not playing. }
14. Be3 Qe6 15. Rad1 Qxd5 16. Rxd5 O-O-O
{ White wins back the pawn, but the advantage is gone. We can break with ...d6 very soon. }
*

