1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Bc4 e6 6. d4
{ White tries to play without Nc3. This could lead, by transposition and just as in part 1, tothe Alapin variation mentioned at the start of this chapter. If you have a Sicilian repertoire and play 2...Nf6 versus the Alapin, then you don't need to look much further - that's perfectly fine for Black. If you don't have such a repertoire, I'll offer an original alternative.   6.Bxd5?!  exd5  7.d4  d6⩱  leaves Black with a powerful light-squared bishop. A potential pin to a knight on f3 would be annoying.   For  6.Nc3  see5.Nc3 e6 6.Bc4. }
6... b6
{ Once again, the way to play if we want to avoid the Alapin.  6...d6  7.cxd6  cxd6  8.Nf3  transposes tothe Alapin Sicilian mentioned at the beginning of this chapter. }
7. cxb6
{ By far the most played move. Yet, I think this makes our play a lot easier. White has some alternatives which can create some problems. }
7... axb6 { Opening up the a-file for our rook. } 8. Nc3
{ If we compare this position to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/8/2PnP3/8/8/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  e6  6.d4  Nxc3  7.bxc3  b6  line coveredhere, the noticeable difference is that White has put the bishop on c4, which strikes me as slightly worse in this position. }
8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ba6
{ Trading off the potentially strong light-squared bishop is fine for Black. }
10. Qe2 Bxc4 11. Qxc4 Ba3
{ Followed by ...Nc6, ...Qe7, ...O-O and ...Rfa8, which leads to immense pressure over the a-file. }
*

