{ White tries to play without Nc3. This could lead, by transposition and just as in part 1, tothe Alapin variation mentioned at the start of this chapter. If you have a Sicilian repertoire and play 2...Nf6 versus the Alapin, then you don't need to look much further - that's perfectly fine for Black. If you don't have such a repertoire, I'll offer an original alternative.   6.Bxd5?!  exd5  7.d4  d6⩱  leaves Black with a powerful light-squared bishop. A potential pin to a knight on f3 would be annoying.   For  6.Nc3  see5.Nc3 e6 6.Bc4. }
