[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Bc4 e6 6. d4
{ White tries to play without Nc3. This could lead, by transposition and just as in part 1, tothe Alapin variation mentioned at the start of this chapter. If you have a Sicilian repertoire and play 2...Nf6 versus the Alapin, then you don't need to look much further - that's perfectly fine for Black. If you don't have such a repertoire, I'll offer an original alternative.   6.Bxd5?!  exd5  7.d4  d6⩱  leaves Black with a powerful light-squared bishop. A potential pin to a knight on f3 would be annoying.   For  6.Nc3  see5.Nc3 e6 6.Bc4. }
6... b6
{ Once again, the way to play if we want to avoid the Alapin.  6...d6  7.cxd6  cxd6  8.Nf3  transposes tothe Alapin Sicilian mentioned at the beginning of this chapter. }
7. cxb6
{ By far the most played move. Yet, I think this makes our play a lot easier. White has some alternatives which can create some problems. }
7... axb6 { Opening up the a-file for our rook. } 8. Nf3 Ba6
{ Certainly not the only move here, yet the reasoning is very straightforward - White has moved the bishop twice, so there is a tempo loss if we trade it with ...Ba6.   8...Bb7  9.O-O  Be7  followed by ...O-O and a timely ...d6 is also fine for Black.   8...d6?!  9.Bg5!  makes things slightly awkward for us.  9...Be7  10.Bxd5  exd5  11.Bxe7  Qxe7  12.O-O  O-O  13.Nc3  Be6⩲  and our bishop is in the wrong place. I much prefer the 8...Ba6 or 8...Bb7 positions. }
9. b3
{ An interesting way to justify the presence of the white bishop on c4. Exchanging on c4 would not be good - our knight would lose its wonderful outpost. }
9... Bb4+ { Other moves are fine too as long as we develop. } 10. Bd2 Nc6 11.
O-O Bxd2 12. Qxd2 Nce7
{ We have been following a game from about 50 years ago: Machulsky,A-Bagirov,V Kirovabad 1973. We can retreat our bishop to b7 and start thinking about breaking with ...f6 to open up the f-file. }
*

