1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. a4
{ An aggressive line where White tries to push the knight back even further with a5. For  4.d4  d6  5.exd6  cxd6  6.a4!?  see the Exchange Variation,Chapter 1.9. }
4... d6 { This line more or less illustrates what White is going for. } 5. a5
N6d7 6. exd6
{ 6.e6?!  has been played as well, but is less clear.  6...fxe6  7.d4  e5!  and it's unclear whether White can get enough compensation for the pawn. }
6... c5
{ This has only been played once and is an interesting way to deal with White's aggression. We sacrifice a pawn for quick development and weak squares on d4 and b4. Also, the pawn on a5 can be targeted with ...Nc6.   6...cxd6?  transposes to a bad line of the Exchange Variation.   6...exd6  is the main line and we transpose to an awkward version of the 5...exd6 answer in the Exchange Variation. This is not congruent with our current repertoire, where we play  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/1n1P4/8/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...cxd6  against the Exchange Variation, but also, I simply believe that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/1n6/4P3/P1P5/8/1P1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR_b_KQkq_a3_0_4@@EndFEN@@ 4...a5  is the better move. }
7. Nc3
{ If White ignores the sacrifice, he will be clearly better, thanks to his development lead.  7.dxe7!?  Bxe7  8.Nf3  Nc6  9.Qa4?  protecting the a5-pawn.  9...O-O  10.Be2  Re8  11.O-O  Bf6∓  and Black has more than enough compensation for the pawn. It really isn't worth it for White to hold on to the a-pawn.White should try  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nbppp/2n5/P1p5/2P5/5N2/1P1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nc3  O-O  10.Be2  and now  10...Bf6!?  is interesting, intending to take the a5-pawn on the next turn.  10...Nxa5  could work, but it gives White the moment to push the d-pawn:  11.d4!  cxd4  12.Nxd4  . The best is probably  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2n5/P1p5/2P5/2N2N2/1P1PBPPP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nf6  11.O-O  a6  12.d3    Since White has pushed this pawn, it's a good time to start thinking about taking the pawn on a5.  12...Bf5  and Black can take the a5-pawn back with a close to equal position. }
7... exd6 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. d4 Be7
{ 9...cxd4?!  10.Nxd4±  leaves White with a clear target on d6. } 10. d5 Nb4
{ With a decent position for Black. } *

