1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. a4
{ An aggressive line where White tries to push the knight back even further with a5. For  4.d4  d6  5.exd6  cxd6  6.a4!?  see the Exchange Variation,Chapter 1.9. }
4... a5
{ With this move, we prevent White's a5 and secure ourselves an outpost on b4. If White tries to play normally with 4.d4 or 4.Nf3, for example, then the inclusion of 4.a4 and 4...a5 makes those lines a lot less dangerous. }
5. d4 d6 6. f4
{ Going for a 'Five' Pawns Attack instead of Four, with a4 included. Compared to the Four Pawns Attack, we once again can use the b4-square. }
6... dxe5
{ 6...g6!?  is congruent with our repertoire and certainly viable, as the inclusion of  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/1n6/4P3/2P5/8/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.a4  a5  gives us a better version thanour mainline in the Four Pawns Attack. }
7. fxe5 Bf5
{ 7...c5?  8.d5  e6  9.Nc3  exd5  10.cxd5  c4  11.d6  and Nb5 intending Nc7 is coming.   7...Nc6  should transpose after  8.Be3  Bf5  9.Nf3  . }
8. Be3 Nc6 9. Nf3 Nb4 10. Na3
{ This leaves White with a terrible knight on a3. } 10... e6 11. Be2 Be7 12.
O-O O-O 13. b3 f6 14. exf6 Bxf6
{ And the position is about equal. Our plan is to put pressure on the d4-pawn with a rook on d8, and perhaps we can even target that pawn with a potential ...c5 break. }
