[White "6) The Aggressive 4.a4"]
[Black "The aggressive 4.a4 - 5.d4 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. a4
{ An aggressive line where White tries to push the knight back even further with a5. For  4.d4  d6  5.exd6  cxd6  6.a4!?  see the Exchange Variation,Chapter 1.9. }
4... a5
{ With this move, we prevent White's a5 and secure ourselves an outpost on b4. If White tries to play normally with 4.d4 or 4.Nf3, for example, then the inclusion of 4.a4 and 4...a5 makes those lines a lot less dangerous. }
5. d4 d6 6. exd6 { We are now comparing lines with the Exchange Variation. }
6... exd6
{ Black gets an improved version of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/1n1P4/8/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...exd6  in the Exchange Variation. In that line, Black often had the problem of where to put the c6-knight. With the now available square on b4, that problem is solved.   6...cxd6?  transposes tothe Exchange Variation with 6.a4. Yet,  6...exd6  is much better in this position. }
7. Nc3 Be7 8. Bd3 { One of the mainlines in the Exchange Variation. } 8... Nc6
9. Nge2 O-O 10. O-O Re8 11. b3
{ A very common idea to protect c4.  11.Be3  Nb4  intending ...c6 and ...d5 is similar to our mainline. }
11... Bf6 12. Be3 Nb4 13. Bb1
{ Again, this Leaves the a1-rook offside. Alternatively,  13.Qd2  d5  14.c5  Nd7=  and Black can start aiming for the light squares with ...c6 and ...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@prepared with ...g6@@EndBracket@@ after trading the d3-bishop followed by ...Nf8. }
13... d5 14. c5 Nd7 15. Qd2 c6 16. h3 b6
{ And Black is the one pushing - White's pieces are misplaced. } *

