1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3
{ This move signifies the Classic Variation in the Alekhine opening. White goes for normal development and tries to support the centre. This is by far the most frequent system. In the past 2 years, I have experimented with the Alekhine in my games and in all of them, literally, this is the move I encountered on the board. }
4... dxe5
{ My recommendation. Let's talk about the alternatives:   The classical mainline and still the most popular choice is  4...Bg4!?  . I have one issue with this move: after  5.exd6  , we transpose to the Exchange Variation, but with ...Bg4 instead of ...g6. Therefore, we are out of our repertoire.   4...c6  has been a big line as well. Yet, once again, if White plays  5.exd6  , we transpose to a line that is not congruent with our repertoire on the Exchange Variation.   I was going to recommend  4...g6!?  but after some days of working on this line, I realised that  5.Bc4  Nb6  6.Bb3  Bg7  7.Qe2  transposes to a popular line in the Modern Defence, commonly reached via the  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  Bg7  3.Nf3  d6  4.Bc4  Nf6  5.Qe2  O-O  6.e5  dxe5  7.dxe5  Nd5  move order.   As usual, I wanted to keep the repertoire original, which led me to opt for the  4...dxe5  line. }
5. Nxe5 g6
{ The second most popular move and my recommendation. World Champion Magnus Carlsen has recently played it in rapid online games.  5...c6!?  is the most played move in this position and certainly a viable option as well.  6.Be2  Bf5  7.O-O  Nd7  8.Nf3  e6  9.c4  N5f6  10.Nc3  Bd6  is the main line of this variation. Black has a solid pawn structure and is looking for the right time to break in the centre with either ...e5 or ...c5. This has been extensively analysed by National Master Bryan Tillis in his Chessable course on the Alekhine. }
6. Bc4 c6
{ An important move. In this position, there is a trap we need to avoid.  6...Bg7?  would lose a pawn.  7.Nxf7!  Kxf7  8.Qf3+  and White wins the piece back on d5.  8...Ke6  doesn't help due to  9.Qe4++-  picking up the knight.   6...Be6!?  is an option too, but we will have to play ...c6 later on anyway. I prefer to keep the bishop on c8 for now.  7.O-O  Bg7  8.Re1  O-O  9.Bb3!?  is possible, or  9.Nd2  Nd7  10.Nef3  and here Black's best move is still 10...c6  . }
7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Bb3
{ White is trying to play c4-Nc3 with some space advantage. In the next chapter, we will take a look at alternatives. }
9... Nd7
{ I like this simple developing move better than the alternative.  9...b5?!  is tempting, but it's not good this time - our knight gets stuck on b8.  10.Nc3!  and now after  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3±  Black still has a hard-to-develop knight on b8, and  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p3ppbp/2p3p1/1p1nN3/3P4/1BN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Be6  is met by  11.Qf3!±  putting more pressure on our position.   9...Be6!?  is the most played move and could transpose to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/6p1/3nN3/2BP4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be6  but, as I mentioned before, I have another idea in mind for the bishop. }
10. Nf3
{ White's main idea is to keep as many light pieces on the board as possible to make the best use of his slight space advantage. }
10... b5
{ We are trying to stop White's c4. Our move does involve a pawn sacrifice but, in exchange, Black gets very decent compensation.   The most played move has been  10...N7f6?!  but it doesn't challenge White's pawn advance.  Michael Adams was in trouble in a game against Garry Kasparov because he allowed  11.c4!  Nc7  12.h3!  preventing ...Bg4. White had a clear advantage and went on to win in Kasparov,G @@StartBracket@@2795@@EndBracket@@ -Adams,M @@StartBracket@@2665@@EndBracket@@ Linares 1997.   10...Re8?!  also allows  11.c4±  . }
11. Bxd5 { White chooses to take the pawn. } 11... cxd5 12. Qe2
{ The worse method to capture the pawn. } 12... Re8 13. Qxb5 Rb8
{ And now, after almost every queen move, we break in the centre. } 14. Qxd5
{ Grabbing a second pawn is very dangerous for White. } 14... Bb7 15. Qc4 Bxf3
16. gxf3 e5
{ With a very dangerous initiative for Black. The kingside is exposed, and not all white pieces are into play. }
*

