11. a4
{ White chooses not to take the pawn. With this move, White is trying to undermine the b5-pawn and open up the a-file for the rook. For  11.c3  seethe next chapter in the 9.c3 variation.   11.c4!?  leaves White with an inferior pawn structure. For example:  11...bxc4  12.Bxc4  N7b6  followed by ...Bg4 and Black has at least equalised. }
11... b4
{ The only move played by Loren Schmidt. I tried this move myself in a classical game and didn't feel at ease. Afterwards, my opponent asked me why I didn't play  11...N7b6  and my answer was that I simply knew  11...b4  had been played before. As we looked a bit deeper, I had to admit that  11...N7b6  made a lot more sense, and it ismy recommendation for this course. Reviewing  11...b4  I got the sense that White always has active ideas and easy play. Here are some sample lines. }
12. Bg5
{ The best, developing his bishop and threatening the pawn on  e7  . My opponent went  12.Nbd2?!  , which was probably a bit too slow.  12...Bb7  13.Ne4  and here I tried to prevent his bishop from entering on g5 with  13...h6?  . It turned out that his bishop had another decent way of developing.  14.c4!  bxc3  15.bxc3!  .M,Schippers@@StartBracket@@2285@@EndBracket@@-R,Pruijssers@@StartBracket@@2565@@EndBracket@@, Dutch competition 2021/2022. White's bishop reached the beautiful spot a3. In the end, I was able to win the game, but it came with a lot of sweat and tears.  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb1nppbp/2p3p1/3n4/Pp1PN3/1B3N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...c5!  is the way to go.  14.Nxc5  Nxc5  15.dxc5  Rc8  and Black wins the pawn back once again. Notice that White cannot move his c1-bishop because it needs to protect the b2-pawn.A better reaction is  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb1nppbp/6p1/2pn4/Pp1PN3/1B3N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.dxc5  e6⇆  followed by ...Qc7 and ...Nxc6, winning the pawn back. This would have left Black with a very decent position. }
12... Re8
{ Preparing an interesting setup. Black's idea is ...Nf8 and ...Be6, after which White has a hard time making progress.   Not  12...Bb7??  13.Bxd5  cxd5  14.Bxe7  and White wins a rook for the bishop. }
13. Nbd2
{ 13.a5  Nf8  14.h3  Be6  15.Nbd2  Nc7  16.c4  bxc3  17.bxc3  Bxb3  18.Qxb3  Rb8  19.Qa4  Nfe6  20.Ne4  f5⇆  ended in a draw in Biedermann,T @@StartBracket@@2427@@EndBracket@@-Schmidt,L @@StartBracket@@2331@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2013. }
13... Nf8 14. Ne5 { And I feel like White is having all the fun. } *

