[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7.2) The Classic Nf3 Variation - 8.Re1 O-O 9.Others"]
[Black "Classic - 9.Nd2?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1
O-O
{ In this chapter, we are going to take a look at 9th move alternatives for White. Play becomes very similar to9.Bb3 lines but I thought it would be good to take a look at the slight differences. }
9. Nd2 { This is a slight error - the d4-pawn isn't yet protected. } 9... Nb6
{ We'll win either the pawn or the bishop pair. } 10. c3 Nxc4 11. Ndxc4 Be6
{ The bishop is nicely positioned here now, aimed at the queenside. } 12. Qe2
Nd7 13. Bf4
{ 13.Nf3  c5⇆  already creates our desired counterplay. Notice how we have prevented White from keeping the position closed with d5. }
13... Re8 { Protecting our e7-pawn. } 14. Rad1 Nxe5 15. Bxe5
{ 15.Nxe5?!  loses a pawn to  15...Bxa2  . } 15... Bxc4 16. Qxc4 e6
{ And Black has no problems. } 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Re5 Qe7
{ White has more space, but without minor pieces, this space advantage isn't worth anything. We can start exchanging rooks and, if White retreats their rooks, push our pawns with ...c5, for example. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
