[White "7.2) The Classic Nf3 Variation - 8.Re1 O-O 9.Others"]
[Black "Classic - 9.Bf1!? #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1
O-O
{ In this chapter, we are going to take a look at 9th move alternatives for White. Play becomes very similar to9.Bb3 lines but I thought it would be good to take a look at the slight differences. }
9. Bf1
{ White puts the bishop on f1. The idea is the same as  9.Bb3  - to play c4 and gain space. }
9... Nd7 10. Nxd7 { Again, not the most ambitious way of playing. } 10... Bxd7
{ I prefer to take with the bishop because our d5-knight is no longer under pressure by the bishop on c4/b3. }
11. c4 { 11.c3  Re8  12.Bg5  Qb6⇆  followed up with ...e5 at some point. }
11... Nb6 12. Be3 { 12.Nc3?!  Be6  leaves both white pawns hanging. } 12... c5
{ And White is already in a bit of trouble. } *

