{ In this chapter, we are going to take a look at 9th move alternatives for White. Play becomes very similar to9.Bb3 lines but I thought it would be good to take a look at the slight differences. }
9. Bf1
{ White puts the bishop on f1. The idea is the same as  9.Bb3  - to play c4 and gain space. }
9... Nd7 10. Nf3
{ White has more space; therefore, keeping pieces on the board makes sense. }
10... b5
{ Once again, we play this move to prevent White's c4. With the bishop on f1 instead of b3,  10...c5?!  is possible - the d5-knight is not attacked. It is the most played move, yet I prefer the text move as it is very straightforward.  11.c4!  Nc7  The knight is better placed here than on b6 or f6 as we might need to break with ...b5. Now  12.d5!?Ν  gaining space is an interesting option. Instead,  12.Nc3  cxd4  13.Nxd4  Nc5  14.Be3±  This position was played in the game Aveskulov,V @@StartBracket@@2526@@EndBracket@@-Vovk,Y @@StartBracket@@2546@@EndBracket@@ ICC INT 2009. I very much prefer the more active white pieces here. }
11. a4 b4 { This also stops c4. } 12. c4 bxc3 13. bxc3
{ Or  13.Nxc3  N7f6⇆  with a roughly equal position. } 13... c5
{ This is now possible since there is no bishop on b3. } *

