[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7.2) The Classic Nf3 Variation - 8.Re1 O-O 9.Others"]
[Black "Classic - 9.a4!? #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1
O-O
{ In this chapter, we are going to take a look at 9th move alternatives for White. Play becomes very similar to9.Bb3 lines but I thought it would be good to take a look at the slight differences. }
9. a4
{ Only played once, but it might be the best. Our ...b5 is stopped for good. }
9... Bf5
{ Since ...Bb7 is no longer possible, we must take our bishop somewhere else, and f5 is a decent place. }
10. c3
{ 10.Nd2?!  neglects the d4-pawn.  10...Nb6  and White has to give up the bishop pair or the pawn. }
10... Nd7 11. Nf3
{ 11.Nxd7  Qxd7  is once again not much of a problem. We can even start pushing our queenside again. }
11... Re8 12. Bg5 { Here, Black has two ways of playing. } 12... Bf6
{ An idea we will see more often in the next chapter. } 13. Qc1
{ This might be better, and forces us to go for our other plan. } 13... Bxb1
{ Anticipating all the following exchanges.  13...e5  is acceptable too, but I prefer to exchange the bishop for the knight first.  14.Bxf6  Qxf6  15.Bxd5  cxd5  16.dxe5  Nxe5  17.Nxe5  Rxe5  18.Rxe5  Qxe5  19.Nd2  and the d2-knight will be magnificently placed on d4. }
14. Rxb1 e5 15. Bxd5
{ To create an isolated pawn on d5. After  15.dxe5  Nxe5  16.Nxe5  Bxg5=  the position is roughly equal, with symmetrical pawn structures and opposite-coloured bishops. }
15... cxd5 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Rxe5 19. Rxe5 Qxe5 20. Qd2 Re8
{ White has a small advantage in pawn structure, but our active pieces compensate for that. }
*

