{ 10.Nd2?!  neglects the d4-pawn.  10...Nb6  and White has to give up the bishop pair or the pawn. }
10... Nd7 11. Nf3
{ 11.Nxd7  Qxd7  is once again not much of a problem. We can even start pushing our queenside again. }
11... Re8 12. Bg5 { Here, Black has two ways of playing. } 12... Bf6
{ An idea we will see more often in the next chapter. } 13. Bxf6 exf6
{ This pawn structure isn't so bad for Black, as you will see in the next chapter. }
