11. Bf1
{ This is a good square for the bishop. It's not in the way of other pieces and keeps an eye on our b5-pawn, thus hindering our ...c5 break. }
11... a5
{ Trying to gain some space on the queenside.  11...N7b6!?  12.Nbd2  Bf5  is a decent setup as well. }
12. a4 { Targeting our b5-pawn. } 12... b4
{ Allowing c4 is OK in this particular position.   12...Ba6  is a decent alternative.  13.Nbd2  exchanging on b5 leaves as very mobile pawns.  13...bxa4  14.Bxa6  Rxa6  15.Qxa4  e6  White is a bit better due to his pawn structure, but we are very solid and currently have zero problems. ...c5 is still in the cards as well. }
13. c4
{ Notice how the f1-bishop lacks a target for the moment.  13.Bg5  c5!⇆  Since our b5-pawn is no longer under attack, we can push our c-pawn. }
13... Nc7
{ The knight can jump to e6, where it puts pressure on the weakened d4-pawn. The idea is to break in the centre with ...c5, and, if White answers with d5, then we will play ...e5 to gain space in the centre. In this strategy, the knight on c7 is a crucial piece. For example: }
14. Bg5 { Or  14.Be3  e5!  and the b2-pawn is a big target. } 14... Ne6 15. Bh4
{ 15.Be3  is safer, yet passive. The text allows us an extra chance to go after the d4-pawn. }
15... g5
{ With our pieces aiming at the d4-pawn, this provocative push gives us good play. }
16. Bxg5
{ 16.Nxg5  Nxd4∓  and Black has all the activity, with ideas like ...Nf5 or ...Nc5.   16.Bg3  g4  is quite dangerous for White. The d4-pawn is in trouble. }
16... Nxg5 17. Nxg5 e5
{ Black has lost a pawn but got a beast of a bishop in return. } *

