{ To gain space on the queenside and allow our bishop to develop on b7. Mamedyarov has tried  10...Re8!?  intending to play ...e5 if allowed.  11.Bg5  Developing and pinning the pawn on e7.   @@StartBracket@@  11.Nbd2  e5!?Ν  @@EndBracket@@  Now  11...h6!?  could be a useful inclusion. An interesting setup is  11...Nf8!?  On f8, the knight supports the bishop on e6.  12.Nbd2  Be6  13.Bh4  Qb6  14.Bb3  Rad8  and Black was quite solid in the game Bologan,V @@StartBracket@@2681@@EndBracket@@-Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ Beijing 2012. }
11. Bf1
{ This is a good square for the bishop. It's not in the way of other pieces and keeps an eye on our b5-pawn, thus hindering our ...c5 break. }
11... a5
{ Trying to gain some space on the queenside.  11...N7b6!?  12.Nbd2  Bf5  is a decent setup as well. }
12. Bg5
{ Always a useful inclusion for White.  12.Nbd2  a4  13.a3  Qc7  and now ...e5 is coming. }
12... Re8 { Defending e7. } 13. Nbd2
{ 13.a4  b4  14.c4  is very similar to 12.a4.  14...Nc7!  15.Nbd2  c5!  with counterplay. }
13... a4 14. a3
{ We have finished our queenside advances, and now we can focus on our main plan again. }
14... Ba6 { Very straightforward. Once again, we are trying to play ...c5. }
15. Qc2 c5
{ We were following the correspondence game. Hablizel,F  @@StartBracket@@2338@@EndBracket@@-Cloes,D @@StartBracket@@2247@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017. With good counterplay for Black. }
