1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1
O-O
{ In this chapter, we are going to take a look at 9th move alternatives for White. Play becomes very similar to9.Bb3 lines but I thought it would be good to take a look at the slight differences. }
9. c3
{ The second most played move besides  9.Bb3  , covered inthe previous chapter. White is trying to solidify the centre, protecting the d4-pawn, before doing anything else. The c4 push may still be tried at some point, but it has been postponed for now. }
9... Nd7 { Developing and offering a knight trade. } 10. Nd3
{ Not a bad place for the knight. It keeps an eye out for the ...c5-break. Therefore, a sensible approach for us is not to try and play on the queenside too much. }
10... Re8 { Aiming to play ...e5. } 11. Nd2 e5 { This is already equalising. }
12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Rxe5
{ The rook recapture is the most principled.  13...Bxe5?!  gives away a free pawn.  14.Nf3  Bg7  15.Rxe8+  Qxe8  16.Bxd5  cxd5  17.Qxd5±  Black still has interesting compensation for the pawn, yet I'd rather not give a pawn if I don't have to. }
14. Rxe5 Bxe5
{ And the position is about equal. The pawn structures are symmetrical, and neither side has any real weaknesses. }
