{ A creative idea we have seen before.   14...Qc8!?  is still a decent option for Black. We play for the same trick as after 14.a3. and now:A@@EndBracket@@  15.Nd2?  h6  16.Bh4  g5  17.Bg3  Bg4  18.Qe4  f5  19.Qe6+  Qxe6  20.Rxe6  f4-+  and we win a piece.B@@EndBracket@@  White sees the trick, dang it. @@StartFEN@@r1q1r1k1/1p2ppbp/1np3p1/p2n1bB1/P2P4/1BPN1Q2/1P3PPP/RN2R1K1 w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.h3  Bxd3  16.Qxd3  Qf5  when  17.Qg3?  e5!  gives Black a huge initiative. Keep in mind that White is still a bit underdeveloped. Safer is  @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/1p2ppbp/1np3p1/p2n1qB1/P2P4/1BPQ3P/1P3PP1/RN2R1K1 w - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Qxf5  gxf5  18.Na3!⩲  and now we cannot force the trade of a pair of bishops, but it's not the end of the world. Black still has a very solid position, though we do have to acknowledge White is somewhat better because of the long-term advantage of the bishop pair. }
