[White "7.3) The Classic Nf3 Variation - Alternatives to 8.Re1"]
[Black "Classic - 8.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. O-O Bg7
{ In this chapter, we are looking at 8th move alternatives where White doesn't play Re1. Many lines transpose, so we look mostly at the lines that can create a different setup. }
8. Nc3
{ Black cannot take the knight on c3 here, disrupting White's pawn structure due to the threat on f7. White's idea is to take on d5 himself, changing Black's pawn structure to his benefit. }
8... Bxe5
{ Steering the game into an ending.  8...O-O  is reasonable as well.  9.Nxd5  cxd5  10.Bb3⩲  and White has a slight advantage, yet nothing too substantial. }
9. dxe5 Nxc3 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. bxc3 Be6
{ Exchanging light-squared bishops. We are left with doubled pawns on the e-file, but White’s doubled pawns on the c-file compensate for that. As it will, this position was played in an old game of Paul Keres, one of the strongest players in the history of chess. }
12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Rb1 b6 14. Rb4 c5
{ Placing all the pawns on dark squares to restrict White's bishop. } 15. Rh4
Nc6 16. Bh6 { Keres tries to trick his opponent. } 16... Rg8
{ But Black doesn't fall for  16...Nxe5??  17.Bg7!  and Black loses material. }
17. Bg5 h5
{ And after  18.Rd1+  Kc7  19.Kf1  Rad8  20.Rxd8  Kxd8  21.Re4  Rf8  a draw was agreed in Keres,P-Mikenas,V Tallinn 1964. If I had this position, I would have probably tried to win with Black. I think we have the better position due to the possibilities on the queenside. }
*

