1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. O-O Bg7
{ In this chapter, we are looking at 8th move alternatives where White doesn't play Re1. Many lines transpose, so we look mostly at the lines that can create a different setup. }
8. Qe2 O-O 9. c3
{ 9.Nd2  Nb6  and White needs to give up the bishop pair or the d4-pawn. } 9...
Nd7 { This is all very similar tothe mainline with 8.Re1. } 10. Nxd7
{ Once again, this is not dangerous.  10.Nf3  Re8  with the white queen on e2, it is a good idea to play for a quick ...e5.  10.Nd3  b5  11.Bb3  a5  is similar to the 8.Re1 line. }
10... Qxd7 11. Nd2 b5
{ Inthe mainline with 8.Re1, we do not play like this because White can target the c5-square with his d2-knight. Here, it is justified because we can target White's queenside. }
12. Bb3
{ Here, we can play ...a5, as inthe mainline with 8.Re1, but we have an extra option. }
12... b4
{ White cannot meet this with c4. Therefore, we can already disrupt White's pawn structure.  12...a5  is fine, too, with similar ideas. }
13. c4 Nf4 14. Qf3 Ne6
{ And White is already close to losing. At the very least, he will lose a pawn. }
