[Black "Classic - 8.Bb3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. O-O Bg7
{ In this chapter, we are looking at 8th move alternatives where White doesn't play Re1. Many lines transpose, so we look mostly at the lines that can create a different setup. }
8. Bb3
{ Most likely transposes toChapter 7.1. but it could also be a try to transpose to the Kasparov-Adams gamementioned in Chapter 7.1, with a clever move order. White wants to play c4 as quickly as possible and then start developing his pieces. }
8... Nd7 9. Nf3
{ Or  9.c4  Nc7  10.Nf3  .   9.Nxd7  is, as usual, not the most dangerous. For example:  9...Qxd7  10.c3  O-O  11.Nd2  b6!  not allowing the weakening of the c5-square; we can follow it up with ...Bb7 and ...c5 in the future. }
9... O-O 10. c4 { Very ambitious play by White. For  10.Re1  seeChapter 7.1. }
10... Nc7 11. Re1
{ Now  11...Nf6  would officially transpose to the Kasparov-Adams game. } 11...
e5
{ We want to target the centre quickly. And now is the right time - the bishop is slightly misplaced on  b3  at the moment.  11...Nf6?!  is Kasparov,G @@StartBracket@@2795@@EndBracket@@-Adams,M @@StartBracket@@2665@@EndBracket@@ Linares 1997. }
12. dxe5 Nc5
{ Suddenly, Black has a good initiative for the pawn. Notice how all our pieces have nice squares and possibilities. The bishop doesn't stand well on b3 at the moment. We play active and try to land our pieces on the best squares. For example: }
13. Bc2 Qxd1 { Trading queens here slightly misplaces White's pieces. } 14.
Rxd1 Re8 15. Bf4 Bg4 { Pinning the knight and thus targeting the e5-pawn. } 16.
Nbd2 N7e6 17. Bg3 { 17.Be3  Nd7  already wins back the pawn. } 17... f5
{ With very good counterplay for Black. All our pieces are very active. We're threatening ...f4, so probably White has to take en passant and unleash our dark-squared bishop. After  18.exf6  Bxf6  the b2-pawn is a target and ...Nd4 becomes an idea. }
