1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. O-O Bg7
{ In this chapter, we are looking at 8th move alternatives where White doesn't play Re1. Many lines transpose, so we look mostly at the lines that can create a different setup. }
8. Bb3
{ Most likely transposes toChapter 7.1. but it could also be a try to transpose to the Kasparov-Adams gamementioned in Chapter 7.1, with a clever move order. White wants to play c4 as quickly as possible and then start developing his pieces. }
8... Nd7 9. Nf3
{ Or  9.c4  Nc7  10.Nf3  .   9.Nxd7  is, as usual, not the most dangerous. For example:  9...Qxd7  10.c3  O-O  11.Nd2  b6!  not allowing the weakening of the c5-square; we can follow it up with ...Bb7 and ...c5 in the future. }
9... O-O 10. c4 { Very ambitious play by White. For  10.Re1  seeChapter 7.1. }
10... Nc7 11. Nc3 b5
{ We will be in trouble if we let White develop and consolidate. Therefore, we need to undermine the centre asap. }
12. c5
{ Closing down the position leads to a fight over the d5-square. For example: }
12... a5 13. a4 { 13.Re1  a4  14.Bc2  Nf6⇆  . } 13... b4 14. Ne2
{ 14.Ne4  Nf6  15.Nxf6+  Black can recapture with either piece with a decent position. }
14... Re8
{ 14...Nf6?!  is a bit awkward now as we cannot protect the c6-pawn with ...Ra6:  15.Ne5  and now  15...Qe8  could still be OK, but I prefer the text for sure.  15...Ra6?  16.Bc4!±  and White wins either the pawn or the exchange. }
15. Re1 Nf8 16. Ne5
{ 16.Bf4  Be6⇆  with a complicated position is a better choice. } 16... Bxe5
17. dxe5 Be6
{ This is already very pleasant for Black. White must choose between keeping the bishop pair or keeping queens on the board. Either choice offers weak pawns to attack. }
