[White "7.3) The Classic Nf3 Variation - Alternatives to 8.Re1"]
[Black "Classic - 8.Nd2 Nd7 9.Nef3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. O-O Bg7
{ In this chapter, we are looking at 8th move alternatives where White doesn't play Re1. Many lines transpose, so we look mostly at the lines that can create a different setup. }
8. Nd2
{ Slightly different from the  8.Re1  lines. White wants to develop his knight as quickly as possible. Notice how our positional trick ...Nb6, attacking the d4-pawn and threatening to grab the bishop pair, doesn't work here because the f7-pawn is unprotected. }
8... Nd7
{ 8...O-O  9.Ndf3  Nd7  10.Nd3!?  is now an extra option. It should still be fine, but why give White the option, right? I included a game just for reference, in case you do get a position like this.  10...b5  11.Bb3  a5  12.a3  N7b6  13.Nfe5  Qc7  14.Re1  Bf5  15.c3  Rad8  16.Qe2  a4  17.Ba2  f6  18.Nf3  Kh8  19.Nc5  e5⇆  and Black won in 36 moves in Godena,M @@StartBracket@@2519@@EndBracket@@-Bacrot,E @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ Liverpool 2008. }
9. Nef3 O-O 10. Re1
{ Placing the rook on the semi-open file is always a good move for White. }
10... b5
{ This transposes to eitherChapter 7.1. after  11.Bb3  or toChapter 7.2. after  11.Bf1  . }
11. Bxd5 cxd5 12. Qe2
{ As usual, this is fine for Black, though here we have to play a little bit differently. }
12... e6
{ 12...Re8  13.Qxb5  Rb8?  doesn't work anymore, as the f3-knight is defended by the d2-knight.  14.Qxd5  Bb7  . }
13. Qxb5 Qc7 14. c3 a5
{ With very decent compensation once again. We can advance the queenside and try to push in the centre as well with ...f6 and ...e5. }
*

