[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. O-O Bg7
{ In this chapter, we are looking at 8th move alternatives where White doesn't play Re1. Many lines transpose, so we look mostly at the lines that can create a different setup. }
8. Nd2
{ Slightly different from the  8.Re1  lines. White wants to develop his knight as quickly as possible. Notice how our positional trick ...Nb6, attacking the d4-pawn and threatening to grab the bishop pair, doesn't work here because the f7-pawn is unprotected. }
8... Nd7
{ 8...O-O  9.Ndf3  Nd7  10.Nd3!?  is now an extra option. It should still be fine, but why give White the option, right? I included a game just for reference, in case you do get a position like this.  10...b5  11.Bb3  a5  12.a3  N7b6  13.Nfe5  Qc7  14.Re1  Bf5  15.c3  Rad8  16.Qe2  a4  17.Ba2  f6  18.Nf3  Kh8  19.Nc5  e5⇆  and Black won in 36 moves in Godena,M @@StartBracket@@2519@@EndBracket@@-Bacrot,E @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ Liverpool 2008. }
9. Nxd7 Qxd7
{ With the bishop still aiming at our d5-knight, I'd rather take with the queen. }
10. Nf3
{ Having gone for a quick Nd2-Nf3, things are slightly different: White doesn't need to worry about the d4-pawn anymore.   10.c3  O-O  Here White once again doesn't have a better move than  11.Re1  , which transposes toChapter 7.2. }
10... O-O 11. Re1 b5 12. Bb3
{ 12.Bf1  a5  is more or less the same asChapter 7.2. } 12... Qd6
{ This might be a move to remember and the quickest way to develop without problems. We do not want to allow White to exchange on d5 when we have to recapture with the pawn.  12...Bb7?!  This plan is a bit slow this time. Thanks to his quick development, White can get a favourable position.  13.Ne5!  Qc7  14.Bxd5  cxd5  15.Bf4±  followed by Qd2 and Bh6 with a good initiative for White. }
13. Bg5 Bg4 { White can grab the pawn now, but that comes with a price. } 14.
Bxd5 { 14.c3  e6  is very solid again for Black. } 14... Qxd5 15. Bxe7 Rfe8 16.
c3 { Protecting d4. } 16... Qd7 { Chasing the bishop away. } 17. Bc5 Rxe1+ 18.
Qxe1 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Re8
{ And after all the exchanges, White is left with a damaged kingside and the e-file is under Black's control. }
