{ With the knight on e5, it is harder to play ...b5. Therefore, the bishop stands better on e6. }
12. Bb3 a5
{ Played by Simen Agdestein in 1994, it is the main move since then. Black tries to undermine the bishop, thus making sure White's c4 will have some drawbacks.   12...Qc7?!  illustrates how White can secure an advantage if we don't challenge c4.  13.c4!  Nb6  14.Bf4  and Black gets more and more cramped. }
13. c4 Nb6
{ This is dangerous for White - we can attack the bishop with ...a4, the very reason why we played ...a5 on our previous move. }
14. c5
{ The only move for White not to lose a pawn.  14.a3?  a4  15.Ba2  Bxe5  and however White recaptures, we win the c4-pawn.   14.a4?  Bxe5  15.Rxe5  Bxc4∓  and we have won a pawn. }
14... Nd7
{ I like to charge on the d4-pawn as soon as possible. If we put our knight on d5, although it would be well-positioned there, it stands in the way. }
15. Bxe6
{ 15.Nxd7!?  Bxb3  16.Qxb3  Qxd7  leaves Black very comfortable with White's weakness on d4. }
15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 { 16.Bb3  Nd7  is very comfortable for Black as well. }
16... fxe6
{ Our doubled e-pawns look a bit suspicious, but they cannot easily be attacked, and we are first to get our rooks on the d-file. }
*

