[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. O-O Bg7
{ In this chapter, we are looking at 8th move alternatives where White doesn't play Re1. Many lines transpose, so we look mostly at the lines that can create a different setup. }
8. Nd2
{ Slightly different from the  8.Re1  lines. White wants to develop his knight as quickly as possible. Notice how our positional trick ...Nb6, attacking the d4-pawn and threatening to grab the bishop pair, doesn't work here because the f7-pawn is unprotected. }
8... Nd7
{ 8...O-O  9.Ndf3  Nd7  10.Nd3!?  is now an extra option. It should still be fine, but why give White the option, right? I included a game just for reference, in case you do get a position like this.  10...b5  11.Bb3  a5  12.a3  N7b6  13.Nfe5  Qc7  14.Re1  Bf5  15.c3  Rad8  16.Qe2  a4  17.Ba2  f6  18.Nf3  Kh8  19.Nc5  e5⇆  and Black won in 36 moves in Godena,M @@StartBracket@@2519@@EndBracket@@-Bacrot,E @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ Liverpool 2008. }
9. Ndf3 { White develops as quickly as possible. } 9... Nxe5
{ We get a chance to take a pair of knights off the board. } 10. Nxe5 O-O 11.
Re1 Be6
{ With the knight on e5, it is harder to play ...b5. Therefore, the bishop stands better on e6. }
12. Bb3 a5
{ Played by Simen Agdestein in 1994, it is the main move since then. Black tries to undermine the bishop, thus making sure White's c4 will have some drawbacks.   12...Qc7?!  illustrates how White can secure an advantage if we don't challenge c4.  13.c4!  Nb6  14.Bf4  and Black gets more and more cramped. }
13. c3 Qc7 { Or  13...Qd6  . } 14. Nd3
{ To play against Black's ...c5. Other moves are not challenging:   14.Bg5  Rfd8  15.Bh4  c5⇆  and Black had good play in Stefansson,H  (2450)  -Kengis,E  (2545)  Gausdal 1991.   14.Nf3Ν  Bg4  15.h3  Bxf3  16.Qxf3  e6  followed by a timely ...c5.   14.h3Ν  with the idea of retreating the knight to f3 once it cannot be pinned.  14...Rad8  15.Nf3  c5⇆  and Black has the usual counterplay. }
14... Bf5 { Keeping the door open to exchanging the d3-knight. } 15. a4
{ 15.a3  Rad8  with similar play. } 15... Rad8
{ The rook is not doing much on a8 anymore, so it's time to put it on the semi-open d-file. }
16. Qf3
{ Now that White has burnt a tempo with the queen, it is a good time to exchange on d3. }
16... Bxd3 17. Qxd3 e5
{ We can comfortably break in the centre. We have a rook on the d-file and active pieces. }
