{ Protecting the f7-pawn. Now play becomes a bit different, although White does have some development issues due to the queen on f3. }
8. Nc3
{ White's idea is to put some pressure on our d5-knight. Fortunately, this isn't so dangerous, and we can leave the knight as it is. }
8... Bg7 9. Ne4 { This doesn't work if White is uncastled. } 9... Qb6
{ And White is in trouble. } 10. c3 Bxe5
{ One of the few times this is a good idea. We get a lot of initiative in return for giving up our important dark-squared bishop. }
11. dxe5 Nd7 12. Qg3 { The only move. Otherwise, White will lose a pawn. }
12... h5 13. h3
{ Creating a retreat square for the queen.  13.O-O?  is met by  13...h4  14.Qg5  Bf5-+  attacking the knight. We win the e5-pawn with a lot of pressure on the kingside. For example, ...h3 is in the cards. }
13... h4 14. Qh2 Rh5 { Yet this is fantastic for Black again. For example: }
15. Ng5 Nc7 16. Be2 Rxg5 17. Bxg5 Qxb2 18. Rd1 Bxa2
{ White cannot castle, so again we have tremendous compensation for the exchange. We can try to collect more pawns and advance on the queenside at some point. }
