[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7.4) The Classic Nf3 Variation - 7.Qf3?!"]
[Black "Classic - 9.Ne4?! #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. Qf3
{ Since f7 is under attack, we have to go for a different setup than our main lines. However, I consider this move inaccurate - the queen is not necessarily well placed on f3, and we get a free tempo to develop our bishop. }
7... Be6
{ Protecting the f7-pawn. Now play becomes a bit different, although White does have some development issues due to the queen on f3. }
8. Nc3
{ White's idea is to put some pressure on our d5-knight. Fortunately, this isn't so dangerous, and we can leave the knight as it is. }
8... Bg7 9. Ne4 { This doesn't work if White is uncastled. } 9... Qb6
{ And White is in trouble. } 10. c3 Bxe5
{ One of the few times this is a good idea. We get a lot of initiative in return for giving up our important dark-squared bishop. }
11. dxe5 Nd7 12. Qg3 { The only move. Otherwise, White will lose a pawn. }
12... h5 13. h4 Qc7 { Threatening to win the e5-pawn. } 14. f4
{ Or  14.O-O?!  Qxe5∓  . } 14... Qb6
{ And White is miraculously stuck with his development. For example: } 15. Ng5
{ 15.Qf2?  Nxc3!  and no matter which piece White takes, we win our piece back with an extra pawn.   15.Bd3  Bf5  and White still faces the same problems. }
15... Bf5 16. Qf2 Qxf2+ 17. Kxf2 Nc5
{ Followed by ...f6 and ...O-O-O. Black has a very pleasant position thanks to our more active pieces. }
*

