1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bc4 c6 7. Qf3
{ Since f7 is under attack, we have to go for a different setup than our main lines. However, I consider this move inaccurate - the queen is not necessarily well placed on f3, and we get a free tempo to develop our bishop. }
7... Be6
{ Protecting the f7-pawn. Now play becomes a bit different, although White does have some development issues due to the queen on f3. }
8. Nc3
{ White's idea is to put some pressure on our d5-knight. Fortunately, this isn't so dangerous, and we can leave the knight as it is. }
8... Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Ne4
{ Heading to the c5-square to attack our bishop.  10.Bg5??  f6  drops a piece.   10.Re1  Nc7  and White has some problems already. }
10... Nc7
{ Forcing the trade of light-squared bishops.  10...Qb6?!  would be a waste of time now. The white king is safe and our queen isn't well-placed here, hindering the development of our b8-knight.  11.c3  Bxe5  12.dxe5  Nd7  13.Qg3±  . }
11. Rd1 { White decides not to exchange on e6. } 11... Bxc4
{ 11...Bd5!?  is a solid alternative, with the idea ...Ne6.  12.Bxd5?!  cxd5  and we have improved our pawn structure. }
12. Nxc4 f5
{ A creative way to put some pressure. The idea is to chase the e4-knight away and then push forward. For example,  12...Nd7  13.a4⩲  and White is slightly better due to the space advantage. }
13. Nc5 b6 14. Nb3 Qd5 15. Qe2 { 15.Qxd5+  Nxd5=  is a roughly equal endgame. }
15... f4 16. f3 Nd7
{ With a complicated position. Black has lots of ideas to choose from. } *

