1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Bd3
{ This move is a rare guest, but a few years ago, Firouzja played it three times in his online blitz match against Carlsen. It was an interesting theoretical battle, yet we will soon deviate from it. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O
{ When White's bishop is not on c4, we don't have to play ...c6 as in the previous chapter with 6.Bc4.   7...c5?!  is a move too early.  8.Bb5+!  a very annoying check.  8...Nd7  9.Qf3  N5f6  10.Bxd7+  Bxd7  11.dxc5±  and we will struggle to win back the pawn. }
8. Re1
{ Protecting the e5-knight to prevent ...c5.  8.c4?!  Nb4∓  threatening to win a piece or the pawn on d4 and White would already be in huge trouble.   8.c3?!  c5!⩱  and the d4-pawn will become a huge liability.   8.Nf3  offers us many ways to equalise. For example,  8...Nc6  9.c3  e5=  is one of them. White actually might already be in some trouble. }
8... Nd7
{ 8...Nb4Ν  is an interesting alternative. The aim is to get the advantage of the bishop pair:A@@EndBracket@@  9.c3  Nxd3  and if  10.Qxd3!?  c5!  White is already in trouble.  11.dxc5??  Bxe5  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  and White loses a piece due to the back-rank threats. Better is  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/6p1/4N3/3P4/2Pn4/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nxd3  Bf5  Notice how White cannot comfortably develop his b1-knight to d2.  11.Bf4  Nc6!  aiming to play ...e5 at some point. Black is very comfortable here.B@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@'rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/6p1/4N3/1n1P4/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bf1?  already loses material.  9...Bxe5  10.Rxe5  N8c6-+  .C@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@'rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/6p1/4N3/1n1P4/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Be4  is the only way to keep the bishop pair.  9...N8c6  10.Nxc6  Nxc6  with chances for both sides after  11.c3  e5  12.d5  Na5⇆  or  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2n3p1/8/3PB3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.d5  Ne5  12.Nc3  e6⇆  when the position should be roughly equal.  The text was played in the before-mentioned match. One of the games continued: }
9. Nf3 { This occurred in the match three times. } 9... c5 10. c4 Nb4 11. d5 b5
{ Ironically, this was played in the first game of the match to reach this position. After checking with the engine, I think this is actually the best move. We care less about the bishop pair and more about winning back the pawn if White takes on b5.   11...Nxd3  was Carlsen's choice in the last two games. His idea was not to allow White to keep the light-squared bishop. Yet it gives his opponent some more options. I will show part of the game for reference.  12.Qxd3  b5  to disrupt the c4-d5 chain.  13.cxb5  Nb6  14.Nc3  and now  14...c4!?  would have been a useful intermediate move. The games went like this:A@@EndBracket@@  14...Bb7?!  15.Bg5  Nxd5  16.Na4!?  Rc8  17.Bxe7  c4  18.Qe4  Qxe7  19.Qxe7  Nxe7  20.Rxe7  Bxf3  21.gxf3  Rb8  22.Rc1  Rxb5  23.Rxc4⩲  Firouzja, A @@StartBracket@@2702@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2876@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020.B@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb2ppbp/6p1/1Ppn2B1/N7/3Q1N2/PP3PPP/R3R1K1 b - - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Nb6  17.Qxd8  Rfxd8  18.Nxc5  Bxf3  19.gxf3  Rd5  20.Bxe7  Bxb2  21.Rab1  Ba3  22.Na6  Bxe7  23.Rxe7⩲  with a draw in 35 moves in Firouzja,A @@StartBracket@@2702@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2876@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
12. Bg5 { Threatening to win the e7-pawn. Yet, this is a mistake. } 12... Bxb2
13. Bxe7 Qb6 14. Bxf8 Nxf8
