[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7.6) The Classic Nf3 Variation - 6.Be2"]
[Black "Classic - 8.Bf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. Be2
{ Another move that happened in the Firouzja-Carlsen match in 2020. The idea is to castle before playing c4. }
6... Bg7
{ Once again, we don't have to play ...c6 here as there is no threat. } 7. O-O
O-O 8. Bf3 { Ttrying to play against our ...c5 idea. } 8... c6
{ Since the bishop is a bit misplaced on f3, we are going to play like in the Bc4 mainline now, only with a better version, as White needed to spend an extra tempo to go to f3. }
9. c3
{ 9.Re1  Nd7  and White is forced to exchange on d7, as the d4-pawn is still unprotected.  10.a4?!  Nxe5  11.dxe5  Bf5  is more than fine for Black.  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nppbp/2p3p1/3nN3/3P4/5B2/PPP2PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nxd7  Qxd7  and Black is fine. We can develop and start preparing our break in the centre. }
9... Nd7 10. Nd3 e5 { This is also absolutely fine for Black. For example: }
11. Bxd5 cxd5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Be3 Bf5 15. Bd4
{ We have been following the game: Van der Wiel,J @@StartBracket@@2509@@EndBracket@@-Feygin,M @@StartBracket@@2475@@EndBracket@@ Essen 2002. }
15... Re8
{ And our superior development secures us enough compensation for our isolated pawn. For example,  16.Bxe5  Rxe5  17.Nd2  We cannot allow the knight to land on d4. Or we can, but that would be highly unpleasant.  17...Bd3  18.Re1  Rxe1+  19.Qxe1  d4  and we have solved our only problem. }
*

