1. e4 d5
{ It's quite interesting to compare this chapter with the 2...Nf6 Scandinavian, in particular this variation: }
2. exd5 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nxd5 4. d4 g6 5. c4 Nb6
{ In our mainline, the white knight is on e5 instead of f3, which is a big difference in Black's favour. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7.7) The Classic Nf3 Variation - 6.c4!?"]
[Black "Classic - 7.c5!? #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3
{ 4.c4  is a different move order for this chapter.  4...Nb6  5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  and we transpose to this chapter's mainline. }
4... dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. c4
{ Not exactly in the spirit of the Nf3 system, but still a viable option. }
6... Nb6 7. c5
{ This has been tried a few times, in the spirit of the above-mentioned 2...Nf6 Scandinavian. It's a bit of an underrated line, in my opinion. It's good to keep in mind that White has tricks up his sleeve with Qb3 and Qf3. }
7... Nd5
{ The drawback of White's move. Our knight has a wonderful outpost on d5. } 8.
Qb3 Bg7 9. Nc3 { Not as harmful as it looks.  9.Bc4  e6!  see 8.Bc4. } 9... e6
{ A slight concession as our bishop on e6 is blocked, yet it is only temporary. }
10. Be2
{ 10.Nxd5  Qxd5  11.Qxd5   @@StartBracket@@  11.Bc4?  Qxg2  and White loses a pawn.  @@EndBracket@@  11...exd5  We have reached an equal endgame. For example:  12.Bf4  Nd7  13.Nf3  c6=  or  @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/pppn1pbp/6p1/2PpN3/3P1B2/8/PP3PPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Nxd7  Bxd7  14.O-O-O  O-O-O=  . }
10... O-O 11. O-O Nc6 { This move solves all our problems. } 12. Nxc6
{ 12.Nf3?  Nxd4  drops a pawn. } 12... bxc6 13. Rd1 Bd7
{ Notice how White cannot develop the dark-squared bishop. We, on the other hand, have completed our development and can start thinking of actions in the centre or queenside. }
*

