[Black "Classic - 7.c5!? #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3
{ 4.c4  is a different move order for this chapter.  4...Nb6  5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  and we transpose to this chapter's mainline. }
4... dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. c4
{ Not exactly in the spirit of the Nf3 system, but still a viable option. }
6... Nb6 7. c5
{ This has been tried a few times, in the spirit of the above-mentioned 2...Nf6 Scandinavian. It's a bit of an underrated line, in my opinion. It's good to keep in mind that White has tricks up his sleeve with Qb3 and Qf3. }
7... Nd5
{ The drawback of White's move. Our knight has a wonderful outpost on d5. } 8.
Bc4 Bg7 { 8...Be6?  9.Qb3!  . } 9. Nxf7 { This trick doesn't work now. } 9...
Kxf7 10. Qf3+
{ Winning back the piece, but at a cost - the d4-pawn is still unprotected. }
10... Ke8 { 10...Ke6??  11.Qe4+  and White wins more than just a piece back. }
11. Bxd5 Rf8
{ Our king will be stuck in the centre for some time, so this move is perfectly justified. The white queen needs to keep an eye on the d5-bishop now. }
12. Qb3 { 12.Qe4?  loses material to  12...Bf5  . } 12... c6 13. Bf3 Qxd4
{ Our queen stands nicely here, restricting White's development and speeding up our own. For example,  14.Be3??  Qxb2  . It seems that we will have problems with our king, but that is not such a big deal at the moment. White hasn't developed yet either, and if we are quick ourselves, we should be more than fine. For example: }
14. Nc3 Na6
{ Quick development. Taking the c5-pawn with the queen is too slow. } 15. Be3
Qb4
{ This move keeps our position healthy. White is forced to exchange queens, after which we have no problems. }
*

