1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3
{ 4.c4  is a different move order for this chapter.  4...Nb6  5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  and we transpose to this chapter's mainline. }
4... dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. c4
{ Not exactly in the spirit of the Nf3 system, but still a viable option. }
6... Nb6 7. c5
{ This has been tried a few times, in the spirit of the above-mentioned 2...Nf6 Scandinavian. It's a bit of an underrated line, in my opinion. It's good to keep in mind that White has tricks up his sleeve with Qb3 and Qf3. }
7... Nd5
{ The drawback of White's move. Our knight has a wonderful outpost on d5. } 8.
Bc4 Bg7 { 8...Be6?  9.Qb3!  . } 9. Nc3 Be6
{ Setting some nasty discoveries against the c4-bishop if White is not careful. }
10. Qb3
{ It seems that White has us! Instead,  10.Bxd5  Bxd5  11.O-O  O-O  is no problem. }
10... Nxc3 { But no, Black is fine after this. } 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Qxe6
{ Now Black wins material. White should play  12.bxc3  Bxe5  13.dxe5  Qd5  when everything is defended, and the position is roughly equal. White has two weak pawns, and our rook will come to the f-file. }
12... Qxd4 { White's checks are no more than checks. } 13. Qc8+
{ 13.Qf7+  Kd8-+  . } 13... Qd8 14. Qxd8+ Kxd8 15. Nf7+ Ke8 16. Nxh8 Bxh8
{ Black has two pieces for the rook and a dominant position. White cannot take on c3 as that drops the a1-rook. }
*

