1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3
{ 4.c4  is a different move order for this chapter.  4...Nb6  5.Nf3  dxe5  6.Nxe5  g6  and we transpose to this chapter's mainline. }
4... dxe5 5. Nxe5 g6 6. c4
{ Not exactly in the spirit of the Nf3 system, but still a viable option. }
6... Nb6 7. Nc3
{ Almost universally played, yet there are some small sidelines.   7.Be2  Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Nc3  c5  will transposehere.   7.Be3  Bg7  8.Nc3  c5  transposeshere. }
7... Bg7
{ Now  8.Nf3?!  would not make sense - White has wasted an extra tempo without developing.  8...Bg4  9.Be3  e6!  followed by ...Nc6 should give White some headaches. After  @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp1ppbp/1n4p1/8/2PP2b1/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9.c5  Nd5  Black is a tempo up compared to the 2...Nf6 Scandinavian line. Seethe informational for comparison.  10.Bc4  e6  and White still has to solve the problem of the d4-pawn. }
8. Bf4
{ Played from the White side by one of the leading experts in the Alekhine, Oleskandr Bortnyk. White is protecting the knight with the bishop and also connecting the queen with the a1-rook, thus neutralizing our ...c5 break. This move has one drawback - the d4-pawn is still slightly unprotected. }
8... Nc6
{ This is therefore my suggestion. We want to get rid of the e5-knight and start targeting the d4-pawn.   8...O-O?!  has been played before.  9.Qd2!Ν  scares me a bit. White wants to protect the d4-pawn with Rd1 before developing the kingside. For example:A:@@EndBracket@@  9...Be6  10.b3  N8d7  11.Qe3!  and once again, it's hard to find a breakthrough.B:@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/1n4p1/4N3/2PP1B2/2N5/PP1Q1PPP/R3KB1R b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...N8d7  10.Qe3  Nxe5  11.Bxe5  Bxe5  12.Qxe5±  followed by Be2 and O-O and White has a clear space-advantage.C:@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/1n4p1/4N3/2PP1B2/2N5/PP1Q1PPP/R3KB1R b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nc6  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Rd1!+-  and I have trouble finding a breakthrough with Black.  11...Be6  12.b3  Qd7  13.Qe3  . }
9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Be5
{ It's a good sign if White decides to spend an extra tempo to defend d4.  10.Be3  O-O  11.Rc1  e5?  12.dxe5  Bxe5  and even though our pawn structure is slightly damaged, we have more than enough development/activity to compensate for that. }
10... Bxe5 11. dxe5 O-O 12. b3 a5 13. a4
{ White is trying to keep the lowest number of pawn islands, yet this weakens his queenside considerably. For  13.Be2  see 12.Be2. }
13... Bf5 14. Be2 Qxd1+ 15. Bxd1 { 15.Rxd1?  Bc2  and Black wins a pawn. }
15... Nd7 { Rerouting the knight to start targeting the b3-pawn. } 16. f4 Nc5
{ And Black is already close to winning due to White's weaknesses. } *

