{ Trying to exchange bishops quickly would be my preferred approach, but other moves are possible as well.  14...Qe7?!  15.Ne4!  makes it a bit difficult for us to develop our knight to c6 - we need to defend our c5-pawn.   14...Qc7!?  prepares a pawn sacrifice. We want to play ...Nc6, yet our pawn is still hanging on c5 if we do. That is not a problem, though, as we will get good compensation for the pawn. If  15.Rb1  Nc6!  16.Bxc5  Rfd8  17.Qc2  Qe5  18.Be3  Nd4=∞  we get very active pieces in return for the pawn.  @@StartFEN@@rn3rk1/ppq2pb1/1n2p1p1/2p5/2P5/2N1B3/PP2BPPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 2 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Ne4  Rd8  16.Qc2  Nc6!  our knight gets to the most favourable square. It is worth sacrificing our c-pawn for that.  17.Nxc5  Nd4  18.Bxd4  Rxd4  19.Nb3  Rdd8  Once again, with excellent compensation. Our bishop on g7 is a beast, and White has problems protecting the b2-pawn. }
