{ Not exactly in the spirit of the Nf3 system, but still a viable option. }
6... Nb6 7. Nc3
{ Almost universally played, yet there are some small sidelines.   7.Be2  Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Nc3  c5  will transposehere.   7.Be3  Bg7  8.Nc3  c5  transposeshere. }
7... Bg7
{ Now  8.Nf3?!  would not make sense - White has wasted an extra tempo without developing.  8...Bg4  9.Be3  e6!  followed by ...Nc6 should give White some headaches. After  @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp1ppbp/1n4p1/8/2PP2b1/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9.c5  Nd5  Black is a tempo up compared to the 2...Nf6 Scandinavian line. Seethe informational for comparison.  10.Bc4  e6  and White still has to solve the problem of the d4-pawn. }
8. Be3 { 8.Be2  c5  9.Be3  O-O  transposes to 8.Be3. } 8... c5
{ We want to undermine White's centre as soon as possible.  8...O-O?!  This gives White the option to solve the problem of the d4-pawn.  9.Qb3!  and now many options as possible, such as  9...Be6!?  ,  9...Nc6!?  or  9...c5  10.Rd1  solidifying the d4-pawn.  10...cxd4  11.Bxd4  Qe8  12.c5  and I would not want to play this position. }
9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Be6
{ A move to remember. We are still targeting White's c4-pawn and keeping intact the fragile relationship between the d4-pawn and the knight on e5.   10...cxd4  11.Bxd4  gives White a solid position where Black has a hard time creating counterplay. We want to avoid this structure. For example:  11...Be6  12.b3⩲  and we really can't do much. Our b6-knight is awkward and our pressure on the h8-a1 diagonal neutralised. }
11. d5 { Leaving the e5-knight unprotected but attacking our bishop. } 11...
Bxd5
{ This solves most of our problems.  11...Bxe5?  12.dxe6±  is not at all favourable for Black. The pawn on e6 gives Black much trouble.   11...Bc8?  12.f4  and White has a dream position with no weaknesses and a lot more space. }
12. Nxg6 { White's best move. } 12... hxg6
{ Keeping our pawn structure intact. } 13. Nxd5 Bxb2
{ This is a bit scary as we allow the rook to enter the b-file. Yet with all the exchanges following, this should still be fine for Black. Still,  my recommendation   @@StartFEN@@'21397158/#/13/b'@@EndFEN@@ is  13...e6  . }
14. Rb1 Bd4
{ Immediately giving the pawn back. 14...Bg7? 15. Bxc5±  and White has all the pressure. }
15. Bxd4 cxd4 16. Qxd4 Nc6
{ A few correspondence games have been played in this position. For example: }
17. Qe3
{ 17.Qd2  e6  and the knight is lost to the pin.   17.Qb2!?  Nxd5  18.Rfd1  Qb6  19.cxd5  Qxb2  20.Rxb2  Na5  and White had some pressure, but not much, in Kermer,W @@StartBracket@@2324@@EndBracket@@-Pavlov,V @@StartBracket@@2427@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017. }
17... Nxd5 18. cxd5 Qxd5 19. Bf3
{ Or  19.Rxb7  Qxa2=  and a draw should be imminent as White does have enough activity for the pawn. }
19... Qd7
{ White has enough compensation for the pawn but not enough to claim an advantage. I'll keep the games in for reference in case you want to see how a game could progress.   20.Rfd1  Qc7  21.h4  Rad8  22.Rdc1  Kg7  23.Qxa7  Qf4  24.Bxc6  bxc6  25.Qxe7  Rfe8  26.Qg5  Qxg5  27.hxg5  Rd2  28.Rxc6  Re5  29.Rbc1  Rxa2  30.R6c5  Ree2  31.Rf1  Rab2  32.Rd5  and a draw was agreed in Nordal,S @@StartBracket@@2238@@EndBracket@@-Schmidt,L  @@StartBracket@@2415@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018.   20.h4  Rad8  21.Rfc1  Kg7  22.Rc5  Nd4  23.Rxb7  Nxf3+  24.Qxf3  Qd1+  25.Qxd1  Rxd1+  26.Kh2  Rh8  27.Kh3  and a draw was agreed in Mandviwala,P @@StartBracket@@2277@@EndBracket@@ -Jeute,V @@StartBracket@@2255@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2013. }
*

