7. O-O Nc6 8. Re1
{ Indirectly protecting e5.   8.h3?!  is clever - we cannot take the e5-pawn.  8...Bxf3?!  is not the most accurate:  9.Bxf3  and now, in any case, we should play  9...Bc5=  with a roughly equal position - White still has problems defending the e5-pawn.  9...Nxe5?  10.Bxd5  Qxd5  11.Qxd5  exd5  12.Re1  and White will win a piece.   @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1p3/3nP3/6b1/5N1P/PPP1BPP1/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bh5  will transpose to other lines, only with h3 and ...Bh5 included. That is no problem:  9.g4?  too weakening  9...Bg6∓  . Black has ...h5 ideas. }
8... Ndb4
{ A very nice move that targets the c2 pawn. White has trouble defending it - we are threatening to exchange the queen. }
9. a3
{ Better is  9.Bd2  though White's pieces look rather uncomfortable after  9...Bf5  10.Na3  Bc5⩱  . }
9... Qxd1 10. Bxd1 Bxf3
{ Disrupting White's kingside pawn structure. White cannot take back with the bishop as it's defending c2. }
11. gxf3 Nd5 { Black has a much healthier position. } *

