1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5
{ 4...Bg4  is very often played as well. White should reply with  5.Be2  ,  5.c4  or  5.Bc4  .  5.h3?!  is not the best, but I'll show it here because after  5...Bxf3  6.Qxf3  dxe5  7.dxe5  e6  we transpose toour main position in this chapter. }
5. dxe5
{ I have not encountered this move in my games, but it has been played surprisingly often and occurs mainly via the above-mentioned move order. I don't find it dangerous, but it possesses interesting positional nuances. }
5... Bg4
{ We must develop our bishop as soon as possible.  5...Nc6?!  6.Bb5!  is quite annoying to face. For example:  6...Bg4  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  e6  9.O-O⩲  and White has the advantage due to the pin, whereas after  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp1pppp/2n5/1B1nP3/6b1/5N1P/PPP2PP1/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bh5  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.e6!  ±  with this very thematic pawn sacrifice, White went on to win in the game Grischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2772@@EndBracket@@ -Bortnyk,O @@StartBracket@@2610@@EndBracket@@ Riadh 2017.   5...Bf5?!  6.Nd4!  and again we have problems with White's e6 push. }
6. Be2
{ The most played move in this position. However, I found it less convincing than  6.h3  . }
6... e6
{ Now, if White plays h3, we can comfortably retreat the bishop because White's e6 push is off the table. }
7. O-O Nc6 8. c4 { Ambitious, yet risky. } 8... Nb6 9. Qc2
{ Keeping queens on the board is a good idea for White. This move also makes room for Rd1, which creates a bit of a problem for us - the queen doesn't have a comfortable square to retreat to. }
9... Nd7
{ Targeting e5.  9...Bxf3?!  10.Bxf3  Nxe5  11.Bxb7  is not a bad trade for White as it leaves Black with many weak squares on the queenside. }
10. Bf4
{ Including  10.Rd1?!  actually helps Black.  10...Qc8!  protecting b7, so now we can take on f3 and then on e5.  11.Bf4  Bxf3  12.Bxf3  Ndxe5∓  wins a pawn. }
10... Qc8
{ We are threatening to take on e5.  10...h6!?  A creative way of developing. The idea is ...Qe7, ...g5 and ...Bg7.  11.Rd1  g5  . }
11. Re1 { Indirectly protecting e5. } 11... Be7 12. Nc3 Bf5 13. Qd2 O-O
{ And the position is roughly equal. Black needs to get the queen to a good square, but that's all the problem we have. We have good active pieces in return, with the rook coming to d8 and ...Nc5-...Nd3 as a potential idea. }
