{ The most played move. } 9... Bc5
{ This has only occurred once, according to my database. Black players tend to go for the ...c6 setup quite instinctively. Yet, in this particular position, there is no need to play  9...c6  as White doesn't need to take on d5. Still, it is a decent move, intending to advance on the queenside. }
10. O-O
{ 10.Bxd5?  only helps Black in this case.  10...exd5  11.O-O  O-O  and we are fine. }
10... O-O 11. Kh1
{ A clever move to enable the development of the knight to d2. } 11... f6
{ Positionally, this looks kind of awful - our pawn structure will be broken up. However, we will get a lot of active possibilities.  11...c6  is a decent alternative.  12.Nd2  b5  13.Bb3  Qc7  14.Nf3  a5⩲  with a solid position for Black, although I would prefer White in this position due to the slight space advantage and bishop pair.   Note that @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1n1ppp/2p1p3/2bnP3/2B5/7P/PPPNQPP1/R1B2R1K b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nf4?  doesn't work anymore and shows how clever White's 11th move has been.  13.Qe4  Qg5??  14.Nb3  and we lose a piece because, with the white king on h1, we no longer have ...Nxh3. }
12. exf6 Qxf6
{ White has many positional trumps, but we have more development and active pieces. All in all, we can assess the position as roughly equal. For example: }
13. Nd2 Nf4 14. Qf3 { Intending Ne4. } 14... Ne5 15. Qxb7 Bb6
{ A prophylactic move against Ne4. White can't do anything and suffers from development issues. Mating ideas will occur if White isn't precise. For example: }
16. Qe4
{ 16.Bb3?  illustrates the dangers of White's position.  16...Nxh3!  17.gxh3  c6  with powerful attacking ideas like ...Qh6/...Qf5 and ...Qxh3. Our rooks can eventually join the attack, whereas White's pieces are passive, and the queen is offside. }
16... Rad8 17. Nb3 Nxc4 18. Qxc4 Nxg2
{ Sacrificing the knight to open up the white king's position. } 19. Kxg2 Qf3+
20. Kh2 Bxf2 21. Qxe6+ Kh8 22. Bd2 Qg3+ { And Black has at least a perpetual. }
