[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7.8) The Classic Nf3 Variation - 5.dxe5!?"]
[Black "Classic - Alternative to 8...Nd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5
{ 4...Bg4  is very often played as well. White should reply with  5.Be2  ,  5.c4  or  5.Bc4  .  5.h3?!  is not the best, but I'll show it here because after  5...Bxf3  6.Qxf3  dxe5  7.dxe5  e6  we transpose toour main position in this chapter. }
5. dxe5
{ I have not encountered this move in my games, but it has been played surprisingly often and occurs mainly via the above-mentioned move order. I don't find it dangerous, but it possesses interesting positional nuances. }
5... Bg4
{ We must develop our bishop as soon as possible.  5...Nc6?!  6.Bb5!  is quite annoying to face. For example:  6...Bg4  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  e6  9.O-O⩲  and White has the advantage due to the pin, whereas after  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp1pppp/2n5/1B1nP3/6b1/5N1P/PPP2PP1/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bh5  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.e6!  ±  with this very thematic pawn sacrifice, White went on to win in the game Grischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2772@@EndBracket@@ -Bortnyk,O @@StartBracket@@2610@@EndBracket@@ Riadh 2017.   5...Bf5?!  6.Nd4!  and again we have problems with White's e6 push. }
6. h3
{ Trying to solve the problem of the pin as soon as possible. Exchanges are simply good for Black:  6.Nc3?!  Nxc3  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  8.bxc3  Bxf3  9.gxf3  e6⩱  White's pawn structure is in complete shambles.   6.c4?!  Nb4!  and exchanging on d8 is far too dangerous for White - we have much more active pieces and development. }
6... Bxf3
{ 6...Bh5?!  runs into the extremely dangerous pawn sacrifice  7.e6!  . For example,  7...fxe6  8.Be2  Nc6  9.O-O  Qd7  10.Ng5  Bg6  11.Re1±  and White has tremendous pressure on the e6-pawn. Notice also how our f8-bishop will not develop in the foreseeable future. }
7. Qxf3 e6
{ We have now transposed to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p4/3nP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg4  variation mentioned at the beginning.   I have tried to figure out an easy way to remember where the Black pieces need to go. In general: we almost always play ...Nc6, except if White plays  8.Qe4  ,  8.a3  or  8.Nc3  . }
8. Bc4 { One of the best squares to put the bishop, targeting our d5-knight. }
8... Nc6
{ This is still possible. I chose  8...Nd7  asour mainline because it is the strongest move against  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3nP3/8/5Q1P/PPP2PP1/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qe4  and could transpose. }
9. Qe4 Qd7 { We want to develop quickly. } 10. Nd2
{ 10.O-O  O-O-O  11.Nd2  transposes. } 10... O-O-O 11. O-O Nb6
{ With our rook on d8, it makes sense to move the knight to use the open d-file. }
12. Bb5
{ 12.Bb3  Qd4⇆  Black has more active pieces, which more than compensates for White's bishop pair. }
12... a6
{ White can trade everything on c6 and keep a small plus due to their slightly better queenside pawn structure. }
