[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Safe 3.Nc3"]
[Black "The safe 3.Nc3 - Petroff & Rubinstein French move orders"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ 1...e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  dxe4  The move that signifies the Rubinstein French Variation.  4.Nxe4  Nd7  5.Nf3  Ngf6  This position is quite similar to the mainline of this chapter. }
2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 { Or  5.d4  d5  . } 5... Nxc3 6. dxc3
{ This is one of the mainlines of the Petroff, which could transpose to a variation in our chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Safe 3.Nc3"]
[Black "The safe 3.Nc3 - 4.Qf3?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3
{ I think this move is slightly underappreciated. It is a safe line where White doesn't overextend with pawn advances, and there are even interesting new ways to keep things fresh and complicated. For example, with  3...e6  4.Ne4  . I expect to see more 3.Nc3 in the future. }
3... e6
{ A very sound reaction. We protect our knight and develop at the same time.  3...Nxc3!?  4.dxc3  d6  and now  5.Nf3!?  is good - Black will hesitate to exchange on e5. However, after  5.exd6  exd6  6.Nf3  we have transposed to a5.Nc3 Petroff.As I mentioned, I like to keep the repertoire original and not let it transpose to other openings unless there is a good reason to. This line is one of the main lines in the Petroff. Therefore, I'm not recommending this in our repertoire, although it should be perfectly fine for Black.   3...Nb6?!  is not the best, but certainly is in the spirit of the Alekhine. We keep the knight on the board and try to break in the centre with ...d6, as usual. }
4. Qf3 { Attacking our knight. } 4... Nb4
{ A sound reaction. White's best move is to retreat the queen to d1. } 5. Qe4
{ Ironically,  5.Qd1  is the best move.  5...d6⇆  and White hasn't achieved anything with the queen sortie. }
5... N8c6 6. a3 d5 7. exd6 f5
{ And White loses material - the queen has to move and thus leave c2 unprotected.   Note that  8.dxc7  won't save White: after  8...Qd7  ,  8...Qe7  or  8...Qf6  he has run out of resources.  8...Qxc7?  is less clear, as it allows  9.Nb5  followed by Qc4 and everything is protected. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Safe 3.Nc3"]
[Black "The safe 3.Nc3 - 4.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3
{ I think this move is slightly underappreciated. It is a safe line where White doesn't overextend with pawn advances, and there are even interesting new ways to keep things fresh and complicated. For example, with  3...e6  4.Ne4  . I expect to see more 3.Nc3 in the future. }
3... e6
{ A very sound reaction. We protect our knight and develop at the same time.  3...Nxc3!?  4.dxc3  d6  and now  5.Nf3!?  is good - Black will hesitate to exchange on e5. However, after  5.exd6  exd6  6.Nf3  we have transposed to a5.Nc3 Petroff.As I mentioned, I like to keep the repertoire original and not let it transpose to other openings unless there is a good reason to. This line is one of the main lines in the Petroff. Therefore, I'm not recommending this in our repertoire, although it should be perfectly fine for Black.   3...Nb6?!  is not the best, but certainly is in the spirit of the Alekhine. We keep the knight on the board and try to break in the centre with ...d6, as usual. }
4. Bc4 Nxc3
{ 4...Nf4!?  is a decent alternative for the adventurous player.  5.g3  Ng6  White has weakened the kingside, and we can now start breaking free with ...d6. }
5. dxc3 { 5.bxc3?!  d5  with easy development. } 5... d5 6. exd6 cxd6
{ We can develop normally with a roughly equal position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Safe 3.Nc3"]
[Black "The safe 3.Nc3 - 4.d4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3
{ I think this move is slightly underappreciated. It is a safe line where White doesn't overextend with pawn advances, and there are even interesting new ways to keep things fresh and complicated. For example, with  3...e6  4.Ne4  . I expect to see more 3.Nc3 in the future. }
3... e6
{ A very sound reaction. We protect our knight and develop at the same time.  3...Nxc3!?  4.dxc3  d6  and now  5.Nf3!?  is good - Black will hesitate to exchange on e5. However, after  5.exd6  exd6  6.Nf3  we have transposed to a5.Nc3 Petroff.As I mentioned, I like to keep the repertoire original and not let it transpose to other openings unless there is a good reason to. This line is one of the main lines in the Petroff. Therefore, I'm not recommending this in our repertoire, although it should be perfectly fine for Black.   3...Nb6?!  is not the best, but certainly is in the spirit of the Alekhine. We keep the knight on the board and try to break in the centre with ...d6, as usual. }
4. d4 Nxc3
{ For  4...d6?!  5.Ne4!  see4.Ne4. I think that is the best line for White, so I would like to avoid it if possible. }
5. bxc3 d5
{ 5...d6!?  should be OK for Black too.  6.f4  Yet, this move worries me a bit, as in some situations, it might actually be better to play ...d6-...d5. That's why 5...d5 strikes me as more accurate.  6...dxe5  7.fxe5  Qh4+  This seems very good for Black, yet looks can be deceiving.  8.Ke2!  c5  9.Nf3  Qd8  10.Kf2  And I like  White's position better. White is going to play Bd3, Rf1 and Kg1, and soon will have a lot of potential on the kingside. Our c8-bishop lacks prospects. }
6. f4
{ White solidifies their centre.  6.exd6?!  cxd6=  looks very pleasant for Black.   6.Nf3  c5  is very pleasant for Black as well. }
6... c5 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. Be2 Qa5 9. Bd2 c4
{ The position is comparable to the Winawer French, which arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  Bb4  . There, Black's dark-squared bishop is usually traded for White's knight on c3.   I much prefer this position - our bishop of f8 is quite pleasant to have. We usually want to castle queenside and make sure that White doesn't get initiative on the kingside. After  10.O-O  Be7  11.Rb1  b6  we can follow up with ...Bd7 and ...O-O-O. Notice how taking the a2-pawn could backfire - White can, at the very least, make a perpetual with Ra1 and Rb1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Safe 3.Nc3"]
[Black "The safe 3.Nc3 - 4.Nxd5 exd5 5.d4 d6 6.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3
{ I think this move is slightly underappreciated. It is a safe line where White doesn't overextend with pawn advances, and there are even interesting new ways to keep things fresh and complicated. For example, with  3...e6  4.Ne4  . I expect to see more 3.Nc3 in the future. }
3... e6
{ A very sound reaction. We protect our knight and develop at the same time.  3...Nxc3!?  4.dxc3  d6  and now  5.Nf3!?  is good - Black will hesitate to exchange on e5. However, after  5.exd6  exd6  6.Nf3  we have transposed to a5.Nc3 Petroff.As I mentioned, I like to keep the repertoire original and not let it transpose to other openings unless there is a good reason to. This line is one of the main lines in the Petroff. Therefore, I'm not recommending this in our repertoire, although it should be perfectly fine for Black.   3...Nb6?!  is not the best, but certainly is in the spirit of the Alekhine. We keep the knight on the board and try to break in the centre with ...d6, as usual. }
4. Nxd5
{ The most played move. Optically, it leads to quite dull positions where it's hard to find an advantage for either player. Yet there are some tricky options for White to consider. }
4... exd5 5. d4
{ 5.Qf3?!  c6  6.d4  d6  and we continue our development normally, while it is doubtful that the queen stands better on f3.   For  5.Nf3  d6  6.d4  seehere. }
5... d6
{ This position is perfectly fine for Black. We want to develop smoothly and castle fast. If  6.exd6?!  Bxd6⩱  Black is first to develop, castle and get a rook to the e-file. }
6. Bf4
{ Not the best way of protecting the e5-pawn, although the bishop is well placed on the h2-b8 diagonal. }
6... dxe5 7. Bxe5 { 7.dxe5?!  c5!  8.Nf3  Nc6  will transposehere. } 7... Nc6
{ Exchanging a bishop for our knight would benefit us. } 8. Bb5 Qe7
{ Both bishops are targets. } 9. Ne2
{ Unpinning the e5-bishop and providing defence against ...Qb4+.  9.Nf3?  Qb4+  and Black wins a piece. }
9... Bd7 { 9...Qb4+?!  10.Nc3  Qxb2?  11.Nxd5+-  is very dangerous for Black. }
10. Bxc7 Qb4+ 11. Nc3 Qxb2
{ White is in trouble.  12.Nxd5  is not possible now because the bishop on b5 is hanging and the c7-bishop is obstructing the fork.  White's only way to avoid losing a piece is the forced sequence  12.Qe2+  Be7  13.Kd2  and now Black wins a pawn and liquidates into an excellent endgame with  13...Nxd4  14.Bxd7+  Kxd7  15.Qg4+  Kxc7  16.Qxd4  and the precise  16...Qb4  forcing the queen trade since  17.Qxg7??  is met by  17...d4-+  . }
*

