{ Basically, all you need to know. Now play becomes very natural, and White has to be careful not to get worse. For example: }
9. c3 { To create a square for the bishop on d3. } 9... Nc6 10. O-O Be6 11. Re1
{ We have been following the game: Vallejo Pons,F @@StartBracket@@2635@@EndBracket@@-Rodriguez Vargas,O @@StartBracket@@2465@@EndBracket@@ Mondariz 2002. }
11... g5
{ This is very pleasant for Black. We want to push the knight away from f3 and launch a kingside attack. Our king has a choice. Depending on the next couple of moves, we can decide to put the king on f8 or to try and castle long. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Safe 3.Nc3"]
[Black "The safe 3.Nc3 - 4.Nxd5 exd5 5.d4 d6 6.Nf3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3
{ I think this move is slightly underappreciated. It is a safe line where White doesn't overextend with pawn advances, and there are even interesting new ways to keep things fresh and complicated. For example, with  3...e6  4.Ne4  . I expect to see more 3.Nc3 in the future. }
3... e6
{ A very sound reaction. We protect our knight and develop at the same time.  3...Nxc3!?  4.dxc3  d6  and now  5.Nf3!?  is good - Black will hesitate to exchange on e5. However, after  5.exd6  exd6  6.Nf3  we have transposed to a5.Nc3 Petroff.As I mentioned, I like to keep the repertoire original and not let it transpose to other openings unless there is a good reason to. This line is one of the main lines in the Petroff. Therefore, I'm not recommending this in our repertoire, although it should be perfectly fine for Black.   3...Nb6?!  is not the best, but certainly is in the spirit of the Alekhine. We keep the knight on the board and try to break in the centre with ...d6, as usual. }
4. Nxd5
{ The most played move. Optically, it leads to quite dull positions where it's hard to find an advantage for either player. Yet there are some tricky options for White to consider. }
4... exd5 5. d4
{ 5.Qf3?!  c6  6.d4  d6  and we continue our development normally, while it is doubtful that the queen stands better on f3.   For  5.Nf3  d6  6.d4  seehere. }
5... d6
{ This position is perfectly fine for Black. We want to develop smoothly and castle fast. If  6.exd6?!  Bxd6⩱  Black is first to develop, castle and get a rook to the e-file. }
6. Nf3 dxe5
{ Here, White has a choice.   6...Bg4?!  has been played quite often, but  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  dxe5  9.dxe5±  with a quick O-O-O is very pleasant for White, and after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/3p4/3pP3/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  7...Bh5  8.Qe2!Ν  Black has a problem due to the Qb5 threat.   6...Nc6!?  has also been tried quite often and is a decent alternative. Yet, blocking the c-pawn with the knight isn't always the healthiest approach, plus Bb5 can now pin the knight. For example,  7.Bb5  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Re1  Bg4  10.c3  dxe5  11.dxe5⩲  and I believe White's position is better. }
7. Nxe5
{ This symmetrical position has many similarities with the Petroff. So far, neither player has a weakness, and it is very close to equal. }
7... Bd6 { We want to castle as quickly as possible. } 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Qh5
{ This isn't as dangerous as it looks. } 9... g6 10. Nxg6
{ White would actually lose on the spot with this. } 10... hxg6
{ The safest capture, not even allowing  10...fxg6  11.Qxd5+  . } 11. Bxg6 Qe8+
{ Protecting g6 indirectly with check. } *

