1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3
{ I think this move is slightly underappreciated. It is a safe line where White doesn't overextend with pawn advances, and there are even interesting new ways to keep things fresh and complicated. For example, with  3...e6  4.Ne4  . I expect to see more 3.Nc3 in the future. }
3... e6
{ A very sound reaction. We protect our knight and develop at the same time.  3...Nxc3!?  4.dxc3  d6  and now  5.Nf3!?  is good - Black will hesitate to exchange on e5. However, after  5.exd6  exd6  6.Nf3  we have transposed to a5.Nc3 Petroff.As I mentioned, I like to keep the repertoire original and not let it transpose to other openings unless there is a good reason to. This line is one of the main lines in the Petroff. Therefore, I'm not recommending this in our repertoire, although it should be perfectly fine for Black.   3...Nb6?!  is not the best, but certainly is in the spirit of the Alekhine. We keep the knight on the board and try to break in the centre with ...d6, as usual. }
4. Ne4
{ An idea my engine came up with. By placing the knight behind the e5-pawn, White ensures that d4 comes without crippling White's pawn structure, as Black can no longer exchange on c3. This idea is more dangerous than it looks - White tries to cramp Black's position.However, this move has rarely been played, with a total of 28 games in my database. Yet, I expect its popularity to grow in the future. It seems a safe option for White to play for an advantage. }
4... d6 5. d4
{ White's idea, trying to keep the pawn on  e5  and with it, a space advantage.  5.exd6!?  Bxd6  6.Nf3  O-O  7.d4  b6  transposes tothe mainline after 4.Nf3. }
5... dxe5 6. dxe5 Nc6 7. Nf3
{ Black can really get in trouble here if not careful. Therefore, a novelty is already in order. }
7... Nb6
{ A new idea which needs some testing. It looks a bit of an awkward move to play, but it does give us some room to breathe.  7...Ndb4?  here is a line to illustrate how quickly things can go wrong for Black.  8.Qe2!  b6  9.a3  Nd5  10.g3  Bb7  11.Bg2  h6  12.O-O  Qc8  13.Rd1±  with a magnificent position for White in the game Zumsande,M @@StartBracket@@2423@@EndBracket@@-Jarvenpaa,J @@StartBracket@@2247@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2015. Notice how we cannot develop our dark-squared bishop due to White's continuous threat of c4. }
8. Bd2 Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qd5 { Black has won a pawn. } 10. Bd3 Qxe5 11. O-O Bd7
{ White has good compensation for the pawn, but has yet to find active ideas. }
