{ My recommendation. I think it's a good idea to prioritise development over the bishop pair.  6...Be7  7.d4  very much resembles a Rubinstein French @@StartBracket@@seethe informational at the beginning of the chapter for comparison@@EndBracket@@, with the difference that we have gained a tempo or two with our knight on d5. The knight on d5 isn't a big advantage, though, as it can be easily kicked away with c4, and it isn't posing White many problems. For example,  7...O-O  Now the principled approach for White is to develop first before taking action in the centre:  8.c4?!  Nf6!  9.Nxf6+  Bxf6  10.Be2  Nc6  11.Be3  e5!  and Black's counterplay is very quick.Therefore, better is  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4p3/3n4/3PN3/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bd3  Nd7  My engine suggests a few other creative solutions to counter White's slight space advantage.   @@StartBracket@@For example, by playing  8...Nb4!?  or  8...f5  and ...c5.@@EndBracket@@  Yet, these feel very engine-like, and after 8 moves, we still have problems to solve. I like this move best.  9.O-O  b6  10.Qe2  Bb7  11.Rd1  This position was reached @@StartBracket@@ironically@@EndBracket@@ by the man himself over a hundred years ago: Alekhine, A-Tartakower,S Budapest 1921.  11...Qc8  12.c4  N5f6  13.Bf4  Re8⩲  and White has a small advantage due to the extra space.   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppnbppp/4p3/3n4/3PN3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...c5!?  is an interesting attempt, yet the position remains a tad better for White.  10.dxc5  Nxc5  11.Nxc5  Bxc5  12.Qe2  Qc7  13.Qe4⩲  Provoking a weakening of the Black kingside. Maybe French players would be happy to play this position. As a 1...e5 and Alekhine Player, I wouldn't be too happy here. }
7. d4 b6 8. Bd3 { White tries to prevent simplifications. } 8... Bb7 9. O-O Nf4
{ This move secures us the trade of a pair of minor pieces. If instead  9...Nd7?!  10.c4  Ne7  11.Nxd6  cxd6±  White has the bishop pair and a clear space advantage. }
10. Bxf4 { 10.Nxd6  Qxd6=  see7. Nxd6. } 10... Bxf4 11. Qe2 Nd7
{ Black is still a bit cramped, yet with the exchange of one pair of minor pieces, I'd much rather play this than the @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/3bp3/3n4/4N3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  line.The bishop pair can become an asset in the late game if White opens up the position. We should keep our pawn structure solid, prevent White from exchanging our light-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@by playing ...a5, for example, to prevent White's Ba6@@EndBracket@@, to put our rooks towards the centre, and perhaps even break with a timely ...e5 or ...c5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.1) Anti-Alekhine 2.Nc3 - 3.exd5 Nxd5 4.Bc4"]
[Black "Anti-Alekhine - Nimzo Sicilian & Scandinavian move orders"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The Scandinavian move order that transposes to our main line appears after  1...d5  2.exd5  Nf6  3.Nc3?!   @@StartBracket@@  3.Nf3  ,  3.d4  and  3.Bb5  are considered critical.@@EndBracket@@  3...Nxd5  and we reachthe main line of this chapter. }
2. Nf3 Nf6 { The start of the Nimzowitsch variation. } 3. Nc3
{ 3.e5  is the main move in current theory. } 3... d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bc4
{ Harmless compared to  5.Bb5  , by far the main line. White tries to disrupt Black's development. }
5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 e6 7. O-O Bd6 8. d4
{ And after  8...Nd7  we have transposed tothis line in the 4.Bc4 system in this chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.1) Anti-Alekhine 2.Nc3 - 3.exd5 Nxd5 4.Bc4"]
[Black "Anti-Alekhine - 4...e6 5.Qf3!? #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ White decides not to delve into the deeps of the Alekhine waters and instead chooses the calmer and safer  2.Nc3  . Black has many good options here. }
2... d5
{ The only line with independent value. I like playing  2...e5  because I have a lot of experience in 1.e4 e5  from the black side. The most dangerous lines occur after 2.Nf3. With this move order, we have avoided them.  3.Nf3  Nc6  The Four Knights Opening and no problem for Black according to current theory.  3...d6!?  was my choice if I wanted a complicated game. We usually transpose to the Black Lion, on which Simon Williams, a.k.a. GingerGM, has published an excellent course here on Chessable.  4.d4  Nbd7  transposes to the Black Lion. }
3. exd5
{ This transposes to a @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  Scandinavian where White played the non-critical  3.Nc3  .   We will cover  3.e5  ina future chapter.  whereas  3.d3?!  is very passive and allows us to choose between an equal ending or an aggressive try to grab as much space as possible.  3...Nc6!⩱  followed by ...e5 and I prefer Black already while  3...dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  e5=  is about equal. }
3... Nxd5 4. Bc4
{ 4.d4!?  Bf5  This move nicely follows our current repertoire. We have the c2-pawn as a target. Now  5.Nf3  Nb4  takes ushere and  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/8/3n1b2/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bc4  e6  6.Nf3  is covered via4.Nf3 Bf5 5.Bc4.   4.Nxd5?!  Qxd5  gives us a nicely centralised queen and  5.Nf3  Bg4!  is now an extra option compared to4.Nf3 Bf5 5.d4. We have very easy development with ...e5 and ...Nc6. }
4... e6
{ I like this move better than the alternatives. The bishop is a bit misplaced on c4 now, staring at what I sometimes call a brick wall, as the pawns on e6 and f7 are blunting it. From here on, the main idea is to exchange on c3 and then develop normally with ...b6-...Bb7-...Bd6 and ...O-O.   I haven't spent too much time on  4...Nxc3!?  , yet it also seems like a reasonable alternative.  5.Qf3  e6  6.dxc3  with an interesting position where White is going to develop quickly while trying to hinder Black's development.   4...c6!?  is a very decent alternative, played by Anish Giri, among others. White has two options:A@@EndBracket@@  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.h3  Bh5  7.d4  e6  8.g4!?   @@StartBracket@@  8.O-O  Be7  poses zero problems - Black can exchange on c3 and try to break with ...c5 at the right moment. If White prevents that, we can grab space with ...b5.@@EndBracket@@  8...Bg6  9.h4Ν  and White has some initiative. Still, I suspect Black is fine.B@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p5/3n4/2B5/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qf3  is an interesting alternative to try and force Black to play ...e6.  5...Nf6!  Yet this move gives decent play. We want to play ...Bg4, or ...e6-...c5 if prevented, and develop normally. After both  6.h3  a6!?Ν  followed by ...e6 and ...c5, and in some cases immediately ...b5 and ...Bb7, or  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/8/2B5/2N2Q2/PPPP1PPP/R1B1K1NR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nge2  Bg4  7.Qg3  e6  , Black can develop naturally. }
5. Qf3
{ Putting pressure on the knight. Instead, after  5.Nxd5?!  exd5  6.Bb3  c6  7.d4  Bd6⩱  Black has the better bishop. }
5... Ne7
{ I always like it when I can recommend a novelty as early as move 5. My engine suggested this move, and I found it very sensible. The one big weakness of White's play is that the queen is on f3. The point of this knight move is to make optimal use of that queen by regrouping to d4 and targeting it. There are some decent alternatives, though. Here is a small summary for you.   5...Nb4!?  is certainly good too.  6.Bb3  N8c6  7.Nge2  Na5  Threatening to take on b3 and then ...Nc2.  8.Ba4+!  Bd7  9.a3  Nd5  and now for example  10.Bxd7+  Qxd7  11.O-O  Nc6=  and Black has no problems, or  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppb1ppp/4p3/n2n4/B7/P1N2Q2/1PPPNPPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nxd5  Bxa4  11.Ne3  Bc6  12.Qh5  b6  and Black had a very healthy position in the game Simagin,V-Bagirov,V Moscow 1968.   5...Nb6  is also perfectly fine and probably the move I would otherwise recommend.  6.Bb3  Be7  7.Nge2  and now  7...Nc6  has been frequently played, but I think it's better to play  7...c5!  first, stopping d4.  8.d3  O-O  9.O-O  Nc6=  and Black can play ...Bd7-...Rc8 and ...Nd4, trying to open up the c-file and target the c2-pawn. }
6. Qe2 Nf5 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. O-O Be7 9. d3
{ White has played arguably the most natural moves possible. } 9... Nfd4 10.
Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qd1 a6
{ This is basically the ideal scenario of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3n4/2B5/2N2Q2/PPPP1PPP/R1B1K1NR b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ne7  . We are preparing ...b5 and ...Bb7, after which Black's pieces look better than White's, especially if you compare light-squared bishops.   A sample continuation is  12.a4  b6  13.Ba2  Bb7  . }
*

