{ I like this move better than the alternatives. The bishop is a bit misplaced on c4 now, staring at what I sometimes call a brick wall, as the pawns on e6 and f7 are blunting it. From here on, the main idea is to exchange on c3 and then develop normally with ...b6-...Bb7-...Bd6 and ...O-O.   I haven't spent too much time on  4...Nxc3!?  , yet it also seems like a reasonable alternative.  5.Qf3  e6  6.dxc3  with an interesting position where White is going to develop quickly while trying to hinder Black's development.   4...c6!?  is a very decent alternative, played by Anish Giri, among others. White has two options:A@@EndBracket@@  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.h3  Bh5  7.d4  e6  8.g4!?   @@StartBracket@@  8.O-O  Be7  poses zero problems - Black can exchange on c3 and try to break with ...c5 at the right moment. If White prevents that, we can grab space with ...b5.@@EndBracket@@  8...Bg6  9.h4Ν  and White has some initiative. Still, I suspect Black is fine.B@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p5/3n4/2B5/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qf3  is an interesting alternative to try and force Black to play ...e6.  5...Nf6!  Yet this move gives decent play. We want to play ...Bg4, or ...e6-...c5 if prevented, and develop normally. After both  6.h3  a6!?Ν  followed by ...e6 and ...c5, and in some cases immediately ...b5 and ...Bb7, or  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/8/2B5/2N2Q2/PPPP1PPP/R1B1K1NR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nge2  Bg4  7.Qg3  e6  , Black can develop naturally. }
5. Nf3 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Nd7
{ I like how straightforward Black's play is here. We develop with ...b6-...Bb7-...Bd6-...O-O and then think of a way to undermine White's centre.   6...c5!?  is also a good option.  7.O-O  and we have funnily transposed to a position which could come from the Nimzo Sicilian. Seethe informational at the beginning of the chapter. }
7. O-O { Or  7.d4!?  Bd6  8.O-O  . } 7... Bd6
{ My preferred move here. After  7...b6!?  8.d4  Bb7  9.Re1  Be7  10.d5!  , the fact that we haven't castled yet is showing its downside.   7...Be7  is certainly a viable option as well.  8.d4  O-O  9.Re1  b6=  is very comfortable for Black after ...Bb7. White could pose problems with  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppnbppp/4p3/8/2BP4/2P2N2/P1P2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Qe2  b6  10.Qe4!  Rb8  11.Bd3  g6  where we should be fine, yet I don’t particularly appreciate weakening the kingside if there is no need for it. Therefore, I prefer  11...Nf6  12.Qh4  Bb7  13.Bg5  when  13...g6?  14.Ne5±  offers White good attacking prospects.Our only move is  @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/pbp1bppp/1p2pn2/6B1/3P3Q/2PB1N2/P1P2PPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...h6  and now White has a chance to force a draw. I put this position on my board at home and decided there was some risk here.  14.Bxh6!  this piece sac requires some precision from our side.  14...gxh6  and now if  15.Qxh6??  Qd5  followed by ...Qh5 and White's initiative is gone, but  @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/pbp1bp2/1p2pn1p/8/3P3Q/2PB1N2/P1P2PPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Ne5!  Kg7  16.Qg3+  Kh8  17.Qf4  Kg7  and White forces a draw with  18.Qg3+  while  18.Rae1?  loses to  18...Rh8-+  and Black is safe with a piece up. }
8. d4 O-O 9. Bg5
{ This looks a bit scary, but we have a good way to counter it. } 9... Be7 10.
Bf4 b6 11. d5
{ A bit of a double-edged move. White weakens the doubled c-pawns in exchange for a temporary initiative. }
11... Nc5 12. Re1 Bb7 13. dxe6 Nxe6
{ And the position is about equal. White shouldn't take on e6, which opens up the f-file for our rook to target White's bishop on f4. }
