1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ White decides not to delve into the deeps of the Alekhine waters and instead chooses the calmer and safer  2.Nc3  . Black has many good options here. }
2... d5
{ The only line with independent value. I like playing  2...e5  because I have a lot of experience in 1.e4 e5  from the black side. The most dangerous lines occur after 2.Nf3. With this move order, we have avoided them.  3.Nf3  Nc6  The Four Knights Opening and no problem for Black according to current theory.  3...d6!?  was my choice if I wanted a complicated game. We usually transpose to the Black Lion, on which Simon Williams, a.k.a. GingerGM, has published an excellent course here on Chessable.  4.d4  Nbd7  transposes to the Black Lion. }
3. exd5
{ This transposes to a @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3P4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  Scandinavian where White played the non-critical  3.Nc3  .   We will cover  3.e5  ina future chapter.  whereas  3.d3?!  is very passive and allows us to choose between an equal ending or an aggressive try to grab as much space as possible.  3...Nc6!⩱  followed by ...e5 and I prefer Black already while  3...dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  e5=  is about equal. }
3... Nxd5 4. Bc4
{ 4.d4!?  Bf5  This move nicely follows our current repertoire. We have the c2-pawn as a target. Now  5.Nf3  Nb4  takes ushere and  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/8/3n1b2/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bc4  e6  6.Nf3  is covered via4.Nf3 Bf5 5.Bc4.   4.Nxd5?!  Qxd5  gives us a nicely centralised queen and  5.Nf3  Bg4!  is now an extra option compared to4.Nf3 Bf5 5.d4. We have very easy development with ...e5 and ...Nc6. }
4... Nb6
{ This is a very decent alternative and my recommendation in my GingerGM course on the Alekhine. }
5. Bb3 Nc6
{ 5...c5!?  is a favourite of Alekhine expert Oleksandr Bortnyk, though I checked his game history, and in his most recent game, he played the text.  6.d3  Nc6  7.Nf3  Bf5  8.O-O  e6  seems perfectly fine for Black. Instead,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/1nn5/2p5/8/1BNP4/PPP2PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qh5!?  e6  8.Bg5  leads to complications and is the reason why I'm not 100% comfortable recommending this line. }
6. Nf3 Bf5
{ 6...Bg4??  falls into the trap  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Ng5++-  and White wins back the piece with a dominant position. }
7. O-O e6 8. d4
{ 8.d3  Na5=  grabs the bishop-pair. We can then develop normally with ...Be7 and ...O-O without problems. }
8... Be7 { 8...Na5=  is very decent too, and should transpose. } 9. Qe2 O-O
{ The simplest. We don't need to allow complications after  9...Na5  10.Qb5+  Nc6  11.Ne5  .   Also, there's no need to go  9...Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qxd4  11.Nb5  Qd7  12.Bf4  . After the text, White has to defend the d4-pawn and we can go after the b3-bishop. }
10. Rd1 Na5 { Before White has time to secure the a2-square for the bishop. }
11. h3 Re8 12. Bf4
{ 12.Ne5  would probably have been better, making sure Black could not exchange more pieces.  12...Nxb3  13.axb3  h6  14.Ne4⇆  with chances for both sides. Black has the bishop pair, yet White's more active pieces and space compensate for that. }
12... Nxb3 13. axb3
{ Ironically, we have been following a game of the expert himself from the White side: Bortnyk,O @@StartBracket@@2604@@EndBracket@@-Jacobson,A @@StartBracket@@2263@@EndBracket@@ Chess. com INT 2022. }
13... Nd5 14. Bg3
{ 14.Nxd5  exd5⩱  and Black is a bit better thanks to the bishop pair. } 14...
a5
{ And Black has absolutely no problems. I dare say I prefer Black already in this position due to the long-term advantage of the bishop pair. }
*

