1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. exd5
{ In chapters9.3 and9.4,  we will discuss  3.e5  . } 3... Nxd5 4. Qf3
{ Trying to force Black to exchange on c3. } 4... Nf6
{ I like this move very much. We can develop with ...Bg4 after we sidestep the threat of Qxb7. }
5. Bb5+
{ Very cleverly trying to prevent ...Nc6.  5.Bc4?!  Nc6  6.Bb5  White has hardly a better option.  6...Bd7  7.Nge2  e5  Black has more space and sounder development. Next are ...Bd6 and ...a6.   White's best is probably  5.h3  , just waiting for Black to play ...Nc6 to pin this knight with Bb5, thus preventing an eventual ...Bg4.  5...a6⩱  In turn, we prevent White's Bb5. Now there are no obstacles for our knight to jump to c6. I already prefer Black - the White queen is still awkwardly placed on f3. }
5... c6 6. Bc4
{ We have won a tempo compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/8/3n4/8/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bc4  c6  @@StartBracket@@see ouralternatives on move 4 in the previous chapter@@EndBracket@@  5.Qf3  Nf6  . }
6... Bg4 7. Qg3 e6 8. d3 Bf5
{ Preventing Bf4, which we would meet now by ...Nh5 winning the bishop pair. }
9. Nge2 Bd6 10. Qxg7
{ 10.Bf4?  Nh5  and, at the very least, we win the bishop pair. } 10... Rg8 11.
Qh6 Rxg2 { White has to be very careful here. } *

