[White "9.2) Anti-Alekhine 2.Nc3 - 3.exd5 Nxd5 4.Nf3"]
[Black "Anti-Alekhine - 4.Nf3 alternatives to 4...Bf5!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. exd5
{ In chapters9.3 and9.4,  we will discuss  3.e5  . } 3... Nxd5 4. Nf3
{ With this move, White postpones the development of the f1-bishop. Quite a few top players have played it. The positions get quite complicated, with many tactical variations that need to be run through until the end. I thought this move was quite interesting, and I might have overdone it a bit with the analysis.   4.d4!?  Bf5  This move nicely follows our current repertoire. We have the c2-pawn as a target. Now  5.Nf3  Nb4  takes ushere and  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/8/3n1b2/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bc4  e6  6.Nf3  is covered via4.Nf3 Bf5 5.Bc4.   4.Nxd5?!  Qxd5  gives us a nicely centralised queen and  5.Nf3  Bg4!  is now an extra option compared to4.Nf3 Bf5 5.d4. We have very easy development with ...e5 and ...Nc6. }
4... Bg4
{ The most played move in this position. Black pins the knight on f3, will follow up with ...e6, and develop naturally afterwards. White's most played moves here are  5.Be2  and  5.Bc4  . Yet, the most dangerous line, in my opinion, is when White doesn't develop the bishop yet.   4...Nxc3!?  5.bxc3  g6  This line was the topic of an online blitz match in 2021 between Rauf Mamedov, a top Azerbaijani player, and the Alekhine expert Oleksandr Bortnyk.  6.h4!  A new move introduced in that match, where the inclusion of h5 and ...g5 with  6...h6?!  7.h5  g5  benefitted White - in the three games that Bortnyk and Mamedov played, White scored 3 out of 3. Better is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/6p1/8/7P/2P2N2/P1PP1PP1/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...h5  7.d4  Bg7  8.Be2  c5!  9.O-O  O-O⇆  with an interesting position that occurred twice in the match. Bortnyk won a game from this position, while Mamedov also won one. Mamedov,R @@StartBracket@@2673@@EndBracket@@-Bortnyk,O @@StartBracket@@2604@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2021.   I wish I could have recommended  4...e6!?  as it's quite nicely in line with my recommendation against4.Bc4. Unfortunately, without the white bishop on c4, this is not as good as other moves.  5.d4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  Nd7  7.Bd3  and White has gained a valuable tempo compared toour 4.Bc4 e6 variation.   4...g6!?  was played by Ivanchuk and Carlsen almost a decade ago. It is certainly a decent option, especially if you have experience in the Grünfeld against 1.d4. For example,  5.Bc4  Nxc3  6.bxc3  Bg7  7.O-O  O-O  8.Re1  c5  and Black was doing fine in the game Artemiev,V @@StartBracket@@2709@@EndBracket@@-Bortnyk,O @@StartBracket@@2598@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2021@@EndBracket@@ or  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/6p1/3n4/8/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nxd5  Qxd5  6.d4  Bg7  7.Be2  O-O  8.O-O  c5  We have been following the game between two top Russian Grandmasters: Predke,A @@StartBracket@@2676@@EndBracket@@-Ponkratov,P @@StartBracket@@2632@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2019.  9.c4!?  Qd6  10.Be3⩲  and Black has some problems as the queenside isn't developed yet. }
5. d4 { Once again, White postpones developing the bishop.  5.Bc4?!  e6  . }
5... e6
{ 5...Nxc3?!  6.bxc3  e6  7.Rb1!  b6  8.h3  Bf5  9.g3!  One of the points of not developing the bishop on f1 yet. By provoking ...b6, the bishop looks magnificent on g2, where it covers the whole h1-a8-diagonal. }
6. h3 { Played only three times. } 6... Bh5
{ 6...Bxf3?!  7.Qxf3⩲  and White has more space and the bishop pair. } 7. g4
Bg6 8. Bg2
{ This position occurred in a game in 2019 between two young talents. } 8...
Nb4
{ Black was a bit over-enthusiastic here in the game: Liang,A @@StartBracket@@2589@@EndBracket@@-Ashwin, J @@StartBracket@@2500@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2019.   8...Nc6  would have been better, yet the position is quite dangerous for Black and requires some accurate moves.   8...Nd7  9.O-O  Be7  10.Ne2!?  intending c4 or  10.Nxd5  exd5  11.Ne5!⩲  and White has the initiative. }
9. Ne5 { Black cannot take the c2-pawn. } 9... Nxc2+
{ 9...c6  10.Nxg6  hxg6±  and Black's 8th move has backfired. White once again has the bishop pair and more space. }
10. Kf1 Nxa1 11. Bxb7 { White wins back the material with interest. } *

