{ With this move, White postpones the development of the f1-bishop. Quite a few top players have played it. The positions get quite complicated, with many tactical variations that need to be run through until the end. I thought this move was quite interesting, and I might have overdone it a bit with the analysis.   4.d4!?  Bf5  This move nicely follows our current repertoire. We have the c2-pawn as a target. Now  5.Nf3  Nb4  takes ushere and  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/8/3n1b2/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bc4  e6  6.Nf3  is covered via4.Nf3 Bf5 5.Bc4.   4.Nxd5?!  Qxd5  gives us a nicely centralised queen and  5.Nf3  Bg4!  is now an extra option compared to4.Nf3 Bf5 5.d4. We have very easy development with ...e5 and ...Nc6. }
4... Bf5
{ After some deliberation, I decided to recommend this move. It leads to fresh positions with room for novelties. I have also included the other options inthis informational if you want to have a look. }
5. d4 Nb4
{ Rarely played, and the reason why I recommend 4...Bf5. This move appears in 20 games in my database.  5...e6  is a solid alternative.  6.Nxd5  exd5?!  7.Bd3  Bxd3  8.Qxd3±  is good for White. Instead, after  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4p3/3N1b2/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qxd5  7.Be2  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Be3⩲  and I think White has a small stable space advantage, yet this position is very acceptable. Black can put a rook on d8 and start playing for ...c5. }
6. Bb5+ { The only way to protect c2. } 6... c6 7. Ba4 e6 8. O-O Be7
{ Generally, White should try to play Ne4 and c3 as soon as possible, as the bishop isn't very well placed on a4 at the moment. }
9. Qe2
{ 9.a3  Nd5  10.Nxd5  exd5=  is, once again, not an issue as long as we contest the e-file. For example:  11.Re1  O-O  12.Bf4  Nd7  13.c3  Re8  14.Bc2  Bxc2  15.Qxc2  a5  16.a4  Nf6=  with an equal position. }
9... a5
{ Forcing White to play a3 seems like a good idea.  9...O-O  10.Ne4!  b5  11.Bb3  followed by c3 creating a square for the white bishop on c2, which is better than a2. }
10. a3 O-O 11. Ne4 { This is safer. } 11... b5 12. Bb3 Nd5
{ Followed by ...Qc7 and ...Nd7, after which I think we have roughly equalised. }
*

