{ With this move, White postpones the development of the f1-bishop. Quite a few top players have played it. The positions get quite complicated, with many tactical variations that need to be run through until the end. I thought this move was quite interesting, and I might have overdone it a bit with the analysis.   4.d4!?  Bf5  This move nicely follows our current repertoire. We have the c2-pawn as a target. Now  5.Nf3  Nb4  takes ushere and  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/8/3n1b2/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bc4  e6  6.Nf3  is covered via4.Nf3 Bf5 5.Bc4.   4.Nxd5?!  Qxd5  gives us a nicely centralised queen and  5.Nf3  Bg4!  is now an extra option compared to4.Nf3 Bf5 5.d4. We have very easy development with ...e5 and ...Nc6. }
4... Bf5
{ After some deliberation, I decided to recommend this move. It leads to fresh positions with room for novelties. I have also included the other options inthis informational if you want to have a look. }
5. Nxd5
{ Taking on d5 helps Black speed up development, as we are going to castle long. However, White intends to exploit the queen on d5 with timely d4 and c4 pushes to gain space. At first, it struck me as a bad move, but looking closely at the lines, it seems quite dangerous, with many complicated lines. }
5... Qxd5 6. d4 Nc6
{ After  6...Qe4+!?  7.Be3  Qxc2  8.Qxc2  Bxc2  9.Rc1  Be4  10.Rxc7↑  White gets a lead in development for the pawn.   6...e6  is a solid alternative, yet I do feel this offers White a slight advantage.  7.Be2  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  and White is a bit better. This transposes to5.d4 e6 6.Nxd5. }
7. c4 Qe4+ 8. Be2 O-O-O 9. d5 { Saving the pawn by pushing it forward. } 9...
Ne5
{ A decent alternative and perfectly fine as well, butmy recommendation will be  9...e6!  . }
10. O-O Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 Qxc4 12. Be3
{ White has enough compensation for the pawn. If Black is not careful, White will generate enormous initiative against our king. }
12... Be4
{ Therefore, this move is practically forced. Now a simplifying sequence will most likely occur. }
13. Rc1 Bxf3 14. Rxc4
{ 14.Qxf3?!  Qxd5  15.Qe2  e6=∞  White is now two pawns down with still enough compensation, though. }
14... Bxd1 15. Rxd1 e6 16. Rdc1 Bd6 17. dxe6 b6
{ If  17...fxe6  18.Bxa7  White has a slightly better pawn structure. } 18.
exf7 Rhf8 { Black wins back the pawn with a completely equal endgame. } *

