[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.3) Anti-Alekhine 2.Nc3 - 3.e5 d4 4.exf6"]
[Black "Anti-Alekhine - 4.exf6 dxc3 5.fxe7?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e5
{ After examining  3.exd5  , we are left with this move. Personally, this is the reason why I prefer to meet  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  with  2...e5  . }
3... d4
{ Basically, the only move that creates an original repertoire for Black.  3...Nfd7  4.f4  most likely transposes to a Steinitz French:  4...e6  5.d4  c5  6.Nf3  Nc6  and we have reached the Steinitz Variation of the French Defence. The usual move order to get this position is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.f4  c5  6.Nf3  Nc6  .   After  3...Ne4?!  4.Nce2!  , White will kick the knight away with d3 and get a big centre. }
4. exf6 { This often steers the game into an endgame. } 4... dxc3 5. fxe7
{ After  5.bxc3  exf6  Black is perfectly fine. If you have Erwin l'Ami's Caro-Kann course, I'm sure you'll feel relaxed here as, in comparison, White has a worse pawn structure. Our ideas include putting our bishop on d6 and, if White ever plays d4, to undermine it with ...c5. Black's kingside doubled pawns can still be an asset. They are bad in pawn endings, but not really in the middlegame. }
5... Qxe7+ 6. Be2 cxb2 7. Bxb2 Bg4
{ Followed by ...Nc6/...Nd7 and ...O-O-O, with zero problems for Black. I think we even have a slight edge due to the pawn structure. }
*

