[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e5
{ After examining  3.exd5  , we are left with this move. Personally, this is the reason why I prefer to meet  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  with  2...e5  . }
3... d4
{ Basically, the only move that creates an original repertoire for Black.  3...Nfd7  4.f4  most likely transposes to a Steinitz French:  4...e6  5.d4  c5  6.Nf3  Nc6  and we have reached the Steinitz Variation of the French Defence. The usual move order to get this position is  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.f4  c5  6.Nf3  Nc6  .   After  3...Ne4?!  4.Nce2!  , White will kick the knight away with d3 and get a big centre. }
4. exf6 { This often steers the game into an endgame. } 4... dxc3 5. fxg7 cxd2+
{ If we recapture on g7, we lose a pawn, so this intermezzo is necessary. } 6.
Qxd2
{ I think this is White's best approach. The endgame is always a bit better for White. }
6... Qxd2+ { 6...Bxg7!?  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  8.Nf3⩲  is similar to our main line. }
7. Bxd2 Bxg7 8. O-O-O
{ White definitely has a small plus here. Their pawn structure is better, and White enjoys a slight lead in development. Yet, if we play normal moves and prevent any initiative, Black should be fine. }
8... Nc6 9. Ne2
{ Intending to place a knight on f4 or to exchange the dark-squared bishops. }
9... Bd7
{ The best place for the bishop at this point. On f5, g4 and e6, it will simply get kicked by the white knight. }
10. Nf4
{ 10.Bc3  Rg8  The bishop trade is not bad for Black - we can let it happen. }
10... O-O-O 11. Nh5
{ This occurred in the game: Popchev,M @@StartBracket@@2316@@EndBracket@@ -Mikicic,D @@StartBracket@@2146@@EndBracket@@ Belgrade 2017.   White still keeps a slight plus after  11.Be2  . }
11... Bxb2+ { 11...Be5  would have been no problem for Black either. } 12. Kxb2
Bg4
{ Black would have won a pawn thanks to the double attack on the d1-rook and the h5-knight. }
