[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.4) Anti-Alekhine 2.Nc3 - 3.e5 d4 4.Nce2"]
[Black "Anti-Alekhine - 5.Nf3?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e5 d4 4. Nce2
{ A funny line where White does take many risks. Ideally, White wants to play Ng3/Nf4 and Bc4, followed by some smooth development. An excellent strategy for Black is to challenge that setup.   Our previouschapter covered  4.exf6  and  4.Nb1?!  Nd5⩱  gives Black an edge @@StartBracket@@the position of the knights speaks for itself@@EndBracket@@.   Finally,  4.Nb5?!  Ng4  5.f4  Nc6  and the white knight is misplaced on b5. We have an easy play with ...e6 and ...a6, while our knight can be re-routed to f5 via h6. }
4... Ng4
{ My recommendation after some consideration. We attack  e5  and force White to react. Notice  4...Nd5  isn't possible as our d4-pawn is attacked.   I'd like to avoid the pawn sacrifice  4...Nfd7  5.e6!  as much as possible. }
5. Nf3 { I faced this move in a recent blitz game. } 5... Nc6 6. h3
{ This helps us play a move we already wanted to play. } 6... Ngxe5 7. Nexd4
{ A small tactic to win back the pawn. } 7... Qd5
{ A nice move in return. We are threatening to win the knight, forcing White to make a decision. }
8. Nxe5 Qxe5+
{ And White has to play the awkward  9.Ne2  to avoid loing a piece. } *

