{ A fantastic move as well. Note that after  7...Bxe6?  8.f5!  we lose a piece. }
8. Nxf5 Bxe6 9. Qxg4 Qd5
{ Threatening to win the piece back by capturing White's knight on f5. Notice how Bd3 can be countered by ...Nb4. }
10. Qh5+ Bf7 11. Qxg5
{ Or  11.Qh3  Be6  12.Qh5+  Bf7=  and we have a perpetual. } 11... Rg8
{ We win back the piece. } 12. Ng7+
{ If  12.Qh4?  Qxf5  White is in deep trouble. We are threatening the c2-pawn, and ...Nb4 is a strong idea. }
12... Rxg7 13. Qxd5 Bxd5
{ With fantastic compensation for the pawn. We have very active pieces while literally all of White's are still on the back-rank. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.4) Anti-Alekhine 2.Nc3 - 3.e5 d4 4.Nce2"]
[Black "Anti-Alekhine - 5.f4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e5 d4 4. Nce2
{ A funny line where White does take many risks. Ideally, White wants to play Ng3/Nf4 and Bc4, followed by some smooth development. An excellent strategy for Black is to challenge that setup.   Our previouschapter covered  4.exf6  and  4.Nb1?!  Nd5⩱  gives Black an edge @@StartBracket@@the position of the knights speaks for itself@@EndBracket@@.   Finally,  4.Nb5?!  Ng4  5.f4  Nc6  and the white knight is misplaced on b5. We have an easy play with ...e6 and ...a6, while our knight can be re-routed to f5 via h6. }
4... Ng4
{ My recommendation after some consideration. We attack  e5  and force White to react. Notice  4...Nd5  isn't possible as our d4-pawn is attacked.   I'd like to avoid the pawn sacrifice  4...Nfd7  5.e6!  as much as possible. }
5. f4 Nc6
{ This is not so frequent in practice, but it strikes me as the most challenging. We quickly enter novelty-area after this move.  5...h5!?  is the main move and a decent alternative, securing a future outpost on f5 for our knight. I am not recommending this because White has no trouble getting their desired setup:  6.Nf3  Nc6  7.h3  Nh6  8.Ng3  followed by Bc4/Bb5 and White has fewer problems than after 5...Nc6, in my opinion. }
6. Ng3 { An attempt to get the bishop out asap. } 6... g5
{ Undermining the centre and paving the way to develop our dark-squared bishop on g7. One simple point is that  7.d3?  fails to  7...gxf4  8.Bxf4  Ncxe5  and Black has won a pawn for free.   6...Qd5!?  is a very decent alternative, denying White's bishop access to c4 or b5. }
7. e6 { The best move, yet very hard to find over the board. } 7... f5
{ A fantastic move as well. Note that after  7...Bxe6?  8.f5!  we lose a piece. }
8. Nxf5 Bxe6 9. Qxg4 Qd5
{ Threatening to win the piece back by capturing White's knight on f5. Notice how Bd3 can be countered by ...Nb4. }
10. Qxg5 Rg8 11. Qh5+ Bf7 12. Qh3 Be6
{ With a perpetual. If White continues, we win back the knight with fantastic compensation thanks to our huge lead in development. For example,  13.Bd3  Nb4  and we still win the piece back as we can trade of the d3-bishop for our knight, or  @@StartFEN@@r3kbr1/ppp1p2p/2n1b3/3q1N2/3p1P2/7Q/PPPP2PP/R1B1KBNR w KQq - 5 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qf3  Qxf5  14.Bd3  Qa5!  15.Bxh7  Rg7  16.Be4  O-O-O=∞  Despite being two pawns down, we have amazing compensation once again. Our ideas include ...Bg4, ...Nb4 and ...d3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.5) Anti-Alekhine - Offbeat 2nd moves"]
[Black "Anti-Alekhine - 2.d3?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. d3 { Another way for White to avoid the Alekhine mainlines. } 2...
e5
{ The best move here. White's choice is a very passive line where Black is simply very much OK, if not outright better. Compared to the Black Lion, colours are reversed, and White is a tempo up. To understand everything, I recommend you take a look at Simon Williams's excellent course on Chessable. Here are a few alternatives to consider:   2...c5!?  is certainly an option if you have a Sicilian repertoire. This should transpose to certain lines there.  2...d5!?  3.e5  Nfd7  4.d4  leads to a position very similar to the Steinitz French, only worse, as White's knight is not on c3 - as strange as it sounds, the knight should be on b1 to enable c2-c3 reinforcing the d4-pawn. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.f4?!  is not good - Black gets excellent play after  3...exf4  4.Bxf4  Nc6  5.Be2  Bc5  or  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/8/4PB2/3P4/PPP3PP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3?!  d5  . For example:  6.e5  Nh5  7.Bc1  f6∓  We have pleasant development and more active pieces. The knight on h5 is currently on the rim, yet we can centralise it soon enough. }
3... Nc6 4. Be2 d5 5. Nbd2
{ 5.exd5  leaves us with central superiority.  5...Nxd5  An easy setup to remember is this: ...Bd6, ...O-O, and try to play in the centre or on the kingside. For example:  6.O-O  Bd6  7.Re1  O-O  8.Bf1  This is a common manoeuvre. The bishop makes room on e1 for the rook. White is playing passively but solidly.  8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Kh8  10.h3  Bh5  Followed by either ...f6 with a solid position or ...f5 with potential attacking chances in the centre or on the kingside. In any case, we can safely claim an advantage here, as we have more control over the board. }
5... Bc5 6. O-O O-O 7. c3 a5
{ To prevent White's b4. Black has a better position and can choose from multiple setups. I like strengthening our centre with ...Re8 and playing a timely ...d4 to take the initiative. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.5) Anti-Alekhine - Offbeat 2nd moves"]
[Black "Anti-Alekhine - 2.Bd3?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. Bd3 { A very weird developing move. } 2... e5
{ With the White bishop on d3, we will have much easier development than White compared to the sounder 1.e4 e5 openings. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.c3?  As a rule of thumb, if White tries to bring the d3-bishop to c2 we push...  3...d5!  and White is already in a lot of trouble. }
3... Nc6 4. O-O Bc5 { The best square for our bishop. } 5. Nc3
{ Again,  5.c3?!  d5!  6.exd5  Qxd5  7.Bc2  e4!  with excellent play. } 5...
O-O
{ And in my opinion, White has no better move than to play  6.Bc4  , after which the position is symmetrical, and it's our turn to move. }
6. Bc4
{ We have transposed to a Four Knights Italian, but with colours reversed. }
6... d6 7. d3 Na5
{ 7...Bg4!?  threatening ...Nd4 is also very strong.  8.h3  Bxf3  9.Qxf3  Nd4  10.Qd1  c6  This has been analyzed to equality with the colours reversed, which is the reason why I prefer the text. We are trying to get the bishop pair. I'll show a sample line of how the game could continue. }
8. Bb3 Nxb3 9. axb3 a5
{ A useful move, making sure that White's b-pawns stay immobile. For example,  10.Be3  Bxe3  11.fxe3  Bd7⩱  with some potential initiative on the queenside with ...b5. We can anticipate White's d4 with ...Re8. I would always pick Black here. }
