[Black "Anti-Alekhine - 2.Qe2?! #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. Qe2 e5
{ Not the only good move, but I like how this adds to other lines in this repertoire. It's fun to notice that in the French opening @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  then  2.Qe2  is a reasonably respected anti-French move, and there  2...e5  is actually a well-known response. Black moves the e-pawn twice, but the reasoning is that 2.Qe2 isn't so helpful, as it hinders the development of the f1-bishop to c4 or b5. Compared to that position, we even have our knight on f6 already. }
3. g3 { A common way to play as White, trying to develop the bishop to g2. }
3... Bc5 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. c3
{ I expect White players to play this move sooner or later. You could compare White's setup with the Black Lion, although it's arguably better to try and go for that system without the white queen on e2. After  5.Nf3  O-O  6.O-O  Re8  7.d3  d5⩱  our play is very similar to our lineagainst 2.d3. If White doesn't play c3 on one of the next moves, we could grab the opportunity to play ...Nd4. As usual, ...a5 is an idea as well. }
5... a5 { To prevent any advance on the queenside. } 6. d3 O-O 7. Nf3 d5
{ The point is that after  8.exd5?!  Qxd5!  we can nicely start targeting White's weak d3-pawn with ...Bf5. }
8. Nbd2 dxe4
{ I wanted to give a simple plan to follow in case you ever encounter this system, although simply  8...Re8  and developing is perfectly fine as well. }
9. Nxe4
{ Again,  9.dxe4?!  b6!  with the treat of ...Ba6 is quite annoying for White.  10.Nc4  Ba6  and the c4-knight will be our prime target from now on, with ideas like ...Qe7-...Qe6 and the regroup of our knight c6-d8-b7-d6, as well as ...a4. }
9... Nxe4 10. Qxe4
{ 10.dxe4?!  b6  intending ...Ba6 is once again very unpleasant for White. }
10... h6 { And the d3-pawn will be our target from now on. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.5) Anti-Alekhine - Offbeat 2nd moves"]
[Black "Anti-Alekhine - 2.Bc4? #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. Bc4
{ Quite a common move. White gives up the e4-pawn, yet wins it back with a spectacular combination. This line is flashy but simply not good for White. }
2... Nxe4 3. Bxf7+
{ White's whole idea. Otherwise, we can simply play ...d5 on the next move and be a full pawn up. }
3... Kxf7 4. Qh5+
{ This wins the piece back for White.  4.Qf3+??  Nf6  and Black is a piece up. }
4... Kg8
{ 4...g6?!  is the move I have always played against this line, but it seems that the text is a lot stronger.  5.Qd5+  e6  6.Qxe4  Bg7⩱  and Black has more development and can grab the centre with ...d5 and ...e5. I was always happy to play this position - because of that, I never gave 4...Kg8 a thought.   Instead,  4...Ke6?  5.Qg4+  and moving our king further towards the centre is strongly not recommended. }
5. Qd5+ e6 6. Qxe4 d5
{ With the Black king safe on g8, we can grab the centre immediately without delay. The queen needs to move back, as  7.Qf4?!  gives us a free development move with  7...Bd6  . }
7. Qe3 { This might be better than  7.Qe2  . } 7... e5
{ I still very much like this move. } 8. Nf3
{ With the queen on e3, this move is better than inthe 7.Qe2 e5 8.Nf3 line. Yet, Black still gets an overwhelming advantage in both cases.   For  8.Qxe5  see7.Qe2 e5 8.Qxe5. We go  8...Nc6  when  9.Qg3  runs into  9...Nd4  .   If  8.d3  Nc6∓  Black has the centre, the bishop pair and more development. }
8... e4 9. Ne5 { Or  9.Nd4?!  c5  10.Nb3  with a cramped position. } 9... Nc6
{ I just want to trade off White's annoying e5-knight as soon as possible.  9...Bd6  10.d4  Nc6  is similar. }
10. d4 { Or  10.Nxc6  bxc6  and ...h5 next. } 10... h5
{ Solving our issues with the h8-rook. Play may continue  11.O-O  h4  12.h3  Nxe5  13.dxe5  Rh5  . }
*

